{"title_page": "Nicola Green", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Nicola Green\n| image         = Nicola Green 4 HR.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Photographic self-portrait\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1972}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = English\n| alma_mater    = [[Edinburgh College of Art]]\n| home_town     = \n| spouse        = {{marriage|[[David Lammy]]|2005}}\n| field         = \n| training      = \n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| awards        = \n| elected       = \n| website       = {{url|nicolagreen.com}}\n| signature     = \n}}\n\n'''Nicola Green''' (born 1972<!--- year only is cited in VIAF--->) is a British [[portrait painter]]. Among her subjects have been the [[Dalai Lama]], [[Barack Obama]], and [[Elle Macpherson]].{{r|ind}}\n\nIn 2005, Green married [[David Lammy]], a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament]]. They have three children.{{r|ind}}<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://archive.voice-online.co.uk/article/labour-mp-and-wife-adopt-baby-girl|title=Labour MP And Wife Adopt Baby Girl|date=17 October 2014|work=The Voice|access-date=9 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nGreen has twice been among the exhibitors for the [[BP Portrait Award]] at the [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]] in London, in 2006 and in 2008.{{r|npg|npg2}} In 2011 a set of seven [[silk-screen print]]s depicting [[Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|Barack Obama's presidential election campaign]] were donated to the [[Library of Congress]]; another set is in the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].{{r|loc}}\n\nIn 2018 ''Encounters'', a series of fifty portraits of religious leaders all with their faces and hands painted out, was shown at the church of [[St. Martin-in-the-Fields]] in [[Trafalgar Square]]. Among those represented were the [[Pope Francis|Pope]], the [[14th Dalai Lama|Dalai Lama]], [[Ali Gomaa]], [[Jonathan Sacks]] and [[Justin Welby]].{{r|ss}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|45em|refs=\n\n<ref name=ind>Adam Jacques (29 December 2013). [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/how-we-met-nicola-green-elle-macpherson-9016738.html How we met: Nicola Green & Elle Macpherson]. London: ''The Independent''.  Accessed March 2018.</ref>\n\n<ref name=loc>[Office of Communications] (28 September 2011). [https://www.loc.gov/item/prn-11-176/ Library Receives Gift of Artwork by Nicola Green] (press-release). Library of Congress. Accessed January 2020.</ref>\n\n<ref name=npg>[https://www.npg.org.uk/whatson/exhibitions/2006/bp-portrait-award-2006/exhibitors.php BP Portrait Award 2006 - Exhibitors]. London: National Portrait Gallery. Accessed March 2018.</ref>\n\n<ref name=npg2>[https://www.npg.org.uk/whatson/exhibitions/2008/bp-portrait-award-2008/exhibitors-bp-portrait-award-2008/ BP Portrait Award 2008 - Exhibitors]. London: National Portrait Gallery. Accessed March 2018.</ref>\n\n<ref name=ss>[s.n.] (17 September 2018). [https://www.shropshirestar.com/entertainment/showbiz/2018/09/17/artist-says-faceless-portraits-of-faith-leaders-is-a-comment-on-celebrity-status/ Artist says faceless portraits of faith leaders is a comment on celebrity status]. ''Shropshire Star''. Accessed January 2020.</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Green, Nicola}}\n[[Category:20th-century British painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century British painters]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Edinburgh College of Art]]\n[[Category:British portrait painters]]\n[[Category:British women painters]]\n[[Category:Spouses of British politicians]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{UK-painter-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name          = Nicola Green\n| image         = Nicola Green 4 HR.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Photographic self-portrait\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth year and age|1972}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = English\n| alma_mater    = [[Edinburgh College of Art]]\n| home_town     = \n| spouse        = {{marriage|[[David Lammy]]|2005}}\n| field         = \n| training      = \n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| awards        = \n| elected       = \n| website       = {{url|nicolagreen.com}}\n| signature     = \n}}\n\n'''Nicola Green''' (born 1972<!--- year only is cited in VIAF--->) is a British [[portrait painter]]. Among her subjects have been the [[Dalai Lama]], [[Barack Obama]], and [[Elle Macpherson]].{{r|ind}}\n\nIn 2005, Green married [[David Lammy]], a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament]]. They have two children.{{r|ind}}\n\nGreen has twice been among the exhibitors for the [[BP Portrait Award]] at the [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]] in London, in 2006 and in 2008.{{r|npg|npg2}} In 2011 a set of seven [[silk-screen print]]s depicting [[Barack Obama 2008 presidential campaign|Barack Obama's presidential election campaign]] were donated to the [[Library of Congress]]; another set is in the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]].{{r|loc}}\n\nIn 2018 ''Encounters'', a series of fifty portraits of religious leaders all with their faces and hands painted out, was shown at the church of [[St. Martin-in-the-Fields]] in [[Trafalgar Square]]. Among those represented were the [[Pope Francis|Pope]], the [[14th Dalai Lama|Dalai Lama]], [[Ali Gomaa]], [[Jonathan Sacks]] and [[Justin Welby]].{{r|ss}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|45em|refs=\n\n<ref name=ind>Adam Jacques (29 December 2013). [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/how-we-met-nicola-green-elle-macpherson-9016738.html How we met: Nicola Green & Elle Macpherson]. London: ''The Independent''.  Accessed March 2018.</ref>\n