onsored by public authorities, has a legal structure and framework, is a weekend event as opposed to week-long, and does not include references to 'Lesbian' and 'Gay' in its title through fear of alienating transgender people.  Moreover, Pride in the early 90s tended to concentrate more on arts, exhibitions, culture, talks, workshops and function evenings, in contrast to the party on the scene/popstar on stage format as seen today.  The events also had a strong political element and aimed to explore and challenge society's attitudes towards sexuality at that time.  To put it into perspective, gay men still faced an unequal [[Ages of consent in Europe|age of consent]], the infamous [[Section 28]] was still in existence, there would be no partnership or adoption rights for same sex couples for at least another decade whilst [[OutRage!]], a UK based LGBT activist group, was just being formed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2551523.stm |title=Timeline: Gay fight for equal rights |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=2012-05-28 |date=6 December 2002}}</ref>  Highlights of the festivals included discussions on women in the church, [[LGBT parenting]] and [[Gay literature|literature]], support for gay and lesbian victims of sexual abuse and health awareness workshops.  T-shirts and badges bearing the Pride logos were sold in local gay venues and at events themselves to help cover running costs (see brochure of events below).\n\nThe celebration took a brief break but returned in 1995 under the new name 'Mersey Pride', an attempt to create a more outdoor cabaret and stage type atmosphere around Pownall Square, chosen for its close proximity to The Brunswick and Time Out, two popular gay frequented pubs of the day.  The occasion was modestly successful as a political statement and was attended by some 1200 revellers from across North West England, albeit attracting noticeable protests from the [[Christian right]].<ref>http://www.qrd.org/qrd/world/europe/uk/scotland/pulse/37-09.95</ref>\n\nIn many ways, Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride of the early 90s paved the way for [[Homotopia Liverpool (festival)|Homotopia]], the city's modern day gay arts festival launched some 12 years later, in the sense that Homotopia took on a similar formula.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/liverpool/hi/people_and_places/history/newsid_8730000/8730769.stm |title=Liverpool's journey to Gay Pride |publisher=BBC Liverpool |accessdate=2012-05-24 |date=11 June 2010}}</ref>  The Mersey Pride of 1995, however, bore a stronger resemblance to the present day festivities at the Pier Head and Gay Quarter in spite of being significantly smaller and much less mainstream.\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1990 Brochure.gif|Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride Brochure 1990\nImage:Liverpool goes to London Pride 1990.jpg|Liverpool goes to London Pride 1990\nImage:Tea Dance Ticket.jpg|Tea Dance Ticket from Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1990\nImage:Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1991 Brochure.gif|Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride Brochure 1991\nImage:Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride Poster 1991.jpg|Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1991 Poster\nImage:Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride T-Shirt 1991.jpg|Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1991 T-shirt\nImage:Coach ticket to London Pride 1991.jpg|Coach ticket to London Pride 1991\nImage:Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1990 & 1991 Badges.jpg|Badges from Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1990 & 1991\nImage:Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1992 Brochure.gif|Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride Brochure 1992\nImage:Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1992 Poster.jpg|Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1992 Poster\nImage:Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1992 T-Shirt.jpg|Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1992 T-shirt\nImage:Pride flyer for benefit night at Jody's.jpg|Benefit night at Jody's, Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1992 \nImage:Liverpool Pride 1992 tea dance programme.gif|Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1992 tea dance programme\nFile:Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1995.gif|Liverpool Lesbian & Gay Pride 1995\n</gallery>\n\n==Liverpool Gay Pride 1979==\n\nThe first recorded Liverpool Pride commenced on 22 June 1979 and consisted of a week long celebration in remembrance of the New York [[Stonewall riots]], which took place in the June some ten years earlier.  The Liverpool event can legitimately claim to be one of the earliest known Prides to ever take place in the [[United Kingdom]], the oldest being a march of 700 people through central London in 1972.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catalystmedia.org.uk/issues/nerve11/june/june.htm |title=Merseyside Resistance Calendar - June |publisher=Nerve Issue 11 (Winter 2007) |accessdate=2012-05-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/this-britain/pride-london-from-gay-protest-to-street-party-551908.html |title=Pride London: From gay protest to street party |publisher=The Independent |accessdate=2012-05-28}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.liverpoolpride.co.uk/ Liverpool Pride (Official Site)]\n\n{{LGBT topics in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Pride parades}}\n\n[[Category:Pride parades in England]]\n[[Category:LGBT culture in Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Festivals in Liverpool]]\n[[Category:LGBT organisations in England]]\n[[Category:Summer events in England]]\n", "name_user": "Jo-Jo Eumerus", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Elouiseclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liverpool_Pride"}
{"title_page": "Terry Ronald", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = Terry Ronald\n|image_size = 156\n|background = non_performing_personnel\n|birth_name = Terry Maxwell Ronald\n|origin = [[South London]], England\n|occupation = Author, writer, producer, songwriter\n|years_active = 1987\u2013present\n|label = [[Music Corporation of America|MCA]] <small>(1987\u20131992)</small>\n|publisher = [[Transworld]]\n|website = [http://www.terryronald.com TerryRonald.com]\n}}\n'''Terry Maxwell Ronald''' is an [[English people|English]] author, singer, songwriter, and music producer.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in South London, Ronald was a founder member and lead singer with the pop band ''[[Gun Shy (band)|Gun Shy]]'',<ref name=SSG/> who released one single \"Just To Be Your Secret\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Gun-Shy-Just-To-Be-Your-Secret/release/1757743 |title=Gun Shy - Just To Be Your Secret (Vinyl) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-06}}</ref> which was [[Peter Powell (disc jockey)|Peter Powell]]'s record of the week on [[BBC Radio 1|Radio One]]. In the early 1990s, Ronald released solo album \"Roma\" on [[MCA Records]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Terry-Ronald-Chains-Of-Love/release/2095464 |title=Terry Ronald - Roma (CD, Album) at Discogs |publisher=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-06}}</ref><ref name=RHBio/> from which four singles were released.\n\nRonald developed his career as a melody writer and lyricist, usually working with another writer. His musical work includes songwriting, production and vocal arranging for [[Kylie Minogue]], [[Girls Aloud]], [[Dannii Minogue]], [[Sophie Ellis-Bextor]], [[The Wanted]], [[Westlife]], [[The Saturdays]],  [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]], [[Sheena Easton]], [[Kim Wilde]], [[Atomic Kitten]], [[Geri Halliwell]], Elouise and French pop starlet [[Lorie (singer)|Lorie]].<ref name=SSG/><ref name=RHBio/> In 2007, he appeared as a guest judge on the Judges' Homes section of The X Factor, alongside Dannii Minogue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.terryronald.com/biography/ |title=\u00bb Biography Terry Ronald |publisher=Terryronald.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-06}}</ref> He has  worked as a vocal coach on music TV shows including ''The Voice'', ''The Voice Kids'', ''All Together Now'' and ''Let's Sing & Dance For Comic Relief''.\n\nRonald has worked on the creative team of several West End theatre productions, including Rent Remixed, which starred [[Denise Van Outen]], Siobhan Donaghy and Luke Evans,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.classicalsource.com/db_control/db_concert_review.php?id=5034 |title=Rent Remixed - from www.classicalsource.com |publisher=Classicalsource.com |date=2007-10-16 |accessdate=2014-06-06}}</ref> and The Hurly Burly Show.<ref name=SSG>{{cite web|url=http://sosogay.co.uk/2011/interview-terry-ronald/|title=Interview: Terry Ronald|author=Alasdair Spiv|publisher=So So Gay|date=16 March 2011|accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref> In 2013 Ronald co-wrote the musical one-woman play ''[[Some Girl I Used To Know]]'' with Denise Van Outen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/birmingham-theatre/news/10-2013/denise-van-outen-tours-one-woman-show-next-year_32317.html |title=Denise Van Outen tours one-woman show next year - Theatre News - 16 Oct 2013 |publisher=Whatsonstage.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-06}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he wrote his first novel ''[[Becoming Nancy]]'',<ref name=RHBio>{{cite web|url=http://www.randomhouse.co.uk/authors/terry-ronald|title=Author: Terry Ronald|publisher=[[Random House]]|accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref> published in April 2011 by Transworld and described by Suzy Feay in [[The Independent]] as \"a deliciously camp rites of passage novel\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Suzi Feay |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/max-wallis-and-the-award-for-savage-wit-goes-to-8348229.html |title=Max Wallis: 'And the award for savage wit goes to ...' - Features - Books |publisher=The Independent |date=2012-11-25 |accessdate=2014-06-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.between-the-lines.co.uk/?p=1284 |title=What Shall I Read? \u00bb Dannii dazzles at best friend Terry Ronald\u2019s launch party |publisher=Between-the-lines.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-06-06}}</ref> The book was shortlisted for the 2012 Polari First Book Prize, and in January 2014 it was announced that [[Tony Award]]-winning director and choreographer [[Jerry Mitchell]] had bought the rights to the musical stage version of the book, which is set to open in the U.S in 2019 at the [[Alliance Theatre]] in Atlanta. <ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Jerry-Mitchell-to-Adapt-Terry-Ronalds-BECOMING-NANCY-to-Stage-Musical-20140124 |title=Jerry Mitchell to Adapt Terry Ronald's BECOMING NANCY to Stage Musical |publisher=Broadwayworld.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-06}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n==Personal life==\nRonald lives in East Dulwich, South London with his [[civil partner]], Mark.<ref name=RHBio/>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Solo albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ebf5ff;\"\n! Year !! Album / Year of release !! Singles\n|-\n|1990\n|\n*''[[Studio Sessions (Terry Ronald album)|Studio Sessions]]''\n|\n*\n*Contains live studio recordings from ''Roma'' and two cover songs\n|-\n|1991\n|Roma\n|\n*Calm the Rage\"\n*\"[[Chains of Love (Terry Ronald song)|Chains of Love]]\"\n*\"[[One More Dollar]]\"\n*\"[[What the Child Needs]]\"\n*Sweet Sound Of Love\n*Save Me From Myself\n*Live Forever\n*Red\n*All I Wanted was To Love You\n*Hearts & Flowers\n*Cold Heart\n*48 Hours\n|-\n|2019\n|Underworld Gospel EP\n|My Underworld\nWhat The Child Needs\n\nChild Theme\n\nUnderworld Gospel\n\nGospel Reprise\n|}\n\n===Solo singles===\n{| class=\"sortable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ebf5ff;\"\n! Year !! Single / Release date / Label !! Tracks\n|-\n|1990\n|\n*\"Calm the Rage\"\n*Released: June 1990\n*Label: [[Music Corporation of 