{"title_page": "Philip Moore, Baron Moore of Wolvercote", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Lord Moore of Wolvercote\n| honorific-suffix =  {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCB|GCVO|CMG|QSO|PC}}\n| image         = Sir Philip Moore 1979.jpg\n| order         =[[Private Secretary to the Sovereign]]\n| term_start    = 12 November 1977\n| term_end      = 1 April 1986\n| monarch       = [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Elizabeth II]]\n| predecessor   = Sir [[Martin Charteris]]\n| successor     = Sir [[William Heseltine]]\n| office3                    = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start3                = 22 July 1986\n| term_end3                  = 7 April 2009<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n|birth_name=Philip Brian Cecil Moore\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1921|4|6|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2009|4|7|1921|4|6|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| party         = \n| religion      = \n| alma_mater    = [[Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n| spouse        = \n}}\n\n'''Philip Brian Cecil Moore, Baron Moore of Wolvercote''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCB|GCVO|CMG|QSO|PC}} (6 April 1921 &ndash; 7 April 2009) was [[Private Secretary to the Sovereign|Private Secretary]] to [[Queen Elizabeth II]] of the [[United Kingdom]] from 1977 to 1986.\n\nHe was educated at the [[Dragon School]], [[Cheltenham College]], then [[Brasenose College, Oxford]], and served in [[RAF Bomber Command]] during [[World War II]]. He played one match for the {{nrut|England}} international rugby union team, against {{nrut|Wales}} in the [[1951 Five Nations Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/england/rugby/player/5356.html|title=ESPNscrum profile|accessdate=17 August 2019|work=ESPN scrum}}</ref>\n\nMoore was then Private Secretary from 1957 to 1958, to the [[George Douglas-Hamilton, 10th Earl of Selkirk|10th Earl of Selkirk]] in the latter's capacity as [[First Lord of the Admiralty]]. He was Deputy British High Commissioner (and acting HC) in Singapore, 1963\u201365, and back in the UK, Chief of Public Relations of the Ministry of Defence 1965\u201366.<ref>Who's Who</ref> He was then Assistant Private Secretary to [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]] from 1966 to 1972, then as Deputy until 1977 and as [[Private Secretary to the Sovereign]] until 1986. On his retirement in 1986, he was created '''Baron Moore of Wolvercote''', of [[Wolvercote]] in the [[Oxford|City of Oxford]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=50610 |date=28 July 1986 |page=9909}}</ref> and he lived in a [[grace and favour]] apartment in [[Hampton Court Palace]]. He received the honour of being made a Permanent Lord in Waiting.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tomlinson|first=Richard|title=They also serve, who only ush|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/they-also-serve-who-only-ush-why-is-the-queen-followed-by-people-in-antique-clothes-richard-tomlinson-on-the-lords-ladies-women-masters-silver-sticks-and-white-staves-at-court-1564751.html|newspaper=Independent|date=20 Dec 1992}}</ref><ref>[The Times, UK, 12 November 1977]</ref>\n\nHis former son-in-law was the singer [[Peter Gabriel]]. His wife Joanna died in 2011 aged 86.\n\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|escutcheon = Gules on a fess between two lions passant guardant Or three moorcocks Sable crested Gules.\n|crest = A moorcock Proper gorged with a crown Or holding in its dexter claw a quill pen proper.\n|supporters = Dexter, a wolf Proper crowned Or gorged with a collar Argent fimbriated Or thereon roses Gules barbed and seeded Proper and cross crosslets Sable; sinister, a stag Proper attired and unguled Or crowned also Or gorged with a collar Argent fimbriated Or thereon cross crosslets Sable and roses Gules barbed and seeded Proper therefrom a chain reflexed over the back ending in a ring Gold, the compartment comprising a grassy mount growing therefrom on each side between a thistle and a shamrock both Proper a rose Gules stalk and leaves Vert barbed and seeded to the front thereof on the dexter side a rugby football and similarly on the sinister side a cricket ball Proper.\n|motto = Moribus Et Consilio <ref>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Peerage |date=2000}}</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/royalty-obituaries/5232128/Lord-Moore-of-Wolvercote.html |title=Obituary: Lord Moore of Wolvercote |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=27 April 2009 |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group|TMG]] |location=[[London, UK|London]] |issn=0307-1235 |oclc=49632006 |accessdate=22 December 2014}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-court}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Private Secretary to the Sovereign]] | before=[[Martin Charteris, Baron Charteris of Amisfield|Sir Martin Charteris]] | after=[[William Heseltine|Sir William Heseltine]] | years=1977&ndash;1986}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Philip}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Assistant Private Secretaries to the Sovereign]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of St Michael and St George|Moore of Wolvercote, Philip Moore, Baron]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Queen's Service Order|Moore of Wolvercote, Philip Moore, Baron]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers|Moore of Wolvercote]]\n[[Category:Deputy Private Secretaries to the Sovereign]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath|Moore of Wolvercote, Philip Moore, Baron]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order|Moore of Wolvercote, Philip Moore, Baron]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Cheltenham College]]\n[[Category:Private Secretaries to the Sovereign]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:England international rugby union players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Gloucestershire]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Oxfordshire cricketers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Lord Moore of Wolvercote\n| honorific-suffix =  {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCB|GCVO|CMG|QSO|PC}}\n| image         = Sir Philip Moore 1979.jpg\n| order         =[[Private Secretary to the Sovereign]]\n| term_start    = 12 November 1977\n| term_end      = 1 April 1986\n| monarch       = [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Elizabeth II]]\n| predecessor   = Sir [[Martin Charteris]]\n| successor     = Sir [[William Heseltine]]\n| office3                    = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start3                = 22 July 1986\n| term_end3                  = 7 April 2009<br>[[Life Peerage]]\n|birth_name=Philip Brian Cecil Moore\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1921|4|6|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2009|4|7|1921|4|6|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| party         = \n| religion      = \n| alma_mater    = [[Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n| spouse        = \n}}\n\n'''Philip Brian Cecil Moore, Baron Moore of Wolvercote''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCB|GCVO|CMG|QSO|PC}} (6 April 1921 &ndash; 7 April 2009) was [[Private Secretary to the Sovereign|Private Secretary]] to [[Queen Elizabeth II]] of the [[United Kingdom]] from 1977 to 1986.\n\nHe was educated at the [[Dragon School]], [[Cheltenham College]], then [[Brasenose College, Oxford]], and served in [[RAF Bomber Command]] during [[World War II]]. He played one match for the {{nrut|England}} international rugby union team, against {{nrut|Wales}} in the [[1951 Five Nations Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/england/rugby/player/5356.html|title=ESPNscrum profile|accessdate=17 August 2019|work=ESPN scrum}}</ref>\n\nMoore was then Private Secretary from 1957 to 1958, to the [[George Douglas-Hamilton, 10th Earl of Selkirk|10th Earl of Selkirk]] in the latter's capacity as [[First Lord of the Admiralty]]. He was Deputy British High Commissioner (and acting HC) in Singapore, 1963\u201365, and back in the UK, Chief of Public Relations of the Ministry of Defence 1965-66.<ref>Who's Who</ref> He was then Assistant Private Secretary to [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen Elizabeth II]] from 1966 to 1972, then as Deputy until 1977 and as [[Private Secretary to the Sovereign]] until 1986. On his retirement in 1986, he was created '''Baron Moore of Wolvercote''', of [[Wolvercote]] in the [[Oxford|City of Oxford]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=50610 |date=28 July 1986 |page=9909}}</ref> and he lived in a [[grace and favour]] apartment in [[Hampton Court Palace]]. He received the honour of being made a Permanent Lord in Waiting.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tomlinson|first=Richard|title=They also serve, who only ush|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/they-also-serve-who-only-ush-why-is-the-queen-followed-by-people-in-antique-clothes-richard-tomlinson-on-the-lords-ladies-women-masters-silver-sticks-and-white-staves-at-court-1564751.html|newspaper=Independent|date=20 Dec 1992}}</ref><ref>[The Times, UK, 12 November 1977]</ref>\n\nHis former son-in-law was the singer [[Peter Gabriel]]. His wife Joanna died in 2011 aged 86.\n\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|escutcheon = Gules on a fess between two lions passant guardant Or three moorcocks Sable crested Gules.\n|crest = A moorcock Proper gorged with a crown Or holding in its dexter claw a quill pen proper.\n|supporters = Dexter, a wolf Proper crowned Or gorged with a collar Argent fimbriated Or thereon roses Gules barbed and seeded Proper and cross crosslets Sable; sinister, a stag Proper attired and unguled Or crowned also Or gorged with a collar Argent fimbriated Or thereon cross crosslets Sable and roses Gules barbed and seeded Proper therefrom a chain reflexed over the back ending in a ring Gold, the compartment comprising a grassy mount growing therefrom on each side between a thistle and a shamrock both Proper a rose Gules stalk and leaves Vert barbed and seeded to the front thereof on the dexter side a rugby football and similarly on the sinister side a cricket ball Proper.\n|motto = Moribus Et Consilio <ref>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Peerage |date=2000}}</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/royalty-obituaries/5232128/Lord-Moore-of-Wolvercote.html |title=Obituary: Lord Moore of Wolvercote |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=27 April 2009 |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group|TMG]] |location=[[London, UK|London]] |issn=0307-1235 |oclc=49632006 |accessdate=22 December 2014}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-court}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Private Secretary to the Sovereign]] | before=[[Martin Charteris, Baron Charteris of Amisfield|Sir Martin Charteris]] | after=[[William Heseltine|Sir William Heseltine]] | years=1977&ndash;1986}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, Philip}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Assistant Private Secretaries to the Sovereign]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of St Michael and St George|Moore of Wolvercote, Philip Moore, Baron]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Queen's Service Order|Moore of Wolvercote, Philip Moore, Baron]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers|Moore of Wolvercote]]\n[[Category:Deputy Private Secretaries to the Sovereign]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath|Moore of Wolvercote, Philip Moore, Baron]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order|Moore of Wolvercote, Philip Moore, Baron]]\n[[Category:Members of the 