{"title_page": "John Mogg, Baron Mogg", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name        = The Lord Mogg\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of St Michael and St George|KCMG]]\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = John Frederick Mogg\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1943|10|5|df=y}}   \n| birth_place = [[Birmingham]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| residence   = \n| nationality = British\n| other_names = Sir John Mogg (1943\u20132003)\n| employer    = \n| occupation  = [[Chairman]], [[Ofgem]]\n| term        =\n| predecessor = \n| successor   = \n| religion    = \n| spouse      = \n| relatives   = \n| website     = \n| footnotes   = \n}}\n\n'''John Frederick Mogg, Baron Mogg''' [[Order of St Michael and St George|KCMG]] (5 October 1943) is a previous Chairman of [[Ofgem]] and the current Chairman of the EU Energy Regulators. It was announced that he would become a [[life peer]] on 18 April 2008,<ref>''House of Lords Appointments Commission \u2013 New Non-Party-Political Peers'' (2008), House of Lords Appointments Commission, London, UK, viewed 8 May 2008, http://www.lordsappointments.gov.uk/news/080418_peers.aspx\n</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=58671 |page=6001|date=18 April 2008}}</ref> and on 28 May 2008 he was created '''Baron Mogg''', of Queen's Park in the county of [[East Sussex]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=58713 |page=8159|date=30 May 2008}}</ref>\nOn 14 January 2019 he retired from the House of Lords.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-mogg/3855|title=Lord Mogg|publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]]}}</ref>\n\n==Professional life==\n\nMogg spent half of his career in the [[Civil Service (United Kingdom)|Civil Service]], particularly with regards to industry and [[European community|European]] issues. He also served with the [[European Commission]], reaching the grade of Director-General with responsibility for the Internal Market and Financial Services. Mogg is currently Chair of the Board of Governors at [[Brighton College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brightoncollege.org.uk/practical-information/governors/|title=Governors - Practical Information - Brighton College|publisher=Brighton College|accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was appointed a [[Knight Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]] (KCMG) in 2003.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=56963|supp=y |page=3|date=18 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn his previous role as chairman of energy regulator Ofgem (a three-day-a-week job), he received \u00a3214,999 a year salary, as revealed to the public in July 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/politics/10482482.stm|title=Quango chiefs' salaries revealed|date=2 July 2010|work=BBC News|accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Titles==\n\n* Mr John Mogg (1943\u20132003)\n* Sir John Mogg KCMG (2003\u20132008)\n* The Rt. Hon. The Lord Mogg KCMG (2008\u2013)\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mogg, John}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name        = The Lord Mogg\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of St Michael and St George|KCMG]]\n| image       = \n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = John Frederick Mogg\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1943|10|5|df=y}}   \n| birth_place = [[Birmingham]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| residence   = \n| nationality = British\n| other_names = Sir John Mogg (1943\u20132003)\n| employer    = \n| occupation  = [[Chairman]], [[Ofgem]]\n| term        =\n| predecessor = \n| successor   = \n| religion    = \n| spouse      = \n| relatives   = \n| website     = \n| footnotes   = \n}}\n\n'''John Frederick Mogg, Baron Mogg''' [[Order of St Michael and St George|KCMG]] (5 October 1943) is a previous Chairman of [[Ofgem]] and the current Chairman of the EU Energy Regulators. It was announced that he would become a [[life peer]] on 18 April 2008,<ref>''House of Lords Appointments Commission \u2013 New Non-Party-Political Peers'' (2008), House of Lords Appointments Commission, London, UK, viewed 8 May 2008, http://www.lordsappointments.gov.uk/news/080418_peers.aspx\n</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=58671 |page=6001|date=18 April 2008}}</ref> and on 28 May 2008 he was created '''Baron Mogg''', of Queen\u2019s Park in the county of [[East Sussex]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=58713 |page=8159|date=30 May 2008}}</ref>\nOn 14 January 2019 he retired from the House of Lords.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-mogg/3855|title=Lord Mogg|publisher=[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]]}}</ref>\n\n==Professional life==\n\nMogg spent half of his career in the [[Civil Service (United Kingdom)|Civil Service]], particularly with regards to industry and [[European community|European]] issues. He also served with the [[European Commission]], reaching the grade of Director-General with responsibility for the Internal Market and Financial Services. Mogg is currently Chair of the Board of Governors at [[Brighton College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brightoncollege.org.uk/practical-information/governors/|title=Governors - Practical Information - Brighton College|publisher=Brighton College|accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was appointed a [[Knight Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]] (KCMG) in 2003.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=56963|supp=y |page=3|date=18 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn his previous role as chairman of energy regulator Ofgem (a three-day-a-week job), he received \u00a3214,999 a year salary, as revealed to the public in July 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/politics/10482482.stm|title=Quango chiefs' salaries revealed|date=2 July 2010|work=BBC News|accessdate=2 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Titles==\n\n* Mr John Mogg (1943\u20132003)\n* Sir John Mogg KCMG (2003\u20132008)\n* The Rt. Hon. The Lord Mogg KCMG (2008\u2013)\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mogg, John}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Mogg,_Baron_Mogg"}
{"title_page": "Jean McFarlane, Baroness McFarlane of Llandaff", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Expand German|Jean McFarlane, Baroness McFarlane of Llandaff|topic=bio|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name=The Baroness McFarlane of Llandaff\n| honorific-suffix = [[Chartered Society of Physiotherapy|MCSP]]\n| image=\n| order=\n|office5         = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start5       = 30 July 1979\n|term_end5       = 13 May 2012<br/>[[Life Peerage]] \n| birth_date    ={{birth date|1926|4|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place   =[[Cardiff]], [[Wales]], [[UK]]\n| death_date    ={{death date and age|2012|5|13|1926|4|1|df=y}}\n| party= [[Crossbench]]\n}}\n\n'''Jean Kennedy McFarlane, Baroness McFarlane of Llandaff''', [[Royal College of Nursing|FRCN]], [[Chartered Society of Physiotherapy|MCSP]] (1 April 1926 \u2013 13 May 2012)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201213/minutes/120515/ldordpap.htm |title=Minutes of Proceedings, House of Lords |date=14 May 2012}}</ref> was a British nurse and member of the [[House of Lords]].\n\n==Biography==\nMcFarlane was born in Cardiff, Wales, and later trained as a nurse, a midwife, and as a health visitor before going on to pursue a successful career in nursing teaching and administration. She studied sociology at [[Bedford College, London]].<ref>Hardy, Susan and Corones, Anthony, \"The Nurse\u2019s Uniform as Ethopoietic Fashion\", ''Fashion Theory'', Vol.21, No.5. (2015), pp. 523-552. [https://doi.org/10.1080/1362704X.2016.1203090 doi=10.1080/1362704X.2016.1203090]</ref> In the 1960s she participated in the [[Royal College of Nursing]] research programme \"Study of Nursing Care\". In 1974 she became the holder of the first Chair of Nursing at an [[England|English]] university (the [[University of Manchester]]) and held it until 1989.\n\nMcFarlane served on the [[Royal Commission]] on the [[National Health Service]], 1976\u201379 (Chairman: Sir [[Alec Merrison]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shef.ac.uk/library/special/royal.html|title=Royal Commission papers|publisher=University of Sheffield|accessdate=14 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nA committed Christian, she served as a member of the [[general synod]] of the [[Church of England]] 1990\u20131994.<ref>Guardian obituary https://www.theguardian.com/education/2012/may/24/lady-jean-mcfarlane-of-llandaff</ref>\n\n==House of Lords==\nMcFarlane was created a [[life peer]] in the House of Lords as '''Baroness McFarlane of Llandaff''', of Llandaff in the County of [[South Glamorgan]] on 30 July 1979,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=47918 |date=2 August 1979 |page=9797}}</ref> in the [[British honours system|Queen's Birthday Honours]] list.\n\nMcFarlane was a member of four [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|select committees]] of the House of Lords. As well as being a Vice President of the League of Nurses of [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], she was a Fellow of the [[Royal College of Nursing]] and a trustee of numerous charities. In 2005, she was awarded the [[British Journal of Nursing]]'s Lifetime Achievement Award.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2009, a new building of the University of Manchester was named the Jean McFarlane Building. It is situated to the east of University Place and is one of many completed in recent years.<ref>''UniLife''; 1 June 2009, p. 4</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nursing.manchester.ac.uk/aboutus/news/jeanmcfarlane|title=Jean McFarlane Building|publisher=University of Manchester|accessdate=14 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nBaroness McFarlane was the author of a number of studies, notably ''A Guide to the Practice of Nursing Using the Nursing Process'', 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://copac.ac.uk/search?&au=Jean+McFarlane&sort-order=ti%2C%2Ddate|title=Writings by Jean McFarlane|publisher=Copac|accessdate=14 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McFarlane of Llandaff, Jean McFarlane, Baroness}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Cardiff]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Welsh nurses]]\n[[Category:British non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Howell's School Llandaff]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal College of Nursing]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=June 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Expand German|Jean McFarlane, Baroness McFarlane of Llandaff|topic=bio|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name=The Baroness McFarlane of Llandaff\n| honorific-suffix = [[Chartered Society of Physiotherapy|MCSP]]\n| image=\n| order=\n|office5         = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start5       = 30 July 1979\n|term_end5       = 13 May 2012<br/>[[Life Peerage]] \n| birth_date    ={{birth date|1926|4|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place   =[[Cardiff]], [[Wales]], [[UK]]\n| death_date    ={{death date and age|2012|5|13|1926|4|1|df=y}}\n| party= [[Crossbench]]\n}}\n\n'''Jean Kennedy McFarlane, Baroness McFarlane of Llandaff''', [[Royal College of Nursing|FRCN]], [[Chartered Society of Physiotherapy|MCSP]] (1 April 1926 \u2013 13 May 2012)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201213/minutes/120515/ldordpap.htm |title=Minutes of Proceedings, House of Lords |date=14 May 2012}}</ref> was a British nurse and member of the [[House of Lords]].\n\n==Biography==\nMcFarlane was born in Cardiff, Wales, and later trained as a nurse, a midwife, and as a health visitor before going on to pursue a successful career in nursing teaching and administration. She studied sociology at [[Bedford College, London]].<ref>Hardy, Susan and Corones, Anthony, \"The Nurse\u2019s Uniform as Ethopoietic Fashion\", ''Fashion Theory'', Vol.21, No.5. (2015), pp. 523-552. [https://doi.org/10.1080/1362704X.2016.1203090 doi=10.1080/1362704X.2016.1203090]</ref> In the 1960s she participated in the [[Royal College of Nursing]] research programme \"Study of Nursing Care\". In 1974 she became the holder of the first Chair of Nursing at an [[England|English]] university (the [[University of Manchester]]) and held it until 1989.\n\nMcFarlane served on the [[Royal Commission]] on the [[National Health Service]], 1976\u201379 (Chairman: Sir [[Alec Merrison]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shef.ac.uk/library/special/royal.html|title=Royal Commission papers|publisher=University of Sheffield|accessdate=14 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nA committed Christian, she served as a member of the [[general synod]] of the [[Church of England]] 1990-1994.<ref>Guardian obituary https://www.theguardian.com/education/2012/may/24/lady-jean-mcfarlane-of-llandaff</ref>\n\n==House of Lords==\nMcFarlane was created a [[life peer]] in the House of Lords as '''Baroness McFarlane of Llandaff''', of Llandaff in the County of [[South Glamorgan]] on 30 July 1979,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=47918 |date=2 August 1979 |page=9797}}</ref> in the [[British honours system|Queen's Birthday Honours]] list.\n\nMcFarlane was a member of four [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|select committees]] of the House of Lords. As well as being a Vice President of the League of Nurses of [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]], she was a Fellow of the [[Royal College of Nursing]] and a trustee of numerous charities. In 2005, she was awarded the [[British Journal of Nursing]]'s Lifetime Achievement Award.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2009, a new building of the University of Manchester was named the Jean McFarlane Building. It is situated to the east of University Place and is one of many completed in recent years.<ref>''UniLife''; 1 June 2009, p. 4</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nursing.manchester.ac.uk/aboutus/news/jeanmcfarlane|title=Jean McFarlane Building|publisher=University of Manchester|accessdate=14 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nBaroness McFarlane was the author of a number of studies, notably ''A Guide to the Practice of Nursing Using the Nursing Process'', 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://copac.ac.uk/search?&au=Jean+McFarlane&sort-order=ti%2C%2Ddate|title=Writings by Jean McFarlane|publisher=Copac|accessdate=14 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McFarlane of Llandaff, Jean McFarlane, Baroness}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Cardiff]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Welsh nurses]]\n[[Category:British non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Howell's School Llandaff]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal College of Nursing]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1990-1994 \u2192 1990\u20131994", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_McFarlane,_Baroness_McFarlane_of_Llandaff"}
