ry|Mexico}} || {{Percentage bar|40|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|25|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|35|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +15\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|India}} || {{Percentage bar|1|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|90|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|9|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +16\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Germany}} || {{Percentage bar|51|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|34|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|15|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +17\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Peru}} || {{Percentage bar|41|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|21|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|38|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +20\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Brazil}} || {{Percentage bar|45|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|25|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|30|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +20\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Russia}} || {{Percentage bar|44|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|16|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|40|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +28\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Chile}} || {{Percentage bar|45|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|15|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|40|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +30\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Indonesia}} || {{Percentage bar|59|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|26|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|15|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +33\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Israel}} || {{Percentage bar|50|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|6|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|44|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +44\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Japan}} || {{Percentage bar|47|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|2|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|51|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +45\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Nigeria}} || {{Percentage bar|67|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|22|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|11|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +45\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|UK}} || {{Percentage bar|72|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|23|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|5|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +49\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|France}} || {{Percentage bar|72|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|20|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|8|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +52\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Australia}} || {{Percentage bar|73|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|18|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|9|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +54\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|South Korea}} || {{Percentage bar|74|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|14|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|12|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +60\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Kenya}} || {{Percentage bar|74|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|10|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|16|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +64\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Ghana}} || {{Percentage bar|78|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|9|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|13|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +69\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Canada}} || {{Percentage bar|80|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|9|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|11|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +71\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|USA}} || {{Percentage bar|81|c=#80FF80|width=50}}||{{Percentage bar|10|c=#FF8080|width=50}}||{{Percentage bar|9|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}}|| +71\n|-\n|}\n</div>\n\n'''Anti-British sentiment''' is prejudice, fear or hatred against the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British Government]], the [[Culture of the United Kingdom|culture]] or the [[British people|people]] of the [[United Kingdom]], or its [[British Overseas Territories|Overseas Territories]].\n\n==Argentina==\n{{See also|Argentina\u2013United Kingdom relations|Falkland Islands sovereignty dispute|Argentina and England football rivalry}}\n\n[[File:Ushuaia - El Fin del Mundo (8319316181).jpg|thumb|Sign in [[Ushuaia]], Argentina some 700&nbsp;km from the [[Falkland Islands]]: \"Mooring by English pirates's ships is prohibited\".]]\nAnti-British feeling in Argentina originates mainly from two causes.\n\nThe first and older cause was the intervention of British [[Capitalism|capital]] and companies together with their disproportional political influence. This political influence is associated with the local [[oligarchy]] and its economic model based on the primary sector and commodities.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Scalabrini Ortiz|first=Raul|title=Pol\u00edtica Brit\u00e1nica en el R\u00edo de la Plata|publisher=La Biblioteca Argentina|year=1940|isbn=84-95594-76-5|location=Argentina|url=https://www.academia.edu/6597566/101809023-Politica-Britanica-en-el-Rio-de-la-Plata}}</ref>{{page needed|date=February 2020}} In turn, this led to controversial actions by successive Argentine governments such as the [[Roca\u2013Runciman Treaty]] and the [[Treaty of Madrid (1989)]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dipublico.org/4051/acuerdo-de-madrid-ii-declaracion-conjunta-de-las-delegaciones-de-la-republica-argentina-y-del-reino-unido-de-gran-bretana-e-irlanda-del-norte/|title=Acuerdo de Madrid II \u2013 Declaraci\u00f3n Conjunta de las delegaciones de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina y del Reino Unido de Gran Breta\u00f1a e Irlanda del Norte.|date=2010-06-24|website=Derecho Internacional P\u00fablico - www.dipublico.org|language=es|access-date=2019-05-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Falkland Enemies Resume Relations|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/02/16/world/falkland-enemies-resume-relations.html|work=The New York Times|date=16 February 1990|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204114647/http://www.nytimes.com/1990/02/16/world/falkland-enemies-resume-relations.html|archivedate=4 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe second one is the [[Falkland Islands sovereignty dispute]] and the [[Falklands War]] in 1982 between Argentina and the United Kingdom. Due to this, anti-British and acts of vandalism do erupt.<ref>{{cite news |author=Ed Stocker |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |title=Argentina to see biggest anti-British protests for years |date=2 April 2010 |via=MercoPress |url=https://en.mercopress.com/2010/04/02/argentina-to-see-biggest-anti-british-protests-for-years}}</ref>\n\n==Ex-British colonies==\n{{main|British Raj|Indian independence movement}}\n{{see also|India\u2013United Kingdom relations}}\n\n[[File:A view of shops with anti-British and pro-Independence signs, possibly on Kings Street, Valetta, Malta (5074435957).jpg|thumb|A view of shops with anti-British and pro-Independence signs, Valletta, [[Malta]], c. 1960]]\nIn many ex-colonial territories, anti-British sentiment was particularly prevalent before and immediately after achieving independence but has ameliorated since.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nIn India, Pakistan and Bangladesh, the [[Indian independence movement]] encouraged this sentiment.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anti-British sentiment in India|url=http://www.tourismofindia.com/ff/history.htm|publisher=Tourism of India|accessdate=2 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Iran==\n{{See also|Iran\u2013United Kingdom relations}}\nAnti-British sentiment, sometimes described as Anglophobia, has been described as \"deeply entrenched in Iranian culture\",<ref name=guardian>Jonathan Freedland, [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2007/apr/04/comment.military \"If this crisis can be overcome, think about the negotiations that matter\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 4 April 2007. Accessed 24 November 2009.</ref> and reported to be increasingly prevalent in [[Iran]]. In July 2009, an adviser to [[Ayatollah]] [[Ali Khamenei]] called Britain \"worse than America\" for its alleged interference in Iran's post-election affairs.  In the first half of the 20th century, the [[British Empire]] exerted political influence over Iran (Persia) in order to control the profits from the [[Anglo-Persian Oil Company]]. As a result, British influence was widely known to have been behind the overthrow of the [[Qajar Dynasty]] in the 1920s, the subsequent rise of [[Rez\u0101 Sh\u0101h|Reza Shah Pahlavi]], and the [[1953 Iranian coup d'\u00e9tat|successful coup d'\u00e9tat]] overthrowing prime minister [[Mohammad Mosaddeq]] in 1953.<ref name=times>Ali Ansari, [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/guest_contributors/article6571685.ece \"Why Iran is obsessed with the British wily fox\"], ''[[The Times]]'', 25 June 2009. Accessed 24 November 2009.{{dead link|date=February 2020}}</ref><ref name=washingtonpost>Tara Bahrampour, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/16/AR2009071604126.html \"In Wake of Unrest, Britain Replacing U.S. as Iran's Great Satan\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', 17 July 2009. Accessed 24 November 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.ir-psri.com/Show.php?Page=ViewHighlight&HighlightID=126&SP=Farsi Conference on \"Iran and British colonialism\"], March 2008 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303151846/http://www.ir-psri.com/Show.php?Page=ViewHighlight&HighlightID=126&SP=Farsi |date=3 March 2012 }}. Accessed 24 November 2009</ref>\n\nOn Monday 9 August 2010, the senior Iranian minister and Iran's first vice president [[Mohammad Reza Rahimi]] declared that the British people were \"stupid\" and \"not human\". His remarks drew criticism from Simon Gass, the British ambassador in Iran, and also from the media in Britain.{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nIn November 2011 the Iranian parliament voted to downgrade relations with the UK after British sanctions were imposed on Iran due to its nuclear programme. Politicians reportedly shouted \"Death to Britain\".<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iran/8908860/Iran-MPs-cry-Death-to-Britain-in-parliament.html \"Iran MPs cry 'Death to Britain' in parliament\"], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 23 November 2011. Accessed 27 May 2015.</ref> On 29 November 2011, Iranian students in Tehran stormed the British embassy, ransacked offices, smashed windows, shouted \"Death to England[sic]\" and burned the British flag.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!-- none--> |date=29 November 2011 |title=Iranian protesters storm UK embassy |publisher=Al Jazeera |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2011/11/20111129132554123213.html}}</ref>\n\nParts of the Iranian media campaigned against the reopening of the British Embassy in Tehran in August 2015, referring to Britain as an \"old fox\" &ndash; a term popularised by the Iranian writer [[Seyyed Ahmad Adib Pishavari]] (born [[Peshawar]] 1844, died Tehran 1930) &ndash; and accusing Britain of having provoked protests against the re-election of [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pourparsa |first1=Parham |title=Why is Britain an 'old fox' in Iranian media rhetoric? |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-34052821 |accessdate=15 May 2019 |publisher=BBC News |date=25 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Ireland==\n{{See also|Ireland\u2013United Kingdom relations}}\n[[File:An gorta Mor.jpg|thumb|270px|A [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Famine]] mural in Belfast. \"An Gorta M\u00f3r, Britain's genocide by starvation, Ireland's holocaust 1845\u20131849, over 1,500,000 deaths\".]]\nThere is a long tradition of anti-British sentiment, especially anti-English sentiment since the [[Norman invasion of Ireland]] and often more specifically [[Anglophobia]], within [[Irish nationalism]]. Much of this was grounded in the hostility felt by the largely Catholic poor for the Anglo-Irish gentry, which was mainly Anglican. In post-famine Ireland, anti-English hostility was adopted into the philosophy and foundation of the Irish nationalist movement. At the turn of the twentieth century, the Celtic Revival movement associated the search for a cultural and national identity with increasing anti-colonial and anti-English sentiment.\n\nA feeling of anti-English sentiment intensified within Irish nationalism during the Boer War leading to xenophobia underlined by Anglophobia. In 2011, tensions and anti-English or anti-British feelings flared in relation to the proposed state visit of [[Queen Elizabeth II]], the first British monarch to visit Ireland in 101 years. A republican demonstration was held at the GPO Dublin by a group of Irish Republicans on 26 February 2011, and a mock trial and decapitation of an effigy of Queen Elizabeth II were carried out by socialist republican group \u00c9ir\u00edg\u00ed. Other protests included one Dublin publican hanging a banner declaring \"the Queen will never be welcome in this country\"<ref>{{cite news |author=James Carroll |date=5 March 2011 |title=Sinn Fein's Gerry Adams slams Queen Elizabeth's upcoming visit to Ireland |website=IrishCentral |url=http://www.irishcentral.com/news/Sinn-Feins-Gerry-Adams-slams-Queen-Elizabeths-upcoming-visit-to-Ireland-117456423.html |accessdate=2013-11-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217083035/http://www.irishcentral.com/news/Sinn-Feins-Gerry-Adams-slams-Queen-Elizabeths-upcoming-visit-to-Ireland-117456423.html |archivedate=17 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> during her visit.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bates|first=Stephen|title=Queen shaken and stirred as Irish tour concludes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/may/20/queen-irish-tour-cork|date=20 May 2011|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Israel==\n{{See also|Israel\u2013United Kingdom relations}}\nThe relationship between Israel and the UK is generally regarded as close and warm,<ref>{{cite news |author=Peter Osborne |date=12 December 2012 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |title=The cowardice at the heart of our relationship with Israel |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/israel/9740044/The-cowardice-at-the-heart-of-our-relationship-with-Israel.html}}</ref> and as a strategic partnership of the two nations.<ref>Sixty years of British-Israeli diplomatic relations' Organisation: Foreign & Commonwealth Office [https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/sixty-years-of-british-israeli-diplomatic-relations]</ref> According to the a [[BBC World Service]] poll in 2014,<ref name=\"BBC World Service poll\"/> five in ten Israelis (50%) have favourable attitudes to the UK, and only 6% of Israelis hold negative views towards the UK, the second lowest percentage after Japan.\n\nOccasional criticism is also found. In Israel, anti-British sentiment may historically stem from British rule and policies in the [[Mandatory Palestine|mandate era]], and in modern times from the perceived anti-Israel stance of the British media.<ref name=\"Jewish Mag Eurabia\">{{cite magazine |author=Alexander Maistrovoy |url=http://www.jewishmag.com/106mag/euroarabia/euroarabia.htm |title=Farewell to Albion, or path to Eurabia |magazine=The Jewish Magazine |date=September 2006 |accessdate=2010-06-01 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100507210623/http://www.jewishmag.com/106mag/euroarabia/euroarabia.htm| archivedate=7 May 2010 | url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Aish UK Antisemitism\">{{cite web |last=Rosenblum |first=Jonathan |url=http://www.aish.com/jw/s/48898202.html |title=UK Anti- Semitism |publisher=Aish.com |date=2005-06-04 |accessdate=2010-06-01| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100606214655/http://www.aish.com/jw/s/48898202.html| archivedate=6 June 2010 | url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Haaretz antisemitism doubled\">{{cite web|last=Liphshiz |first=Cnaan |url=https://www.haaretz.com/1.5081326 |title=Watchdog: British anti-Semitism doubled after Gaza war |work=Haaretz |date=24 July 2009|accessdate=2010-06-01}}</ref><ref name=\"ynetnews British Antisemitism\">{{cite news  |author=Eytan Gilboa |date=31 May 2006 |url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3257290,00.html |title=British anti-Semitism |work=Ynetnews |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nThe Jewish population of the United Kingdom was recorded as being 269,568 in the 2011 Census. Reacting to 609 anti-Semitic incidents across the UK in the first half of 2009,<ref name=\"Haaretz antisemitism doubled\" /> and to the announcement of numerous UK organizations to impose a boycott on Israel,<ref name=\"ynetnews British Antisemitism\" /> some Israelis claimed that the UK is anti-Israeli and [[Antisemitism|Antisemitic]].<ref name=\"Jewish Mag Eurabia\" /><ref name=\"Aish UK Antisemitism\" /> According to an opinion piece by Eytan Gilboa, \"the British media systematically supports the Palestinians, and openly slants its reporting about Israel and Israeli policy. The left-wing Guardian and Independent newspapers regularly print accusatory, anti-Israel editorials, and their correspondents in Israel file biased, and occasionally false, reports. The supposedly prestigious BBC has long been a sounding board to trumpet Palestinian propaganda.\"<ref name=\"ynetnews British Antisemitism\" /> In 2010 Ron Breiman, a former chairman of the right-wing organisation \"Professors for a Strong Israel\", claimed in one of Israel's leading newspapers, ''[[Haaretz]]'', that the United Kingdom has raised and armed Israel's enemies in Jordan and the Arab Legion and described the British media as anti-Israeli.<ref>{{cite news |author=Ron Breiman |date=2 March 2010 |title=End British obsession with anti-Israel propaganda |newspaper=Haaretz |url=https://www.haaretz.com/1.5035718}}</ref>\n\nReacting to the UK government's decision to expel an Israeli diplomat because of Mossad's cloning of 12 British passports for [[Assassination of Mahmoud Al-Mabhouh|an assassination operation]] in 2010, former National Union members of the [[Knesset|Israeli parliament]] [[Michael Ben-Ari]] and [[Aryeh Eldad]] accused the British government of being \"anti-semitic\" and referred to them as \"dogs\".<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article7073250.ece Times Online - 'Israeli diplomat 'spy' expelled over cloned UK passports']{{dead link|date=February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.allvoices.com/contributed-news/5472570-british-antisemitic-dogs-israel |title=British Anti-Semitic Dogs - Israel |access-date=8 April 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726215803/http://www.allvoices.com/contributed-news/5472570-british-antisemitic-dogs-israel |archive-date=26 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Spain==\n{{See also|Disputed status of the isthmus between Gibraltar and Spain|Disputed status of Gibraltar|Telecom dispute between Gibraltar and Spain}}\nAnti-British sentiments evolved in Spain following the ceding of [[Gibraltar]] to the British through the [[Treaty of Utrecht]] in 1713 following the [[War of the Spanish Succession]].{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} In August 2013, Spain was considering forging an alliance with Argentina over the status of the [[Falkland Islands]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/gibraltar/10235937/Gibraltar-Spain-considers-joint-diplomatic-offensive-with-Argentina-over-Falkland-Islands.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Fiona | last=Govan | title=Gibraltar: Spain considers joint diplomatic offensive with Argentina over Falkland Islands | date=11 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==United States==\n{{See also|United Kingdom\u2013United States relations|Special Relationship}}\n[[File:NOLA BP Oil Flood Protest Union Jack stand.JPG|thumb|180px|American protester stands on a [[Union Flag]], presumably associating petroleum company [[BP]] with the [[United Kingdom]]; before adopting the initials \"BP\" as its official corporate name and brand, BP was known as British Petroleum.]]\nPresident [[Thomas Jefferson]] complained of an unreasonable hostility towards the British state by the people in the United States during the [[Napoleonic Wars]], brought about by the [[American Revolutionary War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cooperativeindividualism.org/jefferson_f_01.html|title=Anglophobia|publisher=Allwords.com|accessdate=2008-07-20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704155036/http://www.cooperativeindividualism.org/jefferson_f_01.html|archivedate=4 July 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[anti-Tom]] novel ''[[Tit for Tat (1856 novel)|Tit for Tat]]'' (written anonymously in 1856 by \"A Lady of New Orleans\") encouraged anti-British sentiment in reaction to Britain's positive reception of the anti-slavery novel ''[[Uncle Tom's Cabin]]'' by [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iath.virginia.edu/utc/proslav/titfortathp.html |title=Tit For Tat |publisher=Iath.virginia.edu |accessdate=2010-06-01}}</ref>\n\nDuring the World War II alliance, anti-British sentiment took different forms. In May 1942, when conditions were highly problematic for British prospects, American journalist [[Edward R. Murrow]] privately gave a British friend an analysis of the sources of persistent anti-British sentiment in the United States. He attributed it especially to:\n:partly the hard-core of anglophobes (Irish, Germans and isolationists); partly the frustration produced by war without early victories; partly our bad behaviour at Singapore; and partly the tendency common to all countries at war to blame their allies for doing nothing.<ref>Diary entry of 11 May 1942 in Nigel Nicolson, ed. ''Harold Nicolson: the War Years 1939-1945'' (1967) 2:226.</ref>\n\nSenior American military officers often tried, with little success, to push against Roosevelt support for Britain. [[Fleet Admiral]] [[Ernest King]] had been noted for these views which affected his decision-making during the \"[[Second Happy Time]]\" (in the [[Battle of the Atlantic]]).<ref>{{cite book|last=Moser|first=John E.|title=Twisting the Lion's Tail: American Anglophobia Between the World Wars|publisher=New York University Press|location=New York|date=1998-11-01|isbn=0-8147-5615-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nKLXHQAACAAJ&dq=Twisting+the+Lion%27s+Tail:+American+Anglophobia+Between+the+World+Wars|accessdate=2008-07-20}}</ref> [[Joseph Stilwell]], a four-star general in the China, Burma and India theatre of the [[Second World War]] was another noted for anti British views (for example, in this diaries he wrote, \"Boy, will this burn up the Limeys!\" when Myitkyina was finally taken). Curiously, he got on well with British military commander [[William Slim]], even volunteering to serve under him for a time rather than under [[George Giffard]]. Slim noted that Stilwell had a public persona that differed from his private relations.\n\nIn the 21st century, the [[Special Relationship]] between the United States and the United Kingdom has come under attack by advertising executive Steven A. Grasse who published ''[[The Evil Empire: 101 Ways That England Ruined the World]]'',<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0tkjhI2JiTwC&dq=%22The+Evil+Empire:+101+Ways+That+England+Ruined+The+World%22&printsec=frontcover&source=bn&hl=en&ei=W9PgSYunF5aqjAeBoLnUDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4 |title=Evil Empire: 101 Ways That England Ruined the World |publisher=Quirk Books |date=2007 |accessdate=2010-06-01 |author=Steven A. Grasse, Penny Rimbaud}}</ref> although this work is partly tongue in cheek and forms part of a larger media project launched by the author.\n\n[[Roland Emmerich]]'s [[2000 in film|2000]] movie ''[[The Patriot (2000 film)|The Patriot]]'' drew controversy for demonising the British army,<ref>{{cite news|last=Morris|first=Mark|title=Mel Gibson: Proud or prejudiced? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/jul/16/comment.features|date=16 July 2000|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> and misrepresenting [[armed forces of the United Kingdom|British forces]] depicted as engaging in savagery &ndash; such as the burning of a church with civilians inside &ndash; in the [[Thirteen Colonies]] during the [[American Revolution]].  [[Liverpool City Council]] went on to claim that the film misrepresented British officer [[Banastre Tarleton]] and sought an apology from the producers.<ref><!--no author available-->[https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/jun/30/news.melgibson \"Patriotic Liverpool up in arms over Gibson's blockbuster\"], ''The Guardian'', 3 June 2000. Retrieved 19 January 2015</ref> Other commentators noted that a similar incident was committed by German troops in the [[Oradour-sur-Glane massacre]] in [[World War II]], and suggested that the film producers may have had, consciously or subconsciously, an anti-British agenda in changing the nationalities and relocating the event to an earlier and different conflict<ref>{{cite news|last=Foreman|first=Jonathan|title=The Nazis, er, the Redcoats are coming! |url=http://www.salon.com/2000/07/03/patriot_3/|date=3 July 2000|publisher=Salon.com|accessdate=19 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Von Tunzelmann|first=Alex|title=The Patriot: more flag-waving rot with Mel Gibson|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/jul/22/the-patriot-mel-gibson-reel-history|date=23 July 2009|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> and one stated that it was similar to a \"[[blood libel]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Foreman|first=Johnathan|title=The film that says we're Nazis|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/4252781/The-film-that-says-were-Nazis.html|date=6 July 2000|work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==<!-- New links in alphabetical order please -->\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Anti-German sentiment]]\n* [[Anti-Irish sentiment]]\n* [[Anti-Russian sentiment]]\n* [[Sweden-bashing|Anti-Swedish Sentiment]]\n* [[Antisemitism]]\n* [[Consequences of Nazism]]\n* [[German American]]\n* [[Germanophilia]]\n* [[Internment of German Americans]]\n* [[List of terms used for Germans]]\n* [[Stalag fiction]]\n* [[Stereotypes of Germans]]\n* [[Operation Bolivar]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cultural criticism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anti-British Sentiment}}\n[[Category:Anti-national sentiment|British Discrimination]]\n[[Category:Anti-British sentiment| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||prejudice against England and the English people only|Anglophobia|prejudice against Scotland and the Scottish people only|Anti-Scottish sentiment|prejudice against Northern Ireland and the Irish people only|Anti-Irish sentiment|prejudice against Wales and the Welsh people only|Cultural relationship between the Welsh and the English#Anti-Welsh sentiment}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}{{Discrimination sidebar|state=collapsed}}\n<div style=\"font-size: 85%\">\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"border:1px black; float:right; margin-left:1em;\"\n|+ style=\"background:#f99;\" colspan=\"2\"|Results of 2014 [[BBC World Service]] poll.<br />Views of the United Kingdom's influence by country<ref name=\"BBC World Service poll\">{{cite web |url=http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/country-rating-poll.pdf |title=BBC World Service poll |work=BBC |date=3 June 2014}}</ref><br>Sorted by Pos-Neg\n!Country polled !! <small>Positive</small> !! <small>Negative</small> !! <small>Neutral</small> !! <small>Pos-Neg</small>\n|-\n| {{Flagcountry|Argentina}} || {{Percentage bar|29|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|39|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|32|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || -10\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Pakistan}} || {{Percentage bar|39|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|35|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|26|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +4\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Spain}} || {{Percentage bar|41|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|36|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|23|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +5\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Turkey}} || {{Percentage bar|39|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|30|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|31|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +9\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|China}} || {{Percentage bar|39|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|26|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|35|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +13\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Mexico}} || {{Percentage bar|40|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|25|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|35|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +15\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|India}} || {{Percentage bar|43|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|27|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|30|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +16\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Germany}} || {{Percentage bar|51|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|34|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|15|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +17\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Peru}} || {{Percentage bar|41|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|21|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|38|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +20\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Brazil}} || {{Percentage bar|45|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|25|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|30|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +20\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Russia}} || {{Percentage bar|44|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|16|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|40|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +28\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Chile}} || {{Percentage bar|45|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|15|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|40|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +30\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Indonesia}} || {{Percentage bar|59|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|26|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|15|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +33\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Israel}} || {{Percentage bar|50|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|6|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|44|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +44\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Japan}} || {{Percentage bar|47|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|2|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|51|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +45\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Nigeria}} || {{Percentage bar|67|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|22|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|11|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +45\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|UK}} || {{Percentage bar|72|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|23|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|5|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +49\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|France}} || {{Percentage bar|72|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|20|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|8|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +52\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Australia}} || {{Percentage bar|73|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|18|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|9|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +54\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|South Korea}} || {{Percentage bar|74|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|14|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|12|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +60\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Kenya}} || {{Percentage bar|74|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|10|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|16|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +64\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Ghana}} || {{Percentage bar|78|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|9|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|13|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +69\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|Canada}} || {{Percentage bar|80|c=#80FF80|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|9|c=#FF8080|width=50}} || {{Percentage bar|11|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}} || +71\n|-\n| {{flagcountry|USA}} || {{Percentage bar|81|c=#80FF80|width=50}}||{{Percentage bar|10|c=#FF8080|width=50}}||{{Percentage bar|9|c=#F5F5DC|width=50}}|| +71\n|-\n|}\n</div>\n\n'''Anti-British sentiment''' is prejudice, fear or hatred against the [[Government of the United Kingdom|British Government]], the [[Culture of the United Kingdom|culture]] or the [[British people|people]] of the [[United Kingdom]], or its [[British Overseas Territories|Overseas Territories]].\n\n==Argentina==\n{{See also|Argentina\u2013United Kingdom relations|Falkland Islands sovereignty dispute|Argentina and England football rivalry}}\n\n[[File:Ushuaia - El Fin del Mundo (8319316181).jpg|thumb|Sign in [[Ushuaia]], Argentina some 700&nbsp;km from the [[Falkland Islands]]: \"Mooring by English pirates's ships is prohibited\".]]\nAnti-British feeling in Argentina originates mainly from two causes.\n\nThe first and older cause was the intervention of British [[Capitalism|capital]] and companies together with their disproportional political influence. This political influence is associated with the local [[oligarchy]] and its economic model based on the primary sector and commodities.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Scalabrini Ortiz|first=Raul|title=Pol\u00edtica Brit\u00e1nica en el R\u00edo de la Plata|publisher=La Biblioteca Argentina|year=1940|isbn=84-95594-76-5|location=Argentina|url=https://www.academia.edu/6597566/101809023-Politica-Britanica-en-el-Rio-de-la-Plata}}</ref>{{page needed|date=February 2020}} In turn, this led to controversial actions by successive Argentine governments such as the [[Roca\u2013Runciman Treaty]] and the [[Treaty of Madrid (1989)]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dipublico.org/4051/acuerdo-de-madrid-ii-declaracion-conjunta-de-las-delegaciones-de-la-republica-argentina-y-del-reino-unido-de-gran-bretana-e-irlanda-del-norte/|title=Acuerdo de Madrid II \u2013 Declaraci\u00f3n Conjunta de las delegaciones de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina y del Reino Unido de Gran Breta\u00f1a e Irlanda del Norte.|date=2010-06-24|website=Derecho Internacional P\u00fablico - www.dipublico.org|language=es|access-date=2019-05-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Falkland Enemies Resume Relations|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/02/16/world/falkland-enemies-resume-relations.html|work=The New York Times|date=16 February 1990|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171204114647/http://www.nytimes.com/1990/02/16/world/falkland-enemies-resume-relations.html|archivedate=4 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe second one is the [[Falkland Islands sovereignty dispute]] and the [[Falklands War]] in 1982 between Argentina and the United Kingdom. Due to this, anti-British and acts of vandalism do erupt.<ref>{{cite news |author=Ed Stocker |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |title=Argentina to see biggest anti-British protests for years |date=2 April 2010 |via=MercoPress |url=https://en.mercopress.com/2010/04/02/argentina-to-see-biggest-anti-british-protests-for-years}}</ref>\n\n==Ex-British colonies==\n{{main|British Raj|Indian independence movement}}\n{{see also|India\u2013United Kingdom relations}}\n\n[[File:A view of shops with anti-British and pro-Independence signs, possibly on Kings Street, Valetta, Malta (5074435957).jpg|thumb|A view of shops with anti-British and pro-Independence signs, Valletta, [[Malta]], c. 1960]]\nIn many ex-colonial territories, anti-British sentiment was particularly prevalent before and immediately after achieving independence but has ameliorated since.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nIn India, Pakistan and Bangladesh, the [[Indian independence movement]] encouraged this sentiment.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anti-British sentiment in India|url=http://www.tourismofindia.com/ff/history.htm|publisher=Tourism of India|accessdate=2 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Iran==\n{{See also|Iran\u2013United Kingdom relations}}\nAnti-British sentiment, sometimes described as Anglophobia, has been described as \"deeply entrenched in Iranian culture\",<ref name=guardian>Jonathan Freedland, [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2007/apr/04/comment.military \"If this crisis can be overcome, think about the negotiations that matter\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 4 April 2007. Accessed 24 November 2009.</ref> and reported to be increasingly prevalent in [[Iran]]. In July 2009, an adviser to [[Ayatollah]] [[Ali Khamenei]] called Britain \"worse than America\" for its alleged interference in Iran's post-election affairs.  In the first half of the 20th century, the [[British Empire]] exerted political influence over Iran (Persia) in order to control the profits from the [[Anglo-Persian Oil Company]]. As a result, British influence was widely known to have been behind the overthrow of the [[Qajar Dynasty]] in the 1920s, the subsequent rise of [[Rez\u0101 Sh\u0101h|Reza Shah Pahlavi]], and the [[1953 Iranian coup d'\u00e9tat|successful coup d'\u00e9tat]] overthrowing prime minister [[Mohammad Mosaddeq]] in 1953.<ref name=times>Ali Ansari, [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/columnists/guest_contributors/article6571685.ece \"Why Iran is obsessed with the British wily fox\"], ''[[The Times]]'', 25 June 2009. Accessed 24 November 2009.{{dead link|date=February 2020}}</ref><ref name=washingtonpost>Tara Bahrampour, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/16/AR2009071604126.html \"In Wake of Unrest, Britain Replacing U.S. as Iran's Great Satan\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', 17 July 2009. Accessed 24 November 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.ir-psri.com/Show.php?Page=ViewHighlight&HighlightID=126&SP=Farsi Conference on \"Iran and British colonialism\"], March 2008 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303151846/http://www.ir-psri.com/Show.php?Page=ViewHighlight&HighlightID=126&SP=Farsi |date=3 March 2012 }}. Accessed 24 November 2009</ref>\n\nOn Monday 9 August 2010, the senior Iranian minister and Iran's first vice president [[Mohammad Reza Rahimi]] declared that the British people were \"stupid\" and \"not human\". His remarks drew criticism from Simon Gass, the British ambassador in Iran, and also from the media in Britain.{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nIn November 2011 the Iranian parliament voted to downgrade relations with the UK after British sanctions were imposed on Iran due to its nuclear programme. Politicians reportedly shouted \"Death to Britain\".<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/iran/8908860/Iran-MPs-cry-Death-to-Britain-in-parliament.html \"Iran MPs cry 'Death to Britain' in parliament\"], ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', 23 November 2011. Accessed 27 May 2015.</ref> On 29 November 2011, Iranian students in Tehran stormed the British embassy, ransacked offices, smashed windows, shouted \"Death to England[sic]\" and burned the British flag.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!-- none--> |date=29 November 2011 |title=Iranian protesters storm UK embassy |publisher=Al Jazeera |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/middleeast/2011/11/20111129132554123213.html}}</ref>\n\nParts of the Iranian media campaigned against the reopening of the British Embassy in Tehran in August 2015, referring to Britain as an \"old fox\" &ndash; a term popularised by the Iranian writer [[Seyyed Ahmad Adib Pishavari]] (born [[Peshawar]] 1844, died Tehran 1930) &ndash; and accusing Britain of having provoked protests against the re-election of [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pourparsa |first1=Parham |title=Why is Britain an 'old fox' in Iranian media rhetoric? |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-34052821 |accessdate=15 May 2019 |publisher=BBC News |date=25 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Ireland==\n{{See also|Ireland\u2013United Kingdom relations}}\n[[File:An gorta Mor.jpg|thumb|270px|A [[Great Famine (Ireland)|Great Famine]] mural in Belfast. \"An Gorta M\u00f3r, Britain's genocide by starvation, Ireland's holocaust 1845\u20131849, over 1,500,000 deaths\".]]\nThere is a long tradition of anti-British sentiment, especially anti-English sentiment since the [[Norman invasion of Ireland]] and often more specifically [[Anglophobia]], within [[Irish nationalism]]. Much of this was grounded in the hostility felt by the largely Catholic poor for the Anglo-Irish gentry, which was mainly Anglican. In post-famine Ireland, anti-English hostility was adopted into the philosophy and foundation of the Irish nationalist movement. At the turn of the twentieth century, the Celtic Revival movement associated the search for a cultural and national identity with increasing anti-colonial and anti-English sentiment.\n\nA feeling of anti-English sentiment intensified within Irish nationalism during the Boer War leading to xenophobia underlined by Anglophobia. In 2011, tensions and anti-English or anti-British feelings flared in relation to the proposed state visit of [[Queen Elizabeth II]], the first British monarch to visit Ireland in 101 years. A republican demonstration was held at the GPO Dublin by a group of Irish Republicans on 26 February 2011, and a mock trial and decapitation of an effigy of Queen Elizabeth II were carried out by socialist republican group \u00c9ir\u00edg\u00ed. Other protests included one Dublin publican hanging a banner declaring \"the Queen will never be welcome in this country\"<ref>{{cite news |author=James Carroll |date=5 March 2011 |title=Sinn Fein's Gerry Adams slams Queen Elizabeth's upcoming visit to Ireland |website=IrishCentral |url=http://www.irishcentral.com/news/Sinn-Feins-Gerry-Adams-slams-Queen-Elizabeths-upcoming-visit-to-Ireland-117456423.html |accessdate=2013-11-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217083035/http://www.irishcentral.com/news/Sinn-Feins-Gerry-Adams-slams-Queen-Elizabeths-upcoming-visit-to-Ireland-117456423.html |archivedate=17 December 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> during her visit.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bates|first=Stephen|title=Queen shaken and stirred as Irish tour concludes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/may/20/queen-irish-tour-cork|date=20 May 2011|work=The Guardian|accessdate=17 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Israel==\n{{See also|Israel\u2013United Kingdom relations}}\nThe relationship between Israel and the UK is generally regarded as close and warm,<ref>{{cite news |author=Peter Osborne |date=12 December 2012 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |title=The cowardice at the heart of our relationship with Israel |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/israel/9740044/The-cowardice-at-the-heart-of-our-relationship-with-Israel.html}}</ref> and as a strategic partnership of the two nations.<ref>Sixty years of British-Israeli diplomatic relations' Organisation: Foreign & Commonwealth Office [https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/sixty-years-of-british-israeli-diplomatic-relations]</ref> According to the a [[BBC World Service]] poll in 2014,<ref name=\"BBC World Service poll\"/> five in ten Israelis (50%) have favourable attitudes to the UK, and only 6% of Israelis hold negative views towards the UK, the second lowest percentage after Japan.\n\nOccasional criticism is also found. In Israel, anti-British sentiment may historically stem from British rule and policies in the [[Mandatory Palestine|mandate era]], and in modern times from the perceived anti-Israel stance of the British media.<ref name=\"Jewish Mag Eurabia\">{{cite magazine |author=Alexander Maistrovoy |url=http://www.jewishmag.com/106mag/euroarabia/euroarabia.htm |title=Farewell to Albion, or path to Eurabia |magazine=The Jewish Magazine |date=September 2006 |accessdate=2010-06-01 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100507210623/http://www.jewishmag.com/106mag/euroarabia/euroarabia.htm| archivedate=7 May 2010 | url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Aish UK Antisemitism\">{{cite web |last=Rosenblum |first=Jonathan |url=http://www.aish.com/jw/s/48898202.html |title=UK Anti- Semitism |publisher=Aish.com |date=2005-06-04 |accessdate=2010-06-01| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100606214655/http://www.aish.com/jw/s/48898202.html| archivedate=6 June 2010 | url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Haaretz antisemitism doubled\">{{cite web|last=Liphshiz |first=Cnaan |url=https://www.haaretz.com/1.5081326 |title=Watchdog: British anti-Semitism doubled after Gaza war |work=Haaretz |date=24 July 2009|accessdate=2010-06-01}}</ref><ref name=\"ynetnews British Antisemitism\">{{cite news  |author=Eytan Gilboa |date=31 May 2006 |url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3257290,00.html |title=British anti-Semitism |work=Ynetnews |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nThe Jewish population of the United Kingdom was recorded as being 269,568 in the 2011 Census. Reacting to 609 anti-Semitic incidents across the UK in the first half of 2009,<ref name=\"Haaretz antisemitism doubled\" /> and to the announcement of numerous UK organizations to impose a boycott on Israel,<ref name=\"ynetnews British Antisemitism\" /> some Israelis claimed that the UK is anti-Israeli and [[Antisemitism|Antisemitic]].<ref name=\"Jewish Mag Eurabia\" /><ref name=\"Aish UK Antisemitism\" /> According to an opinion piece by Eytan Gilboa, \"the British media systematically supports the Palestinians, and openly slants its reporting about Israel and Israeli policy. The left-wing Guardian and Independent newspapers regularly print accusatory, anti-Israel editorials, and their correspondents in Israel file biased, and occasionally false, reports. The supposedly prestigious BBC has long been a sounding board to trumpet Palestinian propaganda.\"<ref name=\"ynetnews British Antisemitism\" /> In 2010 Ron Breiman, a former chairman of the right-wing organisation \"Professors for a Strong Israel\", claimed in one of Israel's leading newspapers, ''[[Haaretz]]'', that the United Kingdom has raised and armed Israel's enemies in Jordan and the Arab Legion and described the British media as anti-Israeli.<ref>{{cite news |author=Ron Breiman |date=2 March 2010 |title=End British obsession with anti-Israel propaganda |newspaper=Haaretz |url=https://www.haaretz.com/1.5035718}}</ref>\n\nReacting to the UK government's decision to expel an Israeli diplomat because of Mossad's cloning of 12 British passports for [[Assassination of Mahmoud Al-Mabhouh|an assassination operation]] in 2010, former National Union members of the [[Knesset|Israeli parliament]] [[Michael Ben-Ari]] and [[Aryeh Eldad]] accused the British government of being \"anti-semitic\" and referred to them as \"dogs\".<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article7073250.ece Times Online - 'Israeli diplomat 'spy' expelled over cloned UK passports']{{dead link|date=February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.allvoices.com/contributed-news/5472570-british-antisemitic-dogs-israel |title=British Anti-Semitic Dogs - Israel |access-date=8 April 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726215803/http://www.allvoices.com/contributed-news/5472570-british-antisemitic-dogs-israel |archive-date=26 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Spain==\n{{See also|Disputed status of the isthmus between Gibraltar and Spain|Disputed status of Gibraltar|Telecom dispute between Gibraltar and Spain}}\nAnti-British sentiments evolved in Spain following the ceding of [[Gibraltar]] to the British through the [[Treaty of Utrecht]] in 1713 following the [[War of the Spanish Succession]].{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} In August 2013, Spain was considering forging an alliance with Argentina over the status of the [[Falkland Islands]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/gibraltar/10235937/Gibraltar-Spain-considers-joint-diplomatic-offensive-with-Argentina-over-Falkland-Islands.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Fiona | last=Govan | title=Gibraltar: Spain considers joint diplomatic offensive with Argentina over Falkland Islands | date=11 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==United States==\n{{See also|United Kingdom\u2013United States relations|Special Relationship}}\n[[File:NOLA BP Oil Flood Protest Union Jack stand.JPG|thumb|180px|American protester stands on a [[Union Flag]], presumably associating petroleum company [[BP]] with the [[United Kingdom]]; before adopting the initials \"BP\" as its official corporate name and brand, BP was known as British Petroleum.]]\nPresident [[Thomas Jefferson]] complained of an unreasonable hostility towards the British state by the people in the United States during the [[Napoleonic Wars]], brought about by the [[American Revolutionary War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cooperativeindividualism.org/jefferson_f_01.html|title=Anglophobia|publisher=Allwords.com|accessdate=2008-07-20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704155036/http://www.cooperativeindividualism.org/jefferson_f_01.html|archivedate=4 July 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[anti-Tom]] novel ''[[Tit for Tat (1856 novel)|Tit for Tat]]'' (written anonymously in 1856 by \"A Lady of New Orleans\") encouraged anti-British sentiment in reaction to Britain's positive reception of the anti-slavery novel ''[[Uncle Tom's Cabin]]'' by [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iath.virginia.edu/utc/proslav/titfortathp.html |title=Tit For Tat |publisher=Iath.virginia.edu |accessdate=2010-06-01}}</ref>\n\nDuring the World War II alliance, anti-British sentiment took different forms. In May 1942, when conditions were highly problematic for British prospects, American journalist [[Edward R. Murrow]] privately gave a British friend an analysis of the sources of persistent anti-British sentiment in the United States. He attributed it especially to:\n:partly the hard-core of anglophobes (Irish, Germans and isolationists); partly the frustration produced by war without early victories; partly our bad behaviour at Singapore; and partly the tendency common to all countries at war to blame their allies for doing nothing.<ref>Diary entry of 11 May 1942 in Nigel Nicolson, ed. ''Harold Nicolson: the War Years 1939-1945'' (1967) 2:226.</ref>\n\nSenior American military officers often tried, with little success, to push against Roosevelt support for Britain. [[Fleet Admiral]] [[Ernest King]] had been noted for these views which affected his decision-making during the \"[[Second Happy Time]]\" (in the [[Battle of the Atlantic]]).<ref>{{cite book|last=Moser|first=John E.|title=Twisting the Lion's Tail: American Anglophobia Between the World Wars|publisher=New York University Press|location=New York|date=1998-11-01|isbn=0-8147-5615-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nKLXHQAACAAJ&dq=Twisting+the+Lion%27s+Tail:+American+Anglophobia+Between+the+World+Wars|accessdate=2008-07-20}}</ref> [[Joseph Stilwell]], a four-star general in the China, Burma and India theatre of the [[Second World War]] was another noted for anti British views (for example, in this diaries he wrote, \"Boy, will this burn up the Limeys!\" when Myitkyina was finally taken). Curiously, he got on well with British military commander [[William Slim]], even volunteering to serve under him for a time rather than under [[George Giffard]]. Slim noted that Stilwell had a public persona that differed from his private relations.\n\nIn the 21st century, the [[Special Relationship]] between the United States and the United Kingdom has come under attack by advertising executive Steven A. Grasse who published ''[[The Evil Empire: 101 Ways That England Ruined the World]]'',<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0tkjhI2JiTwC&dq=%22The+Evil+Empire:+101+Ways+That+England+Ruined+The+World%22&printsec=frontcover&source=bn&hl=en&ei=W9PgSYunF5aqjAeBoLnUDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4 |title=Evil Empire: 101 Ways That England Ruined the World |publisher=Quirk Books |date=2007 |accessdate=2010-06-01 |author=Steven A. Grasse, Penny Rimbaud}}</ref> although this work is partly tongue in cheek and forms part of a larger media project launched by the author.\n\n[[Roland Emmerich]]'s [[2000 in film|2000]] movie ''[[The Patriot (2000 film)|The Patriot]]'' drew controversy for demonising the British army,<ref>{{cite news|last=Morris|first=Mark|title=Mel Gibson: Proud or prejudiced? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/jul/16/comment.features|date=16 July 2000|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> and misrepresenting [[armed forces of the United Kingdom|British forces]] depicted as engaging in savagery &ndash; such as the burning of a church with civilians inside &ndash; in the [[Thirteen Colonies]] during the [[American Revolution]].  [[Liverpool City Council]] went on to claim that the film misrepresented British officer [[Banastre Tarleton]] and sought an apology from the producers.<ref><!--no author available-->[https://www.theguardian.com/film/2000/jun/30/news.melgibson \"Patriotic Liverpool up in arms over Gibson's blockbuster\"], ''The Guardian'', 3 June 2000. Retrieved 19 January 2015</ref> Other commentators noted that a similar incident was committed by German troops in the [[Oradour-sur-Glane massacre]] in [[World War II]], and suggested that the film producers may have had, consciously or subconsciously, an anti-British agenda in changing the nationalities and relocating the event to an earlier and different conflict<ref>{{cite news|last=Foreman|first=Jonathan|title=The Nazis, er, the Redcoats are coming! |url=http://www.salon.com/2000/07/03/patriot_3/|date=3 July 2000|publisher=Salon.com|accessdate=19 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Von Tunzelmann|first=Alex|title=The Patriot: more flag-waving rot with Mel Gibson|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2009/jul/22/the-patriot-mel-gibson-reel-history|date=23 July 2009|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref> and one stated that it was similar to a \"[[blood libel]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Foreman|first=Johnathan|title=The film that says we're Nazis|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/4252781/The-film-that-says-were-Nazis.html|date=6 July 2000|work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=20 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==<!-- New links in alphabetical order please -->\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Anti-German sentiment]]\n* [[Anti-Irish sentiment]]\n* [[Anti-Russian sentiment]]\n* [[Sweden-bashing|Anti-Swedish Sentiment]]\n* [[Antisemitism]]\n* [[Consequences of Nazism]]\n* [[German American]]\n* [[Germanophilia]]\n* [[Internment of German Americans]]\n* [[List of terms used for Germans]]\n* [[Stalag fiction]]\n* [[Stereotypes of Germans]]\n* [[Operation Bolivar]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cultural criticism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anti-British Sentiment}}\n[[Category:Anti-national sentiment|British Discrimination]]\n[[Category:Anti-British sentiment| ]]\n", "name_user": "117.217.88.183", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti-British_sentiment"}
{"title_page": "June Lloyd, Baroness Lloyd of Highbury", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Baroness June Kathleen Lloyd \n|image             = File:Lady June Lloyd of Highbury.jpg\n|image_size        = 200px\n|caption           = \n|birth_date        = {{Birth date|1928|1|1|df=yes}} \n|birth_place       = [[Gilgit]], [[Kashmir]]\n|death_date        = {{Death date and age|2006|6|28|1928|1|1|df=yes}}\n|death_place       = [[Aylesbury]], UK\n|residence         =\n|citizenship       =\n|nationality       = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|ethnicity         =\n|field             = [[Metabolic disorder]]s<ref name=\"munk\"/>\n|work_institutions = [[University of Birmingham]],<br>[[Great Ormond Street Hospital]],<br> [[Institute of Child Health]], <br> [[St George's Hospital Medical School]]\n|alma_mater        = [[University of Bristol]]\n|doctoral_advisor  =\n|doctoral_students =\n|known_for         = For discovering that the rare [[Metabolic disorder|metabolic disease]] [[oQ-betalipoproteinaemia]] could be avoided by the use of [[Vitamin E]].<br><br> The discovering the role of [[lipid metabolism]]<br>For the establishment of the [[Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health]].\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences        =\n|influenced        =\n|prizes            = [[Commander (order)|Dame Commander]] of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire,<br> [[DSc]] and a [[Life peer]] in 1996\n|footnotes         =\n|signature         =\n}}\n'''June Kathleen Lloyd, Baroness Lloyd of Highbury''', [[Order of the British Empire|DBE]], [[Fellow of the Royal College of Physicians|FRCP]], [[Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh|FRCP Edin]], [[Royal College of General Practitioners|FRCGP]]  (1 January 1928 &ndash; 28 June 2006) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[paediatrician]] and, in retirement, a [[cross-bencher|cross bench]] member of the [[House of Lords]]. June Lloyd was a determined advocate for children's health and was instrumental in the establishment of the [[Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health]] in 1996 when it gained its royal status.<ref name=\"munk\">{{cite journal|title=Lionel Sharples Penrose Moncrieff|journal=Munks Roll \u2013 Lives of the Fellows|date=10 July 2006|volume=XII |url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/5814 |accessdate=19 January 2018|publisher=Royal College of Physicians|location=Royal College of Physicians}}</ref><ref name=\"guard\">{{cite news|last1=Wolstenholme|first1=Gordon|title=Lady Lloyd of Highbury|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2006/jul/11/guardianobituaries.mainsection|accessdate=19 January 2018|agency=The Guardian|date=11 July 2006}}</ref> She was also known for discovering that the damage caused to patients by the rare [[Metabolic disorder|metabolic disease]] [[oQ-betalipoproteinaemia]] could be avoided by the use of [[Vitamin E]].<ref name=\"bi\">{{cite web|title=Professor Dame June Lloyd|url=https://www.rcpch.ac.uk/paediatrician/professor-dame-june-lloyd|website=The Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref> She was also known for discovering the role of [[lipid metabolism]] in health and disease in childhood, which was original and difficult to investigate at that time.<ref name=\"bi\"/>\n\n==Early life and education==\nLloyd was born in [[Gilgit, Pakistan|Gilgit]], [[Kashmir]],<ref name=\"lance\">{{cite journal|title=Obituary - June Lloyd (Baroness Lloyd of Highbury)|journal=The Lancet|date=12 August 2006|volume=368|issue=9535|page=574|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(06)69185-X|url=http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(06)69185-X/fulltext|accessdate=19 January 2018|last1=Boseley|first1=Sarah}}</ref> where her father was a [[Major]] in the [[Royal Indian Army Service Corps]]. She remained in [[India]] until 1936, when her family returned to [[England]]. She was educated at the [[Royal High School, Bath|Royal High School]] in [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], where she became [[head girl]]. She read [[medicine]] at the [[University of Bristol]], winning honours with distinction and a gold medal.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Craft |first1=Alan |title=June Kathleen, Baroness Lloyd of Highbury Lloyd |journal=Munks Roll \u2013 Lives of the Fellows |date=9 February 2014 |volume=XII |url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/5814 |accessdate=5 July 2018 |publisher=Royal College of Physicians}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShe joined the [[Royal College of Physicians]] in 1954.  After further study in [[South Shields]], Bristol, [[Plymouth]], [[Oxford]], [[Manchester]] and [[Durham, England|Durham]], she became research assistant to [[Otto Herbert Wolff]] in [[Birmingham]]. She taught at the [[University of Birmingham]] from 1958 to 1965, specialising in [[metabolic disorder]]s in children, particularly [[diabetes mellitus]] and [[childhood obesity]].\n\nIn 1965, she followed Wolff to [[Great Ormond Street Hospital]]<ref name=\"lance\"/> in [[London]], and the associated [[Institute of Child Health]] at [[University College London]] where she became a senior lecturer, later a [[Reader (academic rank)|reader]] and finally [[professor]].\n\nLloyd was appointed professor of child health and head of a new department of paediatrics at [[St George's Hospital Medical School]]<ref name=\"lance\"/> in London in 1975, and returned to Great Ormond Street in 1985 as [[Nuffield Professor of Child Health]]. She served with distinction on many committees.  She was the first female president of the [[British Paediatric Association]] from 1988 to 1991, and was a vice-president of the [[Royal College of Physicians]] from 1992 to 1995.\n\n===Establishment of the RCPCH===\nLloyd retired from practising medicine in 1992, but played a role in transforming the British Paediatric Association (abbr. BPA) into the Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health. It was oriinally thought that Lloyd would become president of the BPA, after being honorary secretary for a number of years,<ref name=\"munk\"/> but Lloyd believed that the paediatricians should have their own college.<ref name=\"lance\"/> She was a member of an influential group with the BPA, which enabled her to push for the establishment of a new college. It was a contentious issue, as many in the profession believed it was not necessary, and there was serious differences of opinion, when looking in hindsight<ref name=\"lance\"/> Sir [[Peter Tizard]] and his research group at [[Hammersmith Hospital]], were one group of dissenting voices, who believed that Paediatrics should have the same intellectual footing for medicine for children, as medicine for adults, within general medicine, rather than a speciality.<ref>{{cite journal |title=John Peter Mills (Sir) Tizard |journal=Munks Roll \u2013 Lives of the Fellows|date=21 August 2013 |volume=IX |page=518 |url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/4451 |accessdate=21 December 2017|publisher=Royal College of Physicians|location=Royal College of Physicians |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101030024/http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/6350|archivedate=1 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, it was thanks to her, and people like the great Otto Wolff and [[Roy Meadow]] who were aligned with her ideal that the argument was won. Roy Meadow would become the first president,<ref name=\"lance\"/> but she would feature on the [[coat of arms]] of the new college, in which she is a [[supporter]] holding a [[staff of Aesculapius]] entwined with a [[double helix]] rather than the traditional [[snake]].<ref name=\"munk\"/><!--Can we get a year for the granting of arms?-->  The other supporter was [[Thomas Phaire]], whose ''Boke of Chyldren'' from 1545 was the first book on paediatrics in [[English language|English]], the [[crest (heraldry)|crest]] is a baby, taken from the arms of the [[Foundling Hospital]] in [[Coram's Fields]].<ref name=\"munk\"/> Lloyd took over responsibility for training and standards for paediatricians that had previously been under the control of the Royal College of Physicians.<ref name=\"lance\"/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* Appointed a [[Order of the British Empire|DBE]] in 1990\n* Honorary [[DSc]] from Bristol University in 1991\n* Honorary DSc from Birmingham University in 1993\n* Awarded the [[James Spence Medal]] in 1993\n* [[Life peer]] as '''Baroness Lloyd of Highbury''', of Highbury in the [[London Borough of Islington]] in 1996.\n\n==Later life and death==\nA severe [[stroke]] before her introduction to the House of Lords prevented her taking her seat until 1998. Her resulting disability left her unable to become an active member of the House. She died on 28 June 2006, aged 78. She had never married. Her brother, Philip Lloyd, was a [[Commander]] in the [[Royal Navy]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.rcpch.ac.uk/ The Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health]\n\n{{James Spence Medal winners}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lloyd of Highbury, June Lloyd, Baroness}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century British medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers]]\n[[Category:Dames Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in England]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:British paediatricians]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:People educated at the Royal High School, Bath]]\n[[Category:British women medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Academics of University College London]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the James Spence Medal]]\n[[Category:20th-century women physicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Baroness June Kathleen Lloyd \n|image             = File:Lady June Lloyd of Highbury.jpg\n|image_size        = 200px\n|caption           = \n|birth_date        = {{Birth date|1928|1|1|df=yes}} \n|birth_place       = [[Gilgit]], [[Kashmir]]\n|death_date        = {{Death date and age|2006|6|28|1928|1|1|df=yes}}\n|death_place       = [[Aylesbury]], UK\n|residence         =\n|citizenship       =\n|nationality       = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|ethnicity         =\n|field             = [[Metabolic disorder]]s<ref name=\"munk\"/>\n|work_institutions = [[University of Birmingham]],<br>[[Great Ormond Street Hospital]],<br> [[Institute of Child Health]], <br> [[St George's Hospital Medical School]]\n|alma_mater        = [[University of Bristol]]\n|doctoral_advisor  =\n|doctoral_students =\n|known_for         = For discovering that the rare [[Metabolic disorder|metabolic disease]] [[oQ-betalipoproteinaemia]] could be avoided by the use of [[Vitamin E]].<br><br> The discovering the role of [[lipid metabolism]]<br>For the establishment of the [[Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health]].\n|author_abbrev_bot =\n|author_abbrev_zoo =\n|influences        =\n|influenced        =\n|prizes            = [[Commander (order)|Dame Commander]] of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire,<br> [[DSc]] and a [[Life peer]] in 1996\n|footnotes         =\n|signature         =\n}}\n'''June Kathleen Lloyd, Baroness Lloyd of Highbury''', [[Order of the British Empire|DBE]], [[Fellow of the Royal College of Physicians|FRCP]], [[Royal College of Physicians of Edinburgh|FRCP Edin]], [[Royal College of General Practitioners|FRCGP]]  (1 January 1928 &ndash; 28 June 2006) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[paediatrician]] and, in retirement, a [[cross-bencher|cross bench]] member of the [[House of Lords]]. June Lloyd was a determined advocate for children\u2019s health and was instrumental in the establishment of the [[Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health]] in 1996 when it gained its royal status.<ref name=\"munk\">{{cite journal|title=Lionel Sharples Penrose Moncrieff|journal=Munks Roll \u2013 Lives of the Fellows|date=10 July 2006|volume=XII |url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/5814 |accessdate=19 January 2018|publisher=Royal College of Physicians|location=Royal College of Physicians}}</ref><ref name=\"guard\">{{cite news|last1=Wolstenholme|first1=Gordon|title=Lady Lloyd of Highbury|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2006/jul/11/guardianobituaries.mainsection|accessdate=19 January 2018|agency=The Guardian|date=11 July 2006}}</ref> She was also known for discovering that the damage caused to patients by the rare [[Metabolic disorder|metabolic disease]] [[oQ-betalipoproteinaemia]] could be avoided by the use of [[Vitamin E]].<ref name=\"bi\">{{cite web|title=Professor Dame June Lloyd|url=https://www.rcpch.ac.uk/paediatrician/professor-dame-june-lloyd|website=The Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref> She was also known for discovering the role of [[lipid metabolism]] in health and disease in childhood, which was original and difficult to investigate at that time.<ref name=\"bi\"/>\n\n==Early life and education==\nLloyd was born in [[Gilgit, Pakistan|Gilgit]], [[Kashmir]],<ref name=\"lance\">{{cite journal|title=Obituary - June Lloyd (Baroness Lloyd of Highbury)|journal=The Lancet|date=12 August 2006|volume=368|issue=9535|page=574|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(06)69185-X|url=http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(06)69185-X/fulltext|accessdate=19 January 2018|last1=Boseley|first1=Sarah}}</ref> where her father was a [[Major]] in the [[Royal Indian Army Service Corps]]. She remained in [[India]] until 1936, when her family returned to [[England]]. She was educated at the [[Royal High School, Bath|Royal High School]] in [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], where she became [[head girl]]. She read [[medicine]] at the [[University of Bristol]], winning honours with distinction and a gold medal.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Craft |first1=Alan |title=June Kathleen, Baroness Lloyd of Highbury Lloyd |journal=Munks Roll \u2013 Lives of the Fellows |date=9 February 2014 |volume=XII |url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/5814 |accessdate=5 July 2018 |publisher=Royal College of Physicians}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShe joined the [[Royal College of Physicians]] in 1954.  After further study in [[South Shields]], Bristol, [[Plymouth]], [[Oxford]], [[Manchester]] and [[Durham, England|Durham]], she became research assistant to [[Otto Herbert Wolff]] in [[Birmingham]]. She taught at the [[University of Birmingham]] from 1958 to 1965, specialising in [[metabolic disorder]]s in children, particularly [[diabetes mellitus]] and [[childhood obesity]].\n\nIn 1965, she followed Wolff to [[Great Ormond Street Hospital]]<ref name=\"lance\"/> in [[London]], and the associated [[Institute of Child Health]] at [[University College London]] where she became a senior lecturer, later a [[Reader (academic rank)|reader]] and finally [[professor]].\n\nLloyd was appointed professor of child health and head of a new department of paediatrics at [[St George's Hospital Medical School]]<ref name=\"lance\"/> in London in 1975, and returned to Great Ormond Street in 1985 as [[Nuffield Professor of Child Health]]. She served with distinction on many committees.  She was the first female president of the [[British Paediatric Association]] from 1988 to 1991, and was a vice-president of the [[Royal College of Physicians]] from 1992 to 1995.\n\n===Establishment of the RCPCH===\nLloyd retired from practising medicine in 1992, but played a role in transforming the British Paediatric Association (abbr. BPA) into the Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health. It was oriinally thought that Lloyd would become president of the BPA, after being honorary secretary for a number of years,<ref name=\"munk\"/> but Lloyd believed that the paediatricians should have their own college.<ref name=\"lance\"/> She was a member of an influential group with the BPA, which enabled her to push for the establishment of a new college. It was a contentious issue, as many in the profession believed it was not necessary, and there was serious differences of opinion, when looking in hindsight<ref name=\"lance\"/> Sir [[Peter Tizard]] and his research group at [[Hammersmith Hospital]], were one group of dissenting voices, who believed that Paediatrics should have the same intellectual footing for medicine for children, as medicine for adults, within general medicine, rather than a speciality.<ref>{{cite journal |title=John Peter Mills (Sir) Tizard |journal=Munks Roll \u2013 Lives of the Fellows|date=21 August 2013 |volume=IX |page=518 |url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/4451 |accessdate=21 December 2017|publisher=Royal College of Physicians|location=Royal College of Physicians |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101030024/http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/6350|archivedate=1 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, it was thanks to her, and people like the great Otto Wolff and [[Roy Meadow]] who were aligned with her ideal that the argument was won. Roy Meadow would become the first president,<ref name=\"lance\"/> but she would feature on the [[coat of arms]] of the new college, in which she is a [[supporter]] holding a [[staff of Aesculapius]] entwined with a [[double helix]] rather than the traditional [[snake]].<ref name=\"munk\"/><!--Can we get a year for the granting of arms?-->  The other supporter was [[Thomas Phaire]], whose ''Boke of Chyldren'' from 1545 was the first book on paediatrics in [[English language|English]], the [[crest (heraldry)|crest]] is a baby, taken from the arms of the [[Foundling Hospital]] in [[Coram's Fields]].<ref name=\"munk\"/> Lloyd took over responsibility for training and standards for paediatricians that had previously been under the control of the Royal College of Physicians.<ref name=\"lance\"/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n* Appointed a [[Order of the British Empire|DBE]] in 1990\n* Honorary [[DSc]] from Bristol University in 1991\n* Honorary DSc from Birmingham University in 1993\n* Awarded the [[James Spence Medal]] in 1993\n* [[Life peer]] as '''Baroness Lloyd of Highbury''', of Highbury in the [[London Borough of Islington]] in 1996.\n\n==Later life and death==\nA severe [[stroke]] before her introduction to the House of Lords prevented her taking her seat until 1998. Her resulting disability left her unable to become an active member of the House. She died on 28 June 2006, aged 78. She had never married. Her brother, Philip Lloyd, was a [[Commander]] in the [[Royal Navy]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.rcpch.ac.uk/ The Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health]\n\n{{James Spence Medal winners}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lloyd of Highbury, June Lloyd, Baroness}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century British medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers]]\n[[Category:Dames Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in England]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:British paediatricians]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:People educated at the Royal High School, Bath]]\n[[Category:British women medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Academics of University College London]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the James Spence Medal]]\n[[Category:20th-century women physicians]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/June_Lloyd,_Baroness_Lloyd_of_Highbury"}
{"title_page": "Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen", "text_new": "{{for|the Danish Olympic athlete|Niels Pedersen (athlete)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist<!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen\n| image            = NH\u00d8P.jpg\n| caption          = \n| image_size       = 300px\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = NH\u00d8P, The Great Dane with <br />the Never-Ending Name\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1946|5|27}}\n| birth_place      = [[Osted]], [[Zealand]], Denmark\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|df=yes|2005|4|19|1946|5|27}}\n| death_place      = [[Ish\u00f8j]], Zealand\n| instrument       = [[Double-bass|Upright bass]]\n| genre            = [[Jazz]], [[bebop]], [[hard bop]], [[avant-garde jazz]]\n| occupation       = Musician, composer\n| years_active     = 1960s\u20132005\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Albert Ayler]], [[Chet Baker]], [[Count Basie]], [[Kenny Drew]], [[Roy Eldridge]], [[Bill Evans]], [[Stan Getz]], [[Dizzy Gillespie]], [[Dexter Gordon]], [[Milt Jackson]], [[Slide Hampton]], [[Roland Kirk]], [[Tete Montoliu]], [[Joe Pass]], [[Oscar Peterson]], [[Jean-Luc Ponty]], [[Sonny Rollins]], [[George Shearing]], [[Archie Shepp]], [[Ben Webster]]\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen''' ({{IPA-da|ne\u031dls\u02c8hene\u031d\u014b \u02c8\u0276\u0250\u032fste\u00f0 \u02c8p\u02b0e\u00f0\u0250sn\u0329}}, 27 May 1946 \u2013 19 April 2005), often known as '''NH\u00d8P''', was a Danish [[jazz]] [[double bassist|upright bassist]] known for his technique and musical approach.<ref name=politiken>{{cite web\n |url        = http://politiken.dk/kultur/ECE111233/bassisten-niels-henning-oersted-pedersen-er-doed\n |title      = Bassisten Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen er d\u00f8d\n |language   = Danish\n |publisher  = [[Politiken]]\n |date       = 20 April 2005\n |accessdate = 2014-11-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Yanow |first=Scott |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p85979/biography|pure_url=yes}} |title=Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen |work=Biography |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |date= |accessdate=2014-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\u00d8rsted Pedersen was born in [[Osted]], near [[Roskilde]], on the Danish island of [[Zealand (Denmark)|Zealand]], the son of a church organist. As a child, \u00d8rsted Pedersen played piano, but from the age of 13, he started learning to play [[double bass|upright bass]] and at the age of 14, while studying, he began his professional jazz career in Denmark with his first band, Jazzkvintet 60 ([[Danish language|Danish]] for Jazz Quintet 60). By the age of fifteen, he had the ability to accompany leading musicians at nightclubs, working regularly at Copenhagen's [[Jazzhus Montmartre]], after his debut there on New Year's Eve 1961, when he was only 15. When seventeen, he had already turned down an offer to join the [[Count Basie]] orchestra, mainly because he was too young to get legal permission to live and work as a musician in the United States.\n\nThe Montmartre was a regular stop-off for touring American Jazz stars, and as a member of the house band, the young \u00d8rsted Pedersen performed with saxophonists such as [[Sonny Rollins]], [[Dexter Gordon]], [[Rahsaan Roland Kirk]] and [[Stan Getz]], and pianist [[Bill Evans]], with whom he toured in Europe in 1965. During the 1960s, \u00d8rsted Pedersen played with a series of other important American jazzmen who were touring or resident in Denmark, including [[Ben Webster]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statsbiblioteket.dk/search/showrecord.jsp?record_id=sb_3197543|title=''\u00d8rsted Pedersen Recording With Ben Webster 1965\u201371''|publisher=Danish National Library, statsbiblioteket.dk|accessdate=2010-10-13}}</ref> [[Brew Moore]], [[Bud Powell]], [[Count Basie]], [[Roy Eldridge]], [[Dizzy Gillespie]], [[Jackie McLean]], and vocalist [[Ella Fitzgerald]]. He also played with [[Jean-Luc Ponty]], and became the bassist of choice whenever a big-name musician was touring Copenhagen.\n\nHe was awarded Best Bass Player of the Year by [[Down Beat|Downbeat]] Critics' Poll in 1981.<ref name=downbeat>{{cite web\n |url        = http://www.downbeat.com/default.asp?sect=stories&subsect=story_detail&sid=707\n |title      = 1981 DownBeat Critics Poll\n |publisher  = Downbeat.com\n |date       = 31 August 1981\n |accessdate = 2014-11-07}}</ref>\n\n\u00d8rsted Pedersen worked in duo and trio arrangements with pianist [[Kenny Drew]], recording over 50 albums together. He also worked with [[St\u00e9phane Grappelli]] and [[Joe Pass]] and recorded extensively as a leader. His best known songs are \"My Little Anna\", \"Jaywalkin'\", and \"The Puzzle\", as well as jazz arrangements of traditional Danish folk songs. A duo performance with [[Rune Gustafsson]] at [[Vossajazz]] 1980, concluded on the album ''Just The Way You Are'' on the label Sonet Gramofon, recorded half a year after this first meeting. He was awarded the [[Nordic Council Music Prize]] in 1991. This was the first time this prize for composition was awarded to a performing musician, and this must be ascribed to his great international standing. He was presumably the most sought-after Danish instrumentalist internationally ever, and had traveled and recorded with a series of the greatest jazz soloists internationally.\n\n\u00d8rsted Pedersen also had a particular ability to interpret Danish songs and folk melodies. He often played within trio ensembles, partly collectively with the trumpeter [[Palle Mikkelborg]] and the keyboard player [[Kenneth Knudsen]], and partly under his own name, usually with guitarists like [[Philip Catherine]] and [[Ulf Wakenius]]. In 1999, he co-led a duo with pianist [[Mulgrew Miller]], touring Europe, Japan, Australia, and Korea. This format was later enlarged into a trio featuring drummer [[Alvin Queen]]. This trio remained intact until Pedersen's death.<ref name=politiken/>\n\n== Death ==\n\n\u00d8rsted Pedersen died of heart failure in 2005 at the age of 58 in [[Copenhagen]], Denmark. He was survived by his wife, Solveig, and his three children.<ref>\"N-H. Orsted Pedersen, 58, Bassist in Danish Jazz Scene, Dies\" (21 April 2005) ''New York Times''</ref>\n[[Oscar Peterson]] wrote: \n{{Quote box\n| bgcolor=#EEEEEE\n| quoted=true\n| quote = After hearing this phenomenal talent on bass, I realized that somehow, someday we should meet, thereby giving me the opportunity to also play with him. This vision and thought took place in the early 1970s, when I was fortunate enough to be able to invite him to join my then trio.\n\nAllow me to express my reaction to his playing this way: First and foremost, he never got in my way--but he also had such a great musical perception of what I was trying to do that he served to greatly inspire me from a spontaneous aspect. I came off walking on Cloud 3000 that evening because of Niels' musical contribution. He had the most phenomenal technique, coupled with incredible harmonic perception, along with impeccable time. I shall never forget that evening.\n\nAlmost from that evening on, we became very close friends, not just musically but most certainly personally, for I developed a great admiration for the depth of Niels' political, geographical and personal understandings. He was a man who had an almost unbelievable wealth of historic cognizance pertaining to European history. He also had a very kindred spirit as a human being, always able to easily make good friends, should he care to do so.\n | source =Oscar Peterson, writing in ''Jazztimes''.<ref>{{cite web\n |last       = Peterson\n |first      = Oscar\n |url        = http://jazztimes.com/articles/25476-niels-henning-orsted-pedersen\n |title      = Niels-Henning Orsted Pedersen (5.27.46\u20134.19.05)\n |publisher  = Jazztimes.com\n |year       = 2006\n |accessdate = 2010-12-09}}</ref>\n | width     = 80%\n | qalign    = left\n | salign    = right\n | align     = center\n}}\n\n== Honors ==\n*1974: Grammy Award. Best Jazz Performance by a Group, The Trio - Oscar Peterson, Joe Pass and Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen\n*1981: Best Bass Player of the Year by [[Down Beat|Downbeat]] Critics' Poll<ref name=downbeat/>\n*1991: [[Nordic Council Music Prize]]\n\n== Discography ==\n{{main|Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen discography}}\n'''As leader/co-leader'''\n*1973: ''[[Duo (Kenny Drew and Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen album)|Duo]]'' ([[Steeplechase Records|SteepleChase]]) with [[Kenny Drew]]\n*1976: ''[[Jaywalkin']]'' ([[SteepleChase Records|SteepleChase]])\n*1976: ''[[Double Bass (album)|Double Bass]]'' (SteepleChase) with [[Sam Jones (musician)|Sam Jones]]\n*1976: ''[[Pictures (Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen and Kenneth Knudsen album)|Pictures]]'' (SteepleChase), with Kenneth Knudsen\n*1977: ''[[Trio 1]]'' (SteepleChase) with [[Philip Catherine]] and [[Billy Hart]]\n*1977: ''Trio 2'' (SteepleChase) with Philip Catherine and Billy Hart\n*1979: ''[[Dancing on the Tables]]'' (SteepleChase)\n*1981: ''[[Just the Way You Are (album)|Just the Way You Are]]'' ([[Sonet Records|Sonet]]), with [[Rune Gustafsson]]\n*1982: ''[[Face to Face (Tete Montoliu and Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen album)|Face to Face]]'' (SteepleChase), duo with [[Tete Montoliu]]\n*1983: ''The Viking'' ([[Pablo Records|Pablo]]), with [[Philip Catherine]]\n*1984: ''The Eternal Traveller'' (Pablo)\n*1986: ''[[Looking at Bird]]'' (SteepleChase) with [[Archie Shepp]]\n*1992: ''Uncharted Land'' (Pladecompagniet)\n*1993: ''Ambiance'' ([[Dacapo Records|Dacapo]])\n*1993: ''To a Brother'' (Pladekompagniet), NH\u00d8P Trio including with [[Ulf Wakenius]] & [[Adam Nussbaum]]\n*1995: ''Scandinavian Wood'' (Caprice)\n*1996: ''Those Who Were'' ([[Polygram Records|Polygram]])\n*1997: ''Friends Forever'' ([[Milestone Records|Milestone]])\n*1998: ''This Is All I Ask'' ([[Verve Records|Verve]])\n*1998: ''In the Name of Music'' (BMG Denmark), NH\u00d8P & [[Trio Rococo]]\n*2005: ''Friends Forever'' (Sony BMG Music Entertainment Denmark), compilation\n*2007: ''The Unforgettable NH\u00d8P Trio Live'' ([[ACT Music]]), including with Ulf Wakenius & [[Jonas Johansen (musician)|Jonas Johansen]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of jazz bassists]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{commons category}}\n*\"Scandinavian Wood\": The musical career of Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen in the light of his discography by J\u00f8rgen Mathiasen. Books on Demand 2010. {{ISBN|978-3-8423-5157-8}}.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/news/2005/may/21/guardianobituaries.arts Niels-Henning Orsted Pedersen \u2013 Danish virtuoso bassist who kept pace with Oscar Peterson] by John Fordham, 21 May 2005, at [[The Guardian]]\n*[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p85979/discography|pure_url=yes}} Profile and discography] at [http://www.allmusic.com allmusic.com]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GotQd8pKTGQ&list=RDGotQd8pKTGQ#t=21 Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen Autumn Leaves] on YouTube\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pedersen, Niels-Henning Orsted}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Lejre Municipality]]\n[[Category:20th-century double-bassists]]\n[[Category:21st-century double-bassists]]\n[[Category:20th-century bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Bebop double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Danish jazz double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Male double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Danish jazz bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Danish jazz composers]]\n[[Category:Enja Records artists]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Hard bop double-bassists]]\n[[Category:SteepleChase Records artists]]\n[[Category:Male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century guitarists]]\n[[Category:DR Big Band members]]\n[[Category:Male jazz composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Danish Olympic athlete|Niels Pedersen (athlete)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist<!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen\n| image            = NH\u00d8P.jpg\n| caption          = \n| image_size       = 300px\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = NH\u00d8P, The Great Dane with <br />the Never-Ending Name\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1946|5|27}}\n| birth_place      = [[Osted]], [[Zealand]], Denmark\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|df=yes|2005|4|19|1946|5|27}}\n| death_place      = [[Ish\u00f8j]], Zealand\n| instrument       = [[Double-bass|Upright bass]]\n| genre            = [[Jazz]], [[bebop]], [[hard bop]], [[avant-garde jazz]]\n| occupation       = Musician, composer\n| years_active     = 1960s\u20132005\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Albert Ayler]], [[Chet Baker]], [[Count Basie]], [[Kenny Drew]], [[Roy Eldridge]], [[Bill Evans]], [[Stan Getz]], [[Dizzy Gillespie]], [[Dexter Gordon]], [[Milt Jackson]], [[Slide Hampton]], [[Roland Kirk]], [[Tete Montoliu]], [[Joe Pass]], [[Oscar Peterson]], [[Jean-Luc Ponty]], [[Sonny Rollins]], [[George Shearing]], [[Archie Shepp]], [[Ben Webster]]\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen''' ({{IPA-da|ne\u031dls\u02c8hene\u031d\u014b \u02c8\u0276\u0250\u032fst\u0259\u00f0 \u02c8p\u02b0e\u00f0\u0250sn\u0329}}, 27 May 1946 \u2013 19 April 2005), often known as '''NH\u00d8P''', was a Danish [[jazz]] [[double bassist|upright bassist]] known for his technique and musical approach.<ref name=politiken>{{cite web\n |url        = http://politiken.dk/kultur/ECE111233/bassisten-niels-henning-oersted-pedersen-er-doed\n |title      = Bassisten Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen er d\u00f8d\n |language   = Danish\n |publisher  = [[Politiken]]\n |date       = 20 April 2005\n |accessdate = 2014-11-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Yanow |first=Scott |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p85979/biography|pure_url=yes}} |title=Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen |work=Biography |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |date= |accessdate=2014-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\u00d8rsted Pedersen was born in [[Osted]], near [[Roskilde]], on the Danish island of [[Zealand (Denmark)|Zealand]], the son of a church organist. As a child, \u00d8rsted Pedersen played piano, but from the age of 13, he started learning to play [[double bass|upright bass]] and at the age of 14, while studying, he began his professional jazz career in Denmark with his first band, Jazzkvintet 60 ([[Danish language|Danish]] for Jazz Quintet 60). By the age of fifteen, he had the ability to accompany leading musicians at nightclubs, working regularly at Copenhagen's [[Jazzhus Montmartre]], after his debut there on New Year's Eve 1961, when he was only 15. When seventeen, he had already turned down an offer to join the [[Count Basie]] orchestra, mainly because he was too young to get legal permission to live and work as a musician in the United States.\n\nThe Montmartre was a regular stop-off for touring American Jazz stars, and as a member of the house band, the young \u00d8rsted Pedersen performed with saxophonists such as [[Sonny Rollins]], [[Dexter Gordon]], [[Rahsaan Roland Kirk]] and [[Stan Getz]], and pianist [[Bill Evans]], with whom he toured in Europe in 1965. During the 1960s, \u00d8rsted Pedersen played with a series of other important American jazzmen who were touring or resident in Denmark, including [[Ben Webster]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statsbiblioteket.dk/search/showrecord.jsp?record_id=sb_3197543|title=''\u00d8rsted Pedersen Recording With Ben Webster 1965\u201371''|publisher=Danish National Library, statsbiblioteket.dk|accessdate=2010-10-13}}</ref> [[Brew Moore]], [[Bud Powell]], [[Count Basie]], [[Roy Eldridge]], [[Dizzy Gillespie]], [[Jackie McLean]], and vocalist [[Ella Fitzgerald]]. He also played with [[Jean-Luc Ponty]], and became the bassist of choice whenever a big-name musician was touring Copenhagen.\n\nHe was awarded Best Bass Player of the Year by [[Down Beat|Downbeat]] Critics' Poll in 1981.<ref name=downbeat>{{cite web\n |url        = http://www.downbeat.com/default.asp?sect=stories&subsect=story_detail&sid=707\n |title      = 1981 DownBeat Critics Poll\n |publisher  = Downbeat.com\n |date       = 31 August 1981\n |accessdate = 2014-11-07}}</ref>\n\n\u00d8rsted Pedersen worked in duo and trio arrangements with pianist [[Kenny Drew]], recording over 50 albums together. He also worked with [[St\u00e9phane Grappelli]] and [[Joe Pass]] and recorded extensively as a leader. His best known songs are \"My Little Anna\", \"Jaywalkin'\", and \"The Puzzle\", as well as jazz arrangements of traditional Danish folk songs. A duo performance with [[Rune Gustafsson]] at [[Vossajazz]] 1980, concluded on the album ''Just The Way You Are'' on the label Sonet Gramofon, recorded half a year after this first meeting. He was awarded the [[Nordic Council Music Prize]] in 1991. This was the first time this prize for composition was awarded to a performing musician, and this must be ascribed to his great international standing. He was presumably the most sought-after Danish instrumentalist internationally ever, and had traveled and recorded with a series of the greatest jazz soloists internationally.\n\n\u00d8rsted Pedersen also had a particular ability to interpret Danish songs and folk melodies. He often played within trio ensembles, partly collectively with the trumpeter [[Palle Mikkelborg]] and the keyboard player [[Kenneth Knudsen]], and partly under his own name, usually with guitarists like [[Philip Catherine]] and [[Ulf Wakenius]]. In 1999, he co-led a duo with pianist [[Mulgrew Miller]], touring Europe, Japan, Australia, and Korea. This format was later enlarged into a trio featuring drummer [[Alvin Queen]]. This trio remained intact until Pedersen's death.<ref name=politiken/>\n\n== Death ==\n\n\u00d8rsted Pedersen died of heart failure in 2005 at the age of 58 in [[Copenhagen]], Denmark. He was survived by his wife, Solveig, and his three children.<ref>\"N-H. Orsted Pedersen, 58, Bassist in Danish Jazz Scene, Dies\" (21 April 2005) ''New York Times''</ref>\n[[Oscar Peterson]] wrote: \n{{Quote box\n| bgcolor=#EEEEEE\n| quoted=true\n| quote = After hearing this phenomenal talent on bass, I realized that somehow, someday we should meet, thereby giving me the opportunity to also play with him. This vision and thought took place in the early 1970s, when I was fortunate enough to be able to invite him to join my then trio.\n\nAllow me to express my reaction to his playing this way: First and foremost, he never got in my way--but he also had such a great musical perception of what I was trying to do that he served to greatly inspire me from a spontaneous aspect. I came off walking on Cloud 3000 that evening because of Niels' musical contribution. He had the most phenomenal technique, coupled with incredible harmonic perception, along with impeccable time. I shall never forget that evening.\n\nAlmost from that evening on, we became very close friends, not just musically but most certainly personally, for I developed a great admiration for the depth of Niels' political, geographical and personal understandings. He was a man who had an almost unbelievable wealth of historic cognizance pertaining to European history. He also had a very kindred spirit as a human being, always able to easily make good friends, should he care to do so.\n | source =Oscar Peterson, writing in ''Jazztimes''.<ref>{{cite web\n |last       = Peterson\n |first      = Oscar\n |url        = http://jazztimes.com/articles/25476-niels-henning-orsted-pedersen\n |title      = Niels-Henning Orsted Pedersen (5.27.46\u20134.19.05)\n |publisher  = Jazztimes.com\n |year       = 2006\n |accessdate = 2010-12-09}}</ref>\n | width     = 80%\n | qalign    = left\n | salign    = right\n | align     = center\n}}\n\n== Honors ==\n*1974: Grammy Award. Best Jazz Performance by a Group, The Trio - Oscar Peterson, Joe Pass and Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen\n*1981: Best Bass Player of the Year by [[Down Beat|Downbeat]] Critics' Poll<ref name=downbeat/>\n*1991: [[Nordic Council Music Prize]]\n\n== Discography ==\n{{main|Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen discography}}\n'''As leader/co-leader'''\n*1973: ''[[Duo (Kenny Drew and Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen album)|Duo]]'' ([[Steeplechase Records|SteepleChase]]) with [[Kenny Drew]]\n*1976: ''[[Jaywalkin']]'' ([[SteepleChase Records|SteepleChase]])\n*1976: ''[[Double Bass (album)|Double Bass]]'' (SteepleChase) with [[Sam Jones (musician)|Sam Jones]]\n*1976: ''[[Pictures (Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen and Kenneth Knudsen album)|Pictures]]'' (SteepleChase), with Kenneth Knudsen\n*1977: ''[[Trio 1]]'' (SteepleChase) with [[Philip Catherine]] and [[Billy Hart]]\n*1977: ''Trio 2'' (SteepleChase) with Philip Catherine and Billy Hart\n*1979: ''[[Dancing on the Tables]]'' (SteepleChase)\n*1981: ''[[Just the Way You Are (album)|Just the Way You Are]]'' ([[Sonet Records|Sonet]]), with [[Rune Gustafsson]]\n*1982: ''[[Face to Face (Tete Montoliu and Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen album)|Face to Face]]'' (SteepleChase), duo with [[Tete Montoliu]]\n*1983: ''The Viking'' ([[Pablo Records|Pablo]]), with [[Philip Catherine]]\n*1984: ''The Eternal Traveller'' (Pablo)\n*1986: ''[[Looking at Bird]]'' (SteepleChase) with [[Archie Shepp]]\n*1992: ''Uncharted Land'' (Pladecompagniet)\n*1993: ''Ambiance'' ([[Dacapo Records|Dacapo]])\n*1993: ''To a Brother'' (Pladekompagniet), NH\u00d8P Trio including with [[Ulf Wakenius]] & [[Adam Nussbaum]]\n*1995: ''Scandinavian Wood'' (Caprice)\n*1996: ''Those Who Were'' ([[Polygram Records|Polygram]])\n*1997: ''Friends Forever'' ([[Milestone Records|Milestone]])\n*1998: ''This Is All I Ask'' ([[Verve Records|Verve]])\n*1998: ''In the Name of Music'' (BMG Denmark), NH\u00d8P & [[Trio Rococo]]\n*2005: ''Friends Forever'' (Sony BMG Music Entertainment Denmark), compilation\n*2007: ''The Unforgettable NH\u00d8P Trio Live'' ([[ACT Music]]), including with Ulf Wakenius & [[Jonas Johansen (musician)|Jonas Johansen]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of jazz bassists]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{commons category}}\n*\"Scandinavian Wood\": The musical career of Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen in the light of his discography by J\u00f8rgen Mathiasen. Books on Demand 2010. {{ISBN|978-3-8423-5157-8}}.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/news/2005/may/21/guardianobituaries.arts Niels-Henning Orsted Pedersen \u2013 Danish virtuoso bassist who kept pace with Oscar Peterson] by John Fordham, 21 May 2005, at [[The Guardian]]\n*[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p85979/discography|pure_url=yes}} Profile and discography] at [http://www.allmusic.com allmusic.com]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GotQd8pKTGQ&list=RDGotQd8pKTGQ#t=21 Niels-Henning \u00d8rsted Pedersen Autumn Leaves] on YouTube\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pedersen, Niels-Henning Orsted}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Lejre Municipality]]\n[[Category:20th-century double-bassists]]\n[[Category:21st-century double-bassists]]\n[[Category:20th-century bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Bebop double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Danish jazz double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Male double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Danish jazz bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Danish jazz composers]]\n[[Category:Enja Records artists]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Hard bop double-bassists]]\n[[Category:SteepleChase Records artists]]\n[[Category:Male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century guitarists]]\n[[Category:DR Big Band members]]\n[[Category:Male jazz composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fixingDanish IPA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niels-Henning_%C3%98rsted_Pedersen"}
{"title_page": "Terence Lewin", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= The Lord Lewin\n|image= Tlewin.jpg\n|image_size= 200\n|caption= Admiral Sir Terence Lewin\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1920|11|19|df=y}}\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1999|01|23|1920|11|19|df=y}}\n|birth_place= [[Dover]], [[Kent]], England\n|death_place= [[Ufford, Suffolk|Ufford]], [[Suffolk]], England\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= United Kingdom\n|branch= [[Royal Navy]]\n|serviceyears=1939\u20131982              \n|rank= [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]]\n|unit= \n|commands= [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]]<br/>[[First Sea Lord]]<br/>[[Commander-in-Chief, Naval Home Command (Royal Navy)|Naval Home Command]]<br/>[[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]]<br/>{{HMS|Hermes|R12|6}}<br/>{{HMS|Tenby|F65|6}}<br/>{{HMS|Urchin|R99|6}}<br/>[[HMY Britannia|HM Yacht ''Britannia'']]<br/>{{HMS|Corunna|D97|6}}\n|battles= [[Second World War]]<br/>[[Falklands War]]\n|awards= [[Knight of the Order of the Garter]]<br/>[[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Lieutenant of the Royal Victorian Order]]<br/>[[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Cross]]<br/>[[Mentioned in Despatches]] (3)\n|laterwork= \n}}\n[[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]] '''Terence Thornton Lewin, Baron Lewin''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KG|GCB|LVO|DSC}} (19 November 1920 \u2013 23 January 1999) was a [[Royal Navy]] officer. He served in the [[Second World War]] and then commanded a destroyer, the [[Royal yacht]], two frigates and an aircraft carrier before achieving higher command. He was [[First Sea Lord]] and Chief of the Naval Staff in the late 1970s and in that role he worked hard to secure a decent wage for servicemen and helped win them a 32% pay rise. He went on to be [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]] during the [[Falklands War]], serving as chief war planner and as Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s chief advisor during the war. He was also the first Chief of Defence Staff to act as head of the Armed Forces rather than just Chairman of the Chiefs of Staff Committee.\n\n==Naval career==\nBorn the son of Eric Lewin and Maggie Lewin (n\u00e9e Falconer)<ref name=odnb>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/71891 |title=Lewin, Terence Thornton, Baron Lewin (1920\u20131999) |author=[[J. Richard Hill|Richard Hill]]|work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date= September 2004|accessdate=30 August 2012}} {{subscription}}</ref> and educated at [[The Judd School]] in [[Tonbridge]], where he was head prefect in 1938, Lewin joined the Royal Navy as a [[cadet]] in 1939.<ref name=heath155>Heathcote, p. 155</ref> He was initially posted to the training ship [[HMS Vindictive (1918)|HMS ''Vindictive'']] but when the [[Second World War]] broke out in September 1939 he transferred to the cruiser {{HMS|Belfast|C35|6}} and then two months later to the [[battleship]] {{HMS|Valiant|1914|6}}.<ref name=Heath156>Heathcote, p. 156</ref>\n\n[[File:HMS Ashanti.jpg|thumb|left|The destroyer {{HMS|Ashanti|F51|6}} in which Lewin he took part in the Arctic Convoys during the Second World War]]\nIn the Valiant he took part in the [[Norwegian Campaign]] in April and May 1940 and then in the [[Attack on Mers-el-K\u00e9bir|attack on the French Fleet at Mers-el-K\u00e9bir]] in July 1940.<ref name=Heath156/> He transferred to the [[destroyer]] {{HMS|Highlander|H44|6}} in October 1941 and then to the destroyer {{HMS|Ashanti|F51|6}} in January 1942.<ref name=Heath156/> During a long period of service in the Ashanti he took part in the [[Arctic convoys of World War II|Arctic Convoys]], and having been promoted to [[lieutenant]] on 1 July 1942, he took part in [[Operation Pedestal]] to relieve [[Malta]] in August 1942 and then the [[Operation Torch|allied landings in North Africa]] in November 1942 before returning to the Arctic Convoys again and finally taking part in the [[Normandy landings|allied landings in Normandy]] in June 1944.<ref name=Heath156/> He served with distinction being [[mentioned in despatches]] three times<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=35679|page=3719|date=21 August 1942}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=36676 |supp=y|page=4010|date=25 August 1944 |nolink=y}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=36794 |supp=y|page=5224|date=10 November 1944 |nolink=y}}</ref> and being awarded the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Cross]] in 1942 for saving the lives of many fellow servicemen when the destroyer {{HMS|Somali|F33|6}} was hit by a [[torpedo]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35805 |date=27 November 1942 |page=5226 |supp=y |nolink=y}}</ref><ref name=inde>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-admiral-of-the-fleet-lord-lewin-1076155.html|title=Obituary: Admiral of the Fleet Lord Lewin|newspaper=The Independent|date=25 January 1999|accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nLewin attended the gunnery school at {{HMS|Excellent|shore establishment|6}} in Spring 1945 and then joined the staff there in May 1945.<ref name=Heath156/> He was posted to the cruiser {{HMS|Bellona|63|6}} as gunnery officer in April 1946 and, after attending the advanced gunnery course at the [[Royal Naval College, Greenwich|Royal Naval College]], [[Greenwich]], in 1947, he returned to the staff at HMS ''Excellent'' in December.<ref name=Heath156/> Promoted to [[lieutenant commander]] on 1 July 1949,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=38681|page=3760|date=2 August 1949 |nolink=y}}</ref> he became gunnery officer of the First Destroyer Flotilla in the [[Mediterranean Fleet]].<ref name=heath157>Heathcote, p. 157</ref> He rejoined the staff of HMS Excellent in January 1952 and, having been promoted to [[commander]] on 31 December 1952,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=39749|page=220|date=9 January 1953 |nolink=y}}</ref> he joined the staff of the [[Second Sea Lord]] at the [[Admiralty]] in December 1953.<ref name=heath157/>\n\nLewin was given command of the destroyer {{HMS|Corunna|D97|6}} in October 1955 and then of [[HMY Britannia|HM Yacht ''Britannia'']] in April 1957, before being promoted to [[Captain (Royal Navy)|captain]] on 30 June 1958.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=41450|page=4514|date=18 July 1958 |nolink=y}}</ref> He went back to the Admiralty as Assistant Director of the Tactical Ship Requirements and Staff Duties Division in November 1958 and then, having been appointed a [[Lieutenant of the Royal Victorian Order]] in the 1959 [[New Year Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=41589 |supp=y|page=5|date=30 December 1958 |nolink=y}}</ref> he became Assistant Director of the Tactical and Weapons Policy Division in 1960.<ref name=heath157/> After attending the [[Royal College of Defence Studies|Imperial Defence College]] in 1961,<ref name=heath157/> he was appointed Captain (F) of the [[17th Frigate Squadron (United Kingdom)|17th Frigate Squadron]] in December 1961 sailing successively in the frigates {{HMS|Urchin|R99|6}} and then {{HMS|Tenby|F65|6}}.<ref name=heath157/> He went back to the Admiralty again as [[Directorate of Naval Tactical and Weapons Policy|Director of Tactical and Weapons Policy]] in December 1963 and took command of the [[aircraft carrier]] {{HMS|Hermes|R12|6}} in May 1966.<ref name=heath157/> He was appointed Naval [[Aide-de-Camp]] to [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] on 7 July 1967<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=44365 |supp=y|page=7881|date=14 July 1967 |nolink=y}}</ref> and promoted to [[rear admiral]] on 7 January 1968,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=44405 |supp=y|page=9891|date=8 September 1967 |nolink=y}}</ref> on appointment as Assistant Chief of the Naval Staff (Policy) before becoming Flag Officer Second in Command [[Eastern Fleet|Far East Fleet]] in August 1969.<ref name=heath157/> Promoted to [[vice admiral]] on 7 October 1970,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=45214 |supp=y|page=11458|date=16 October 1970 |nolink=y}}</ref> he became [[Vice Chief of the Naval Staff (United Kingdom)|Vice Chief of the Naval Staff]] in January 1971.<ref name=heath158>Heathcote, p. 158</ref> He was appointed [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] in the 1973 [[New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=45860 |supp=y|page=2|date=29 December 1972 |nolink=y}}</ref> He was promoted to full [[admiral]] on 1 December 1973,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=46138 |supp=y|page=14081|date=26 November 1973 |nolink=y}}</ref> on appointment as [[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]] and [[NATO]] Commander-in-Chief, Channel and Commander-in-Chief Eastern Atlantic and became [[Commander-in-Chief, Naval Home Command (Royal Navy)|Commander-in-Chief Naval Home Command]] in November 1975<ref name=heath158/> before being advanced to [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]] in the 1976 [[Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=46919 |supp=y|page=8016|date=4 June 1976 |nolink=y}}</ref>\n\n[[File:HMS Bristol storing at Ascension Island 1982.JPG|thumb|left|Supplies being delivered to the destroyer {{HMS|Bristol|D23|6}} by helicopter during a stopover at Ascension Island on the ship's voyage to take part in the Falklands War]]\nLewin was appointed [[First Sea Lord]] and Chief of Naval Staff on 1 March 1977.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=47173 |supp=y|page=3571|date=14 March 1977 |nolink=y}}</ref> In that role he worked hard to secure a decent wage for servicemen and helped win them a 32% pay rise.<ref name=inde/> Promoted to [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]] on 6 July 1979,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=47904 |supp=y|page=8998|date=16 July 1979 |nolink=y}}</ref> he went on to be [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]] in September 1979 and served as a member of the [[War Cabinet]] during the [[Falklands War]] giving [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Margaret Thatcher]] his resolute support when losses began to be suffered.<ref name=heath159>Heathcote, p. 159</ref><ref>Stephen Prince \"British command and control in the Falklands Campaign.\" ''Defense & Security Analysis'' 18.4 (2002): 333-349.</ref>\n\nLewin was the first Chief of Defence Staff to act as Head of the Armed Forces rather than just Chairman of the Chiefs of Staff Committee.<ref name=heath159/> He was created a [[life peer]], as '''Baron Lewin''', of [[Greenwich]] in Greater London in October 1982<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=49176|page=15347|date=24 November 1982 |nolink=y}}</ref> on his retirement.<ref name=heath159/>\n\n==Later life==\nIn retirement Lewin became Chairman of the Trustees of the [[National Maritime Museum]], President of the [[Society for Nautical Research]], a Liveryman of the [[Worshipful Company of Skinners|Skinners' Company]] and of the [[Worshipful Company of Shipwrights|Shipwrights' Company]] and an elder brother of [[Trinity House]].<ref name=debrett>People of Today 1994, Debrett, {{ISBN|1 870520 19 X}}</ref> His interests included military history: he was an expert on the life of [[James Cook|Captain Cook]].<ref name=inde/> He was appointed a [[Order of the Garter|Knight of the Order of the Garter]] in April 1983.<ref name=heath159/> He died at his home at [[Ufford, Suffolk|Ufford]] in [[Suffolk]] on 23 January 1999.<ref name=heath159/>\n\n==Family==\nIn 1944 Lewin married Jane Branch-Evans; they had two sons and a daughter.<ref name=Heath156/>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = \n|image size =\n|notes = \n|year_adopted = \n|coronet = [[Coronet|Coronet of a Baron]]\n|escutcheon = Quarterly Gules and Azure, three Boars' Heads, two and one, couped Or, tusked Argent, on a Chief barry wavy of four Bleu Celeste and Argent, a Naval Gun circa 1800 proper, mounted on its Carriage Gold.\n|supporters = Dexter: an Able Seaman of Her Majesty's Ship Victory, wearing the South Atlantic Medal proper.\nSinister: a Royal Marine, wearing the South Atlantic Medal proper. \nThe whole upon a Compartment comprising a Grassy Mount with Outcrops of Rock proper, and having on each side a Sea Inlet barry wavy Argent and Azure.\n|crest = Out of a Naval Crown Azure, a Lion rampant in trian aspect Or, on its head a Baron's Coronet and Cap of Estate proper, brandishing in the dexter paw a Sword proper, Hilt, Knuckle Guard and Pommel in the form of an eagle's head Gold.\n| other_elements = Order of the Garter circlet bearing the inscription '''HONI SOIT QUI MAL Y PENSE'''\n|badge = \n|motto = '''FLEXIBLE BUT FIRM OF PURPOSE'''\n|symbolism = \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Finlan, Alastair. ''The Royal Navy in the Falklands Conflict and the Gulf War: Culture and Strategy'' (Psychology Press, 2004).\n* {{cite book |last=Heathcote |first=Tony |title=The British Admirals of the Fleet 1734 \u2013 1995 |publisher=Pen & Sword Ltd |year=2002 |isbn=0-85052-835-6}}\n* {{cite book|title=Lewin of Greenwich|author=Rear-Admiral [[J. Richard Hill|Richard Hill]]|publisher= Weidenfeld Military|year= 2000|isbn= 978-0-304-35329-3}}\n* Prince, Stephen. \"British command and control in the Falklands Campaign.\" ''Defense & Security Analysis'' 18.4 (2002): 333\u2013349.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Edward Ashmore|Sir Edward Ashmore]]|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Vice Chief of the Naval Staff (United Kingdom)|Vice Chief of the Naval Staff]]|years=1971\u20131973}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Treacher|Sir John Treacher]]|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]]|years=1973\u20131975}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Derek Empson|Sir Derek Empson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Commander-in-Chief, Naval Home Command (Royal Navy)|Commander-in-Chief Naval Home Command]]|years=1975\u20131976}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David Williams (Royal Navy officer)|Sir David Williams]]}}\n|-\n{{succession box | title=[[First Sea Lord]] | before=Sir Edward Ashmore | after=[[Henry Leach|Sir Henry Leach]] | years=1977\u20131979}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]] | before=[[Neil Cameron, Baron Cameron of Balhousie|Sir Neil Cameron]] | after=[[Edwin Bramall, Baron Bramall|Sir Edwin Bramall]] | years=1979\u20131982}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Chiefs of Defence Staff}}\n{{First Sea Lord}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lewin, Terence}}\n[[Category:First Sea Lords]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals of the fleet]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers of World War II]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the Falklands War]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Lieutenants of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at The Judd School]]\n[[Category:Chiefs of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Naval College, Greenwich]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Defence Studies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= The Lord Lewin\n|image= Tlewin.jpg\n|image_size= 200\n|caption= Admiral Sir Terence Lewin\n|birth_date= {{birth date|1920|11|19|df=y}}\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1999|01|23|1920|11|19|df=y}}\n|birth_place= [[Dover]], [[Kent]], England\n|death_place= [[Ufford, Suffolk|Ufford]], [[Suffolk]], England\n|nickname=\n|allegiance= United Kingdom\n|branch= [[Royal Navy]]\n|serviceyears=1939\u20131982              \n|rank= [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]]\n|unit= \n|commands= [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]]<br/>[[First Sea Lord]]<br/>[[Commander-in-Chief, Naval Home Command (Royal Navy)|Naval Home Command]]<br/>[[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]]<br/>{{HMS|Hermes|R12|6}}<br/>{{HMS|Tenby|F65|6}}<br/>{{HMS|Urchin|R99|6}}<br/>[[HMY Britannia|HM Yacht ''Britannia'']]<br/>{{HMS|Corunna|D97|6}}\n|battles= [[Second World War]]<br/>[[Falklands War]]\n|awards= [[Knight of the Order of the Garter]]<br/>[[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Lieutenant of the Royal Victorian Order]]<br/>[[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Cross]]<br/>[[Mentioned in Despatches]] (3)\n|laterwork= \n}}\n[[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]] '''Terence Thornton Lewin, Baron Lewin''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KG|GCB|LVO|DSC}} (19 November 1920 \u2013 23 January 1999) was a [[Royal Navy]] officer. He served in the [[Second World War]] and then commanded a destroyer, the [[Royal yacht]], two frigates and an aircraft carrier before achieving higher command. He was [[First Sea Lord]] and Chief of the Naval Staff in the late 1970s and in that role he worked hard to secure a decent wage for servicemen and helped win them a 32% pay rise. He went on to be [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]] during the [[Falklands War]], serving as chief war planner and as Prime Minister [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s chief advisor during the war. He was also the first Chief of Defence Staff to act as head of the Armed Forces rather than just Chairman of the Chiefs of Staff Committee.\n\n==Naval career==\nBorn the son of Eric Lewin and Maggie Lewin (n\u00e9e Falconer)<ref name=odnb>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/71891 |title=Lewin, Terence Thornton, Baron Lewin (1920\u20131999) |author=[[J. Richard Hill|Richard Hill]]|work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date= September 2004|accessdate=30 August 2012}} {{subscription}}</ref> and educated at [[The Judd School]] in [[Tonbridge]], where he was head prefect in 1938, Lewin joined the Royal Navy as a [[cadet]] in 1939.<ref name=heath155>Heathcote, p. 155</ref> He was initially posted to the training ship [[HMS Vindictive (1918)|HMS ''Vindictive'']] but when the [[Second World War]] broke out in September 1939 he transferred to the cruiser {{HMS|Belfast|C35|6}} and then two months later to the [[battleship]] {{HMS|Valiant|1914|6}}.<ref name=Heath156>Heathcote, p. 156</ref>\n\n[[File:HMS Ashanti.jpg|thumb|left|The destroyer {{HMS|Ashanti|F51|6}} in which Lewin he took part in the Arctic Convoys during the Second World War]]\nIn the Valiant he took part in the [[Norwegian Campaign]] in April and May 1940 and then in the [[Attack on Mers-el-K\u00e9bir|attack on the French Fleet at Mers-el-K\u00e9bir]] in July 1940.<ref name=Heath156/> He transferred to the [[destroyer]] {{HMS|Highlander|H44|6}} in October 1941 and then to the destroyer {{HMS|Ashanti|F51|6}} in January 1942.<ref name=Heath156/> During a long period of service in the Ashanti he took part in the [[Arctic convoys of World War II|Arctic Convoys]], and having been promoted to [[lieutenant]] on 1 July 1942, he took part in [[Operation Pedestal]] to relieve [[Malta]] in August 1942 and then the [[Operation Torch|allied landings in North Africa]] in November 1942 before returning to the Arctic Convoys again and finally taking part in the [[Normandy landings|allied landings in Normandy]] in June 1944.<ref name=Heath156/> He served with distinction being [[mentioned in despatches]] three times<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=35679|page=3719|date=21 August 1942}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=36676 |supp=y|page=4010|date=25 August 1944 |nolink=y}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=36794 |supp=y|page=5224|date=10 November 1944 |nolink=y}}</ref> and being awarded the [[Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)|Distinguished Service Cross]] in 1942 for saving the lives of many fellow servicemen when the destroyer {{HMS|Somali|F33|6}} was hit by a [[torpedo]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=35805 |date=27 November 1942 |page=5226 |supp=y |nolink=y}}</ref><ref name=inde>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-admiral-of-the-fleet-lord-lewin-1076155.html|title=Obituary: Admiral of the Fleet Lord Lewin|newspaper=The Independent|date=25 January 1999|accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nLewin attended the gunnery school at {{HMS|Excellent|shore establishment|6}} in Spring 1945 and then joined the staff there in May 1945.<ref name=Heath156/> He was posted to the cruiser {{HMS|Bellona|63|6}} as gunnery officer in April 1946 and, after attending the advanced gunnery course at the [[Royal Naval College, Greenwich|Royal Naval College]], [[Greenwich]], in 1947, he returned to the staff at HMS ''Excellent'' in December.<ref name=Heath156/> Promoted to [[lieutenant commander]] on 1 July 1949,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=38681|page=3760|date=2 August 1949 |nolink=y}}</ref> he became gunnery officer of the First Destroyer Flotilla in the [[Mediterranean Fleet]].<ref name=heath157>Heathcote, p. 157</ref> He rejoined the staff of HMS Excellent in January 1952 and, having been promoted to [[commander]] on 31 December 1952,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=39749|page=220|date=9 January 1953 |nolink=y}}</ref> he joined the staff of the [[Second Sea Lord]] at the [[Admiralty]] in December 1953.<ref name=heath157/>\n\nLewin was given command of the destroyer {{HMS|Corunna|D97|6}} in October 1955 and then of [[HMY Britannia|HM Yacht ''Britannia'']] in April 1957, before being promoted to [[Captain (Royal Navy)|captain]] on 30 June 1958.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=41450|page=4514|date=18 July 1958 |nolink=y}}</ref> He went back to the Admiralty as Assistant Director of the Tactical Ship Requirements and Staff Duties Division in November 1958 and then, having been appointed a [[Lieutenant of the Royal Victorian Order]] in the 1959 [[New Year Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=41589 |supp=y|page=5|date=30 December 1958 |nolink=y}}</ref> he became Assistant Director of the Tactical and Weapons Policy Division in 1960.<ref name=heath157/> After attending the [[Royal College of Defence Studies|Imperial Defence College]] in 1961,<ref name=heath157/> he was appointed Captain (F) of the [[17th Frigate Squadron (United Kingdom)|17th Frigate Squadron]] in December 1961 sailing successively in the frigates {{HMS|Urchin|R99|6}} and then {{HMS|Tenby|F65|6}}.<ref name=heath157/> He went back to the Admiralty again as [[Directorate of Naval Tactical and Weapons Policy|Director of Tactical and Weapons Policy]] in December 1963 and took command of the [[aircraft carrier]] {{HMS|Hermes|R12|6}} in May 1966.<ref name=heath157/> He was appointed Naval [[Aide-de-Camp]] to [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] on 7 July 1967<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=44365 |supp=y|page=7881|date=14 July 1967 |nolink=y}}</ref> and promoted to [[rear admiral]] on 7 January 1968,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=44405 |supp=y|page=9891|date=8 September 1967 |nolink=y}}</ref> on appointment as Assistant Chief of the Naval Staff (Policy) before becoming Flag Officer Second in Command [[Eastern Fleet|Far East Fleet]] in August 1969.<ref name=heath157/> Promoted to [[vice admiral]] on 7 October 1970,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=45214 |supp=y|page=11458|date=16 October 1970 |nolink=y}}</ref> he became [[Vice Chief of the Naval Staff (United Kingdom)|Vice Chief of the Naval Staff]] in January 1971.<ref name=heath158>Heathcote, p. 158</ref> He was appointed [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] in the 1973 [[New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=45860 |supp=y|page=2|date=29 December 1972 |nolink=y}}</ref> He was promoted to full [[admiral]] on 1 December 1973,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=46138 |supp=y|page=14081|date=26 November 1973 |nolink=y}}</ref> on appointment as [[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]] and [[NATO]] Commander-in-Chief, Channel and Commander-in-Chief Eastern Atlantic and became [[Commander-in-Chief, Naval Home Command (Royal Navy)|Commander-in-Chief Naval Home Command]] in November 1975<ref name=heath158/> before being advanced to [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]] in the 1976 [[Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=46919 |supp=y|page=8016|date=4 June 1976 |nolink=y}}</ref>\n\n[[File:HMS Bristol storing at Ascension Island 1982.JPG|thumb|left|Supplies being delivered to the destroyer {{HMS|Bristol|D23|6}} by helicopter during a stopover at Ascension Island on the ship's voyage to take part in the Falklands War]]\nLewin was appointed [[First Sea Lord]] and Chief of Naval Staff on 1 March 1977.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=47173 |supp=y|page=3571|date=14 March 1977 |nolink=y}}</ref> In that role he worked hard to secure a decent wage for servicemen and helped win them a 32% pay rise.<ref name=inde/> Promoted to [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]] on 6 July 1979,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=47904 |supp=y|page=8998|date=16 July 1979 |nolink=y}}</ref> he went on to be [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]] in September 1979 and served as a member of the [[War Cabinet]] during the [[Falklands War]] giving [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Margaret Thatcher]] his resolute support when losses began to be suffered.<ref name=heath159>Heathcote, p. 159</ref><ref>Stephen Prince \"British command and control in the Falklands Campaign.\" ''Defense & Security Analysis'' 18.4 (2002): 333-349.</ref>\n\nLewin was the first Chief of Defence Staff to act as Head of the Armed Forces rather than just Chairman of the Chiefs of Staff Committee.<ref name=heath159/> He was created a [[life peer]], as '''Baron Lewin''', of [[Greenwich]] in Greater London in October 1982<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=49176|page=15347|date=24 November 1982 |nolink=y}}</ref> on his retirement.<ref name=heath159/>\n\n==Later life==\nIn retirement Lewin became Chairman of the Trustees of the [[National Maritime Museum]], President of the [[Society for Nautical Research]], a Liveryman of the [[Worshipful Company of Skinners|Skinners' Company]] and of the [[Worshipful Company of Shipwrights|Shipwrights' Company]] and an elder brother of [[Trinity House]].<ref name=debrett>People of Today 1994, Debrett, {{ISBN|1 870520 19 X}}</ref> His interests included military history: he was an expert on the life of [[James Cook|Captain Cook]].<ref name=inde/> He was appointed a [[Order of the Garter|Knight of the Order of the Garter]] in April 1983.<ref name=heath159/> He died at his home at [[Ufford, Suffolk|Ufford]] in [[Suffolk]] on 23 January 1999.<ref name=heath159/>\n\n==Family==\nIn 1944 Lewin married Jane Branch-Evans; they had two sons and a daughter.<ref name=Heath156/>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = \n|image size =\n|notes = \n|year_adopted = \n|coronet = [[Coronet|Coronet of a Baron]]\n|escutcheon = Quarterly Gules and Azure, three Boars' Heads, two and one, couped Or, tusked Argent, on a Chief barry wavy of four Bleu Celeste and Argent, a Naval Gun circa 1800 proper, mounted on its Carriage Gold.\n|supporters = Dexter: an Able Seaman of Her Majesty's Ship Victory, wearing the South Atlantic Medal proper.\nSinister: a Royal Marine, wearing the South Atlantic Medal proper. \nThe whole upon a Compartment comprising a Grassy Mount with Outcrops of Rock proper, and having on each side a Sea Inlet barry wavy Argent and Azure.\n|crest = Out of a Naval Crown Azure, a Lion rampant in trian aspect Or, on its head a Baron's Coronet and Cap of Estate proper, brandishing in the dexter paw a Sword proper, Hilt, Knuckle Guard and Pommel in the form of an eagle's head Gold.\n| other_elements = Order of the Garter circlet bearing the inscription '''HONI SOIT QUI MAL Y PENSE'''\n|badge = \n|motto = '''FLEXIBLE BUT FIRM OF PURPOSE'''\n|symbolism = \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Finlan, Alastair. ''The Royal Navy in the Falklands Conflict and the Gulf War: Culture and Strategy'' (Psychology Press, 2004).\n* {{cite book |last=Heathcote |first=Tony |title=The British Admirals of the Fleet 1734 \u2013 1995 |publisher=Pen & Sword Ltd |year=2002 |isbn=0-85052-835-6}}\n* {{cite book|title=Lewin of Greenwich|author=Rear-Admiral [[J. Richard Hill|Richard Hill]]|publisher= Weidenfeld Military|year= 2000|isbn= 978-0-304-35329-3}}\n* Prince, Stephen. \"British command and control in the Falklands Campaign.\" ''Defense & Security Analysis'' 18.4 (2002): 333-349.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Edward Ashmore|Sir Edward Ashmore]]|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Vice Chief of the Naval Staff (United Kingdom)|Vice Chief of the Naval Staff]]|years=1971\u20131973}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Treacher|Sir John Treacher]]|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Commander-in-Chief Fleet]]|years=1973\u20131975}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Derek Empson|Sir Derek Empson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Commander-in-Chief, Naval Home Command (Royal Navy)|Commander-in-Chief Naval Home Command]]|years=1975\u20131976}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David Williams (Royal Navy officer)|Sir David Williams]]}}\n|-\n{{succession box | title=[[First Sea Lord]] | before=Sir Edward Ashmore | after=[[Henry Leach|Sir Henry Leach]] | years=1977\u20131979}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]] | before=[[Neil Cameron, Baron Cameron of Balhousie|Sir Neil Cameron]] | after=[[Edwin Bramall, Baron Bramall|Sir Edwin Bramall]] | years=1979\u20131982}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Chiefs of Defence Staff}}\n{{First Sea Lord}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lewin, Terence}}\n[[Category:First Sea Lords]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy admirals of the fleet]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers of World War II]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of the Falklands War]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Lieutenants of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Cross (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[