{"title_page": "Digby Jones, Baron Jones of Birmingham", "text_new": "{{redirect|Digby Jones|the British musician and producer|Digby Jones (musician)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Jones of Birmingham\n|honorific-suffix = | image = official portrait of Lord Jones of Birmingham crop 2.jpg\n| caption = \n| office = [[Minister of State for Trade|Minister of State for Trade, Investment and Business]]\n| term_start = 29 June 2007\n| term_end = 3 October 2008\n| primeminister = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| predecessor = [[Ian McCartney]]\n| successor = [[Gareth Thomas (English politician)|Gareth Thomas]]\n|office12         = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start12       = 10 July 2007<br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n|term_end12      =\n| birthname = Digby Marritt Jones\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1955|10|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Birmingham]], [[Warwickshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Patricia, Lady Jones\n| party = [[Crossbench]]\n| alma_mater = [[University College London]]\n| profession = Businessman\n| website = [http://digbylordjones.com/ www.digbylordjones.com]\n}}\n'''Digby Marritt Jones, Baron Jones of Birmingham''' (born 28 October 1955), known as '''Sir Digby Jones''' between 2005 and 2007, is a British businessman and politician, who has served as Director General of the [[Confederation of British Industry|CBI]] (2000\u201306) and [[Minister of State for Trade|Minister of State for Trade and Investment]] (2007\u201308).\n\nHe sits in the [[House of Lords]] as a non-aligned active [[crossbencher]]. He serves as Non Executive Chairman of Triumph Motorcycles Ltd, Thatcher's Cider Ltd, Elonex Ltd, Metalfloor UK Ltd, ProBuild 360 Ltd, Argentex Group plc and On Logistics Ltd and is a Non-Executive Director of DRP Holdings Ltd. Digby is Chairman of the Advisory Board of X-Force (the Social Enterprise helping Veterans into self-employment) and he is a Member of the South Warwickshire Multi Academy Trust.\n\n==Education and legal career==\nJones was born on 28 October 1955 in [[Birmingham]], England. He was educated at [[Bromsgrove School]] where he was [[Head Boy]]. He read Law at [[University College London]] as a [[Sub-Lieutenant]] in the [[Royal Navy]] on a University Cadetship, graduating with [[Bachelor's degree#England.2C Wales and Northern Ireland|upper second class honours]]. After graduation, Jones worked for 20 years at Edge & Ellison, a firm of lawyers based in Birmingham, culminating in serving as Senior Partner from 1995\u20131998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digbylordjones.com/biography.html|title=Biography of Lord Digby Jones|publisher=|accessdate=15 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==CBI==\nJones was Chairman of the CBI's [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]] Regional Council and became the first serving regional chairman to be appointed [[Director-General]]. He was Director-General of the [[Confederation of British Industry]] (CBI) between 1 January 2000 and 30 June 2006. He was appointed a [[Knight Bachelor]] in the [[2005 New Year Honours]] for services to Business.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=57509 |date=31 December 2004 |supp=y |page=1}}</ref> He then acted as an adviser to [[Barclays Capital]], [[Ford]], [[Deloitte]] and [[J. C. Bamford|JCB]]. He served as the unpaid [[UK|UK Skills Envoy]] from 2006\u201307.\n\nJones was a [[non-executive director]] for the IT contractor [[iSOFT]] from 2000 until his resignation in July 2005, when he stayed on for one year as an adviser. Following the collapse in the value of iSOFT and investigations into its [[accountancy]] practices, Jones said \"there is a limit to what a non-executive can know... They have to rely on what advisers tell them and what the executive team tells them. It is important that people understand this.\"\n\n==Political career==\nOn 29 June 2007, Jones became [[Minister of State for Trade|Minister of State for Trade and Investment]] in both the newly created [[Department for Business, Enterprise and Regulatory Reform]] and the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]]. He was appointed as a [[Government Minister]] in a move to create a government \"of all the talents\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6251788.stm Brown brings in more 'outsiders'] BBC News, 29 June 2007</ref> As he was not a parliamentarian at the time, Jones was made a [[life peer]], and became a member of the [[House of Lords]]. It was suggested that he was taking the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] whip in the House of Lords, but he chose not to join the Labour Party. He was gazetted as a peer on 10 July 2007 as '''Baron Jones of Birmingham''', ''of [[Alvechurch]] and of [[Bromsgrove]] in the County of Worcestershire'',<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=58392|date=16 July 2007|page=10219}}</ref> and took his seat in the House of Lords that same day.\n\nFormally styled ''The Lord Jones of Birmingham'', he sits as a [[Crossbencher]] in the House of Lords.\n\nJones had considered running for [[Mayor of London]] after being encouraged by a group of prominent businessmen. He was also approached by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] about becoming its candidate, but rejected this idea.<ref name=\"spat\">{{cite news|title=Tories in Digby mayor offer spat|date=6 July 2007|publisher=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6277044.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=12 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2008 Jones announced his intention to resign as Minister of Trade and Investment later in the year.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article3746942.ece Business minister Lord Jones of Birmingham plans to jump ship] Times Online, 15 April 2008</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/apr/16/gordonbrown.labour?gusrc=rss&feed=politics Digby Jones offers Brown 100% support despite plans to quit] The Guardian, 16 April 2008</ref> He resigned in October 2008 and was appointed to be a UK Business Ambassador for UK Trade & Investment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article4878530.ece|title=Former M&S chairman Paul Myners becomes Minister for the City|newspaper=The Times|author=Carl Mortishead|date=4 October 2008|accessdate=4 October 2008}}</ref> In testimony to the [[Public Administration Committee]] he said that his time as a junior minister was \"one of the most dehumanising and depersonalising experiences\" anyone could have and that he had been amazed by how many civil servants he thought deserved the sack.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jan/16/digby-jones-says-sack-civil-servants|title=Brown steps in after Digby Jones calls for half of civil service to be sacked|date=16 January 2009|newspaper=The Guardian|first=Deborah|last=Summers}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 January 2009, in a subsequent blog entry on the ''Daily Telegraph's'' blogsite, Jones was described as \"the walking personification of the spirit of big business at its corporatist worst\".<ref>Martin, Iain [https://web.archive.org/web/20100429174335/http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/iainmartin/8117867/Fire_Digby_Jones \"Fire Digby Jones\"] ''Daily Telegraph'' blog site, 16 January 2009</ref>\n\nOn 20 September 2013, he spoke at the [[UK Independence Party]] conference in London as a guest speaker, addressing the conference on business and economic matters.\n\nOn 29 September 2014, Jones introduced the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[George Osborne]], before his keynote speech at the Conservative Party conference in Birmingham. He said that Osborne \"deserves a personal pat on the back\" for having \"stuck to your guns and did what was right for our country.\" In response to any rumour regarding a possible defection, he also confirmed \"I don't do party politics\" and \"business is my constituency.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/11127382/Conservative-Party-Conference-2014-live.html|title=Conservative Party Conference 2014: live|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=29 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Other posts==\nJones is a Corporate Ambassador for the [[Cancer Research UK]] Corporate Ambassadors. He is President of the [[Diversity Works]] initiative \u2013 a programme led by the disability organisation [[Scope (charity)|Scope]], a Diamond Ambassador for [[Mencap]]'s WorkRight initiative, designed to spread the message of equality for disabled people, a Vice-President of [[Birmingham Hospice]], and a Patron of [[Lifecycle UK]], Ladies Fighting Breast Cancer and Get A-Head, the cancer charity fighting head and neck diseases. He is an active supporter of Ovarian Cancer Action, the Royal Navy's Royal Marine Charity, the Royal Shakespeare Company, the City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra. He is the Patron of the Thomas Edington Scholarship of the University of Western Australia in Perth.\n\nHe is also a Vice-President of the [[Friends of the British Library]], a charity which provides funding support to the [[British Library]].<ref name=\"ar0607\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bl.uk/supportus/pdf/friendsannrep0607.pdf |title=Friends of the British Library Annual Report 2006/07 |accessdate=7 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100415020637/http://www.bl.uk/supportus/pdf/friendsannrep0607.pdf |archivedate=15 April 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nJones is a Vice-Patron of the [[National Museum of the Royal Navy]]. The National Museum through its six museums tell the stories and preserves the rich heritage of all aspects of the Royal Navy.\n\nHe was a non-executive director of [[Leicester Tigers]].<ref>[http://www.guinnesspremiership.com/news/2945.php Sir Digby Jones appointed to Tigers Board] Guinness Premiership, 5 October 2005</ref> He is a Vice-President of [[The Birmingham Civic Society]] and was President of the Speakers Trust and their Speaker of the Year in 2008.\n\nIn November 2006, Jones was appointed \"Business Adviser\" to [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|the Duke of York]], receiving \u00a31,000 a month from the royal payroll for working one day a month. This position ended upon his appointment as a Minister in July 2007.\n\nJones is \u201cChairman of the Advisory Board of X-Force, the Social Enterprise helping Veterans into self-employment\u201d.\n\nJones is also \"Adjunct Professor at the University of Western Australia.\"\n\n==Fellowships and doctorates==\n\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=June 2017}}\n\nJones is a Fellow of [[University College London]] (2004); an Honorary Fellow of [[Cardiff University]] (2004); and an Honorary Doctor of the [[Birmingham City University|University of Central England]] (2002), the [[University of Birmingham]] (2002), the [[University of Manchester Institute of Science and Technology]] (2003), the [[University of Hertfordshire]] (2004), [[Middlesex University]] (2005), [[Sheffield Hallam University]] (2005), [[Aston University]] (2006), the [[University of Hull]] (2006), [[Queen's University, Belfast]] (2006), [[Warwick University]] (2006), [[Bradford University]] (2006), [[University of West London|Thames Valley University]] (2006), [[Wolverhampton University]] (2006), the [[University of Nottingham]], [[Loughborough University]] (2007) and Honorary Fellow of [[Cardiff Metropolitan University]] (2013).\n\n==View on unions==\nJones has said of trades unions:\n{{quote|They are in danger of withering on the vine of irrelevance. They are backward looking and not on today's agenda.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|first=Larry|last=Elliott|author2=|title=Sir Digby rides off with all guns blazing|date=26 June 2006|publisher=|url=https://www.theguardian.com/euro/story/0,,1805980,00.html|work=[[The Guardian]]|pages=|accessdate=25 July 2007}}</ref>}}\nand:\n{{quote|The trade unions put their members first and not the country. Labour is always in thrall to the [[trade unions|unions]]. People keep banging on about [[cash for peerages]], but the unions have bunged money to the government for years.<ref name=\"Guardian\" />}}\n\n==Media appearances==\nJones was the guest on [[BBC Radio]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'', broadcast on 21 May 2006. He won BBC One's ''[[Celebrity Mastermind]]'' with a 9-point margin finishing on 33 points on 5 January 2011. Jones nominated Winston Churchill on BBC Radio 4 Great Lives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00tpsvk|title=Winston Churchill, Series 22, Great Lives - BBC Radio 4|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nHe presented the [[BBC Two]] programme ''The New Troubleshooter'' where he \"helps businesses realise their potential, ruffling feathers and bruising egos along the way as he gets stuck in and delivers his analysis and advice\", taking over the mantle of [[John Harvey-Jones]] who presented the original series ''[[Troubleshooter (TV series)|Troubleshooter]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=BBC Two \u2013 Digby Jones: The New Troubleshooter|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b040tmm9|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014 he presented a programme on [[BBC Radio 4]], ''The Business Covenant''.\n\n==Books==\nIn 2011 Jones published his first book ''Fixing Britain: The Business of Reshaping Our Nation'' (with publisher Wiley) which was shortlisted for the 2012 CMI Management Book of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yearbook.managers.org.uk/|title=CMI Management Book of the Year \u2013 Celebrating excellence in all areas of Management and Leadership writing|work=Management Book of the Year|accessdate=15 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 ''Fixing Business: Making Profitable Business Work for the Good of All'', was published in April 2017, also with Wiley.\n\n==Personal life==\nJones is a supporter of [[Leicester Tigers]] (officially Leicester Football Club), [[Aston Villa FC]]<ref>[http://www.birminghampost.net/news/west-midlands-news/2010/05/14/david-cameron-has-been-aston-villa-fan-since-a-teenager-97319-26442362/ David Cameron has been Aston Villa fan since a teenager] Birmingham Post, 14 May 2010</ref> and a member of the [[Reform Club]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070926224644/http://www.cbi.org.uk/pdf/annualreport2007.pdf CBI annual report & accounts, 2007]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/lord_jones_of_birmingham Lord Jones of Birmingham] on TheyWorkForYou.com\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Adair Turner]]|title=Director of the [[Confederation of British Industry]]|years=2000\u20132006|after=[[Richard Lambert]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Ian McCartney]]|title=[[Minister of State for Trade]]|years=2007\u20132008|after=[[Gareth Thomas (English politician)|Gareth Thomas]]}}\n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Baron West of Spithead|The Lord West of Spithead]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom|Gentlemen]]'''<br />''Baron Jones of Birmingham'' '''}}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Baron Darzi of Denham|The Lord Darzi of Denham]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones Of Birmingham, Digby Jones, Baron}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English lawyers]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College London]]\n[[Category:Commissioners for Racial Equality]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bromsgrove School]]\n[[Category:People from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:British business writers]]\n[[Category:Freemen of the City of London]]\n[[Category:British Eurosceptics]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Digby Jones|the British musician and producer|Digby Jones (musician)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Jones of Birmingham\n|honorific-suffix = | image = official portrait of Lord Jones of Birmingham crop 2.jpg\n| caption = \n| office = [[Minister of State for Trade|Minister of State for Trade, Investment and Business]]\n| term_start = 29 June 2007\n| term_end = 3 October 2008\n| primeminister = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| predecessor = [[Ian McCartney]]\n| successor = [[Gareth Thomas (English politician)|Gareth Thomas]]\n|office12         = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start12       = 10 July 2007<br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n|term_end12      =\n| birthname = Digby Marritt Jones\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1955|10|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Birmingham]], [[Warwickshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Patricia, Lady Jones\n| party = [[Crossbench]]\n| alma_mater = [[University College London]]\n| profession = Businessman\n| website = [http://digbylordjones.com/ www.digbylordjones.com]\n}}\n'''Digby Marritt Jones, Baron Jones of Birmingham''' (born 28 October 1955), known as '''Sir Digby Jones''' between 2005 and 2007, is a British businessman and politician, who has served as Director General of the [[Confederation of British Industry|CBI]] (2000\u201306) and [[Minister of State for Trade|Minister of State for Trade and Investment]] (2007\u201308).\n\nHe sits in the [[House of Lords]] as a non-aligned active [[crossbencher]]. He serves as Non Executive Chairman of Triumph Motorcycles Ltd, Thatcher\u2019s Cider Ltd, Elonex Ltd, Metalfloor UK Ltd, ProBuild 360 Ltd, Argentex Group plc and On Logistics Ltd and is a Non-Executive Director of DRP Holdings Ltd. Digby is Chairman of the Advisory Board of X-Force (the Social Enterprise helping Veterans into self-employment) and he is a Member of the South Warwickshire Multi Academy Trust.\n\n==Education and legal career==\nJones was born on 28 October 1955 in [[Birmingham]], England. He was educated at [[Bromsgrove School]] where he was [[Head Boy]]. He read Law at [[University College London]] as a [[Sub-Lieutenant]] in the [[Royal Navy]] on a University Cadetship, graduating with [[Bachelor's degree#England.2C Wales and Northern Ireland|upper second class honours]]. After graduation, Jones worked for 20 years at Edge & Ellison, a firm of lawyers based in Birmingham, culminating in serving as Senior Partner from 1995-1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digbylordjones.com/biography.html|title=Biography of Lord Digby Jones|publisher=|accessdate=15 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==CBI==\nJones was Chairman of the CBI's [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]] Regional Council and became the first serving regional chairman to be appointed [[Director-General]]. He was Director-General of the [[Confederation of British Industry]] (CBI) between 1 January 2000 and 30 June 2006. He was appointed a [[Knight Bachelor]] in the [[2005 New Year Honours]] for services to Business.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=57509 |date=31 December 2004 |supp=y |page=1}}</ref> He then acted as an adviser to [[Barclays Capital]], [[Ford]], [[Deloitte]] and [[J. C. Bamford|JCB]]. He served as the unpaid [[UK|UK Skills Envoy]] from 2006\u201307.\n\nJones was a [[non-executive director]] for the IT contractor [[iSOFT]] from 2000 until his resignation in July 2005, when he stayed on for one year as an adviser. Following the collapse in the value of iSOFT and investigations into its [[accountancy]] practices, Jones said \"there is a limit to what a non-executive can know... They have to rely on what advisers tell them and what the executive team tells them. It is important that people understand this.\"\n\n==Political career==\nOn 29 June 2007, Jones became [[Minister of State for Trade|Minister of State for Trade and Investment]] in both the newly created [[Department for Business, Enterprise and Regulatory Reform]] and the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]]. He was appointed as a [[Government Minister]] in a move to create a government \"of all the talents\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6251788.stm Brown brings in more 'outsiders'] BBC News, 29 June 2007</ref> As he was not a parliamentarian at the time, Jones was made a [[life peer]], and became a member of the [[House of Lords]]. It was suggested that he was taking the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] whip in the House of Lords, but he chose not to join the Labour Party. He was gazetted as a peer on 10 July 2007 as '''Baron Jones of Birmingham''', ''of [[Alvechurch]] and of [[Bromsgrove]] in the County of Worcestershire'',<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=58392|date=16 July 2007|page=10219}}</ref> and took his seat in the House of Lords that same day.\n\nFormally styled ''The Lord Jones of Birmingham'', he sits as a [[Crossbencher]] in the House of Lords.\n\nJones had considered running for [[Mayor of London]] after being encouraged by a group of prominent businessmen. He was also approached by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] about becoming its candidate, but rejected this idea.<ref name=\"spat\">{{cite news|title=Tories in Digby mayor offer spat|date=6 July 2007|publisher=|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6277044.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=12 September 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2008 Jones announced his intention to resign as Minister of Trade and Investment later in the year.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article3746942.ece Business minister Lord Jones of Birmingham plans to jump ship] Times Online, 15 April 2008</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/apr/16/gordonbrown.labour?gusrc=rss&feed=politics Digby Jones offers Brown 100% support despite plans to quit] The Guardian, 16 April 2008</ref> He resigned in October 2008 and was appointed to be a UK Business Ambassador for UK Trade & Investment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/banking_and_finance/article4878530.ece|title=Former M&S chairman Paul Myners becomes Minister for the City|newspaper=The Times|author=Carl Mortishead|date=4 October 2008|accessdate=4 October 2008}}</ref> In testimony to the [[Public Administration Committee]] he said that his time as a junior minister was \"one of the most dehumanising and depersonalising experiences\" anyone could have and that he had been amazed by how many civil servants he thought deserved the sack.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jan/16/digby-jones-says-sack-civil-servants|title=Brown steps in after Digby Jones calls for half of civil service to be sacked|date=16 January 2009|newspaper=The Guardian|first=Deborah|last=Summers}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 January 2009, in a subsequent blog entry on the ''Daily Telegraph's'' blogsite, Jones was described as \"the walking personification of the spirit of big business at its corporatist worst\".<ref>Martin, Iain [https://web.archive.org/web/20100429174335/http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/news/iainmartin/8117867/Fire_Digby_Jones \"Fire Digby Jones\"] ''Daily Telegraph'' blog site, 16 January 2009</ref>\n\nOn 20 September 2013, he spoke at the [[UK Independence Party]] conference in London as a guest speaker, addressing the conference on business and economic matters.\n\nOn 29 September 2014, Jones introduced the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[George Osborne]], before his keynote speech at the Conservative Party conference in Birmingham. He said that Osborne \"deserves a personal pat on the back\" for having \"stuck to your guns and did what was right for our country.\" In response to any rumour regarding a possible defection, he also confirmed \"I don't do party politics\" and \"business is my constituency.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/11127382/Conservative-Party-Conference-2014-live.html|title=Conservative Party Conference 2014: live|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=29 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Other posts==\nJones is a Corporate Ambassador for the [[Cancer Research UK]] Corporate Ambassadors. He is President of the [[Diversity Works]] initiative \u2013 a programme led by the disability organisation [[Scope (charity)|Scope]], a Diamond Ambassador for [[Mencap]]'s WorkRight initiative, designed to spread the message of equality for disabled people, a Vice-President of [[Birmingham Hospice]], and a Patron of [[Lifecycle UK]], Ladies Fighting Breast Cancer and Get A-Head, the cancer charity fighting head and neck diseases. He is an active supporter of Ovarian Cancer Action, the Royal Navy's Royal Marine Charity, the Royal Shakespeare Company, the City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra. He is the Patron of the Thomas Edington Scholarship of the University of Western Australia in Perth.\n\nHe is also a Vice-President of the [[Friends of the British Library]], a charity which provides funding support to the [[British Library]].<ref name=\"ar0607\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bl.uk/supportus/pdf/friendsannrep0607.pdf |title=Friends of the British Library Annual Report 2006/07 |accessdate=7 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100415020637/http://www.bl.uk/supportus/pdf/friendsannrep0607.pdf |archivedate=15 April 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nJones is a Vice-Patron of the [[National Museum of the Royal Navy]]. The National Museum through its six museums tell the stories and preserves the rich heritage of all aspects of the Royal Navy.\n\nHe was a non-executive director of [[Leicester Tigers]].<ref>[http://www.guinnesspremiership.com/news/2945.php Sir Digby Jones appointed to Tigers Board] Guinness Premiership, 5 October 2005</ref> He is a Vice-President of [[The Birmingham Civic Society]] and was President of the Speakers Trust and their Speaker of the Year in 2008.\n\nIn November 2006, Jones was appointed \"Business Adviser\" to [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|the Duke of York]], receiving \u00a31,000 a month from the royal payroll for working one day a month. This position ended upon his appointment as a Minister in July 2007.\n\nJones is \u201cChairman of the Advisory Board of X-Force, the Social Enterprise helping Veterans into self-employment\u201d.\n\nJones is also \"Adjunct Professor at the University of Western Australia.\"\n\n==Fellowships and doctorates==\n\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=June 2017}}\n\nJones is a Fellow of [[University College London]] (2004); an Honorary Fellow of [[Cardiff University]] (2004); and an Honorary Doctor of the [[Birmingham City University|University of Central England]] (2002), the [[University of Birmingham]] (2002), the [[University of Manchester Institute of Science and Technology]] (2003), the [[University of Hertfordshire]] (2004), [[Middlesex University]] (2005), [[Sheffield Hallam University]] (2005), [[Aston University]] (2006), the [[University of Hull]] (2006), [[Queen's University, Belfast]] (2006), [[Warwick University]] (2006), [[Bradford University]] (2006), [[University of West London|Thames Valley University]] (2006), [[Wolverhampton University]] (2006), the [[University of Nottingham]], [[Loughborough University]] (2007) and Honorary Fellow of [[Cardiff Metropolitan University]] (2013).\n\n==View on unions==\nJones has said of trades unions:\n{{quote|They are in danger of withering on the vine of irrelevance. They are backward looking and not on today's agenda.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|first=Larry|last=Elliott|author2=|title=Sir Digby rides off with all guns blazing|date=26 June 2006|publisher=|url=https://www.theguardian.com/euro/story/0,,1805980,00.html|work=[[The Guardian]]|pages=|accessdate=25 July 2007}}</ref>}}\nand:\n{{quote|The trade unions put their members first and not the country. Labour is always in thrall to the [[trade unions|unions]]. People keep banging on about [[cash for peerages]], but the unions have bunged money to the government for years.<ref name=\"Guardian\" />}}\n\n==Media appearances==\nJones was the guest on [[BBC Radio]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'', broadcast on 21 May 2006. He won BBC One's ''[[Celebrity Mastermind]]'' with a 9-point margin finishing on 33 points on 5 January 2011. Jones nominated Winston Churchill on BBC Radio 4 Great Lives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00tpsvk|title=Winston Churchill, Series 22, Great Lives - BBC Radio 4|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nHe presented the [[BBC Two]] programme ''The New Troubleshooter'' where he \"helps businesses realise their potential, ruffling feathers and bruising egos along the way as he gets stuck in and delivers his analysis and advice\", taking over the mantle of [[John Harvey-Jones]] who presented the original series ''[[Troubleshooter (TV series)|Troubleshooter]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=BBC Two \u2013 Digby Jones: The New Troubleshooter|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b040tmm9|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014 he presented a programme on [[BBC Radio 4]], ''The Business Covenant''.\n\n==Books==\nIn 2011 Jones published his first book ''Fixing Britain: The Business of Reshaping Our Nation'' (with publisher Wiley) which was shortlisted for the 2012 CMI Management Book of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yearbook.managers.org.uk/|title=CMI Management Book of the Year \u2013 Celebrating excellence in all areas of Management and Leadership writing|work=Management Book of the Year|accessdate=15 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 ''Fixing Business: Making Profitable Business Work for the Good of All'', was published in April 2017, also with Wiley.\n\n==Personal life==\nJones is a supporter of [[Leicester Tigers]] (officially Leicester Football Club), [[Aston Villa FC]]<ref>[http://www.birminghampost.net/news/west-midlands-news/2010/05/14/david-cameron-has-been-aston-villa-fan-since-a-teenager-97319-26442362/ David Cameron has been Aston Villa fan since a teenager] Birmingham Post, 14 May 2010</ref> and a member of the [[Reform Club]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070926224644/http://www.cbi.org.uk/pdf/annualreport2007.pdf CBI annual report & accounts, 2007]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/lord_jones_of_birmingham Lord Jones of Birmingham] on TheyWorkForYou.com\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bus}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Adair Turner]]|title=Director of the [[Confederation of British Industry]]|years=2000\u20132006|after=[[Richard Lambert]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Ian McCartney]]|title=[[Minister of State for Trade]]|years=2007\u20132008|after=[[Gareth Thomas (English politician)|Gareth Thomas]]}}\n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Baron West of Spithead|The Lord West of Spithead]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom|Gentlemen]]'''<br />''Baron Jones of Birmingham'' '''}}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Baron Darzi of Denham|The Lord Darzi of Denham]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones Of Birmingham, Digby Jones, Baron}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English lawyers]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers]]\n[[Category:English businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College London]]\n[[Category:Commissioners for Racial Equality]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bromsgrove School]]\n[[Category:People from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:British business writers]]\n[[Category:Freemen of the City of London]]\n[[Category:British Eurosceptics]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's, 1995-1998 \u2192 1995\u20131998", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digby_Jones,_Baron_Jones_of_Birmingham"}
{"title_page": "Michael Jay, Baron Jay of Ewelme", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name = The Lord Jay of Ewelme\n|honorific-suffix = [[Order of St Michael and St George|GCMG]]\n|image = official portrait of Lord Jay of Ewelme crop 2.jpg\n|imagesize =\n|smallimage =\n|caption =\n|office1      = [[Permanent Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs|Permanent Under Secretary of State of the Foreign and Commonwealth Office]]\n|term_start1  = 2002\n|term_end1    = 2006\n|predecessor1 = [[Sir John Kerr]]\n|successor1   = [[Sir Peter Ricketts]]\n|office2      = Chairman of the [[House of Lords Appointments Commission]]\n|term_start2  = 23 July 2008\n|term_end2    = 19 July 2013\n|predecessor2 = [[Dennis Stevenson, Baron Stevenson of Coddenham|The Lord Stevenson]]\n|successor2   = [[Ajay Kakkar, Baron Kakkar|The Lord Kakkar]]\n|office3      = [[Members of the House of Lords|Member]] of the [[House of Lords]]<br/><small>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]</small>\n|term_start3  = 18 September 2006<br/><small>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]</small>\n|term_end3    =\n|birthname = Michael Hastings Jay\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1946|06|19}}\n|birth_place = \n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|nationality = British\n|restingplace =\n|restingplacecoordinates =\n|partner =\n|profession =\n}}\n'''Michael Hastings Jay, Baron Jay of Ewelme''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCMG}} (born 19 June 1946) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] politician and former [[HM Diplomatic Service|diplomat]]. He sits as a [[Crossbench]] member of the [[House of Lords]], and previously served as Ambassador to France and [[Permanent Under Secretary]] at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]].\n\n==Education==\nJay was born in [[Hampshire]] and educated at [[Winchester College]], [[Magdalen College, Oxford]] (at which he read [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]]<ref>Transcript of interview with Baron Jay</ref>), of which he is an honorary fellow, and the University of London's [[School of Oriental and African Studies]] (SOAS). He served as a [[Voluntary Service Overseas|VSO]] teacher in [[Zambia]].\n\n==Diplomatic career==\nJay joined the [[Department for International Development|Ministry of Overseas Development]] in 1969, serving in [[London]], [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] (at the [[World Bank Group|World Bank]]) in 1973 and as [[Diplomatic rank|First Secretary (Development)]] at the [[British High Commission, New Delhi]], in 1978. He transferred to the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] in 1981, serving as [[Private Secretary]] to the [[Permanent Under-Secretary of State]]. As [[Minister-counselor|Counsellor]] he served in the European Secretariat of the [[Cabinet Office]] from 1985 to 1987.<ref>The Diplomatic Service List 1989, p. 219), [[HMSO]], {{ISBN|0-11-591707-1}}</ref> He was posted as Counsellor in the [[Paris]] Embassy from 1987 to 1990, returning to the FCO as Director for European Affairs until 1994. He was appointed Director General for European and Economic Affairs 1994\u201396, following which he became a Senior Associate Member of [[St Antony's College, Oxford]].\n\nFrom July 1996 to September 2001 he was [[List of ambassadors from the United Kingdom to France|British Ambassador to France]]. During this tenure, he was the first British spokesman to speak publicly on the death of [[Diana, Princess of Wales]]. In July 2001, he was appointed [[Permanent Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs]] and thus Head of the [[Diplomatic Service]], a post he took up on 14 January 2002.\n\nIn 2005 and 2006, Jay served as the Prime Minister's Personal Representative ([[Sherpa (G8)|Sherpa]]) for the G8 summits at Gleneagles and St Petersburg in addition to his PUS duties.\n\nHe was appointed a Companion of the [[Order of St Michael & St George]] in the [[1992 Birthday Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=52952 |date=13 June 1992 |page=3 |supp=y}}</ref> promoted to Knight Commander in the [[1997 New Year Honours]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54625 |date=31 December 1996 |page=3 |supp=y}}</ref> and made a Knight Grand Cross in the [[2006 Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58014 |date=17 June 2006 |page=3 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n==Post retirement==\nUpon his retirement from [[Her Majesty's Diplomatic Service|HM's Diplomatic Service]] on 27 July 2006, he was recommended for a [[Life peer]]age, and this was [[London Gazette|gazetted]] as '''Baron Jay of Ewelme''', of [[Ewelme]] in the [[Oxfordshire|County of Oxfordshire]], on 18 September 2006.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58105 |date=22 September 2006 |page=12975}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200506/minutes/061012/ldminute.htm |title=Announcement of Michael Jay's introduction at the House of Lords |date=12 October 2006}}</ref>\n\nLord Jay was the Chair of [[Merlin (charity)|Merlin]], the British health and medical aid agency, from 2007 until 2013. He has been a non-executive director of Associated British Foods (2006-),Credit Agricole (2007-2011), EDF (2009-), Candover PLC (2008-)and Valeo SA (2007-). He is a Trustee of the Thomson Reuters Founders share company (2013-), and Chairman of the Advisory Council of the British Library (2011 -). He was Chairman of the House of Lords Appointments Commission from 2008 until 2013). he has served on sub-committees C, E and F of the House of Lords Select Committee on European Union affairs.\n\n==Family==\nJay married Sylvia Mylroie in 1975. In 2005 Lady Jay was appointed Vice-Chairman of [[L'Oreal]] UK & Ireland, then Chairman from 2011\u20132013. She has been a non-executive director on the board of [[Alcatel-Lucent]], and is non-executive director of St-Gobain, Lazard and Casino Group. She is Chairman of the [[Pilgrim Trust]] and has been a trustee of the [[Prison Reform Trust]] and Entente Cordiale Scholarship Scheme. In 2019 she was appointed as High Sheriff of Oxfordshire.\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = \n|image size = \n|notes = \n|year_adopted = 2007\n|coronet = [[Coronet|Coronet of a Baron]]\n|escutcheon = Per saltire Argent and Sable two Clarions in pale each ensigned with an Ancient Crown Sable and two Clarions in fess Argent each ensigned by an Ancient Crown Or\n|supporters = On either side a Manx Shearwater contourny supporting with the wings addorsed and inverted proper beaked and legged Or in the beak a Trefoil slipped also Or\n|crest = Upon a Helm with a Wreath Argent Or and Sable an Otter sejant erect Sable holding with both forepaws and blowing a Trumpet Or\n|badge = An Otter's Face Sable anciently crowned Or\n|motto = '''IN HOMINES BENEVOLENTIA'''\n|symbolism = The grantee's career in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office is reflected in the pelagic Manx Shearwaters. The latter's short legs prevent them from supporting the shield with a foot in a satisfactory manner. Accordingly, they have been shown contourny, thus enabling them to support with the wings. The natural black and white of the shearwater is reflected in the Arms which are divided to represent North, South, East, and West. Crown service is reflected in the coronets which ensign clarions which, in turn, suggest the initial J. General proclamation and industry is found with the trumpet-blowing otter in the crest. An industrious otter in the Crown Service is an idea repeated in the Badge.\n}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060925230945/http://www.number-10.gov.uk/output/Page9890.asp Announcement of life peerage]\n\n==Offices held==\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{succession box\n  | title = [[List of ambassadors from the United Kingdom to France|British Ambassador to France]]\n  | years = 1996\u20132001\n  | before = [[Christopher Mallaby|Sir Christopher Mallaby]]\n  | after = [[John Holmes (British diplomat)|Sir John Holmes]]\n}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box\n  | title = Director-General, European and Economic Affairs of the <br /> [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]]\n  | years = 1994\u20131996\n  | before = Unknown\n  | after = Unknown\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title = [[Permanent Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs|Permanent Secretary]] of the <br /> [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]]\n  | years = 2002\u20132006\n  | before = [[John Kerr, Baron Kerr of Kinlochard|Sir John Kerr]]\n  | after = [[Peter Ricketts|Sir Peter Ricketts]]\n}}\n{{s-other}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dennis Stevenson, Baron Stevenson of Coddenham|The Lord Stevenson of Coddenham]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairman of the [[House of Lords Appointments Commission]]|years=2008\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ajay Kakkar, Baron Kakkar|The Lord Kakkar]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jay, Michael}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Winchester College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Magdalen College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Magdalen College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of SOAS University of London]]\n[[Category:Crossbench life peers|Jay of Ewelme, Michael Jay, Baron]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the United Kingdom to France]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George|Jay of Ewelme, Michael Jay, Baron]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic peers|Jay of Ewelme, Michael Jay, Baron]]\n[[Category:Permanent Under-Secretaries of State for Foreign Affairs]]\n[[Category:Civil servants in the Ministry of Overseas Development]]\n[[Category:Civil servants in the Cabinet Office]]\n[[Category:Members of HM Diplomatic Service]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name = The Lord Jay of Ewelme\n|honorific-suffix = [[Order of St Michael and St George|GCMG]]\n|image = official portrait of Lord Jay of Ewelme crop 2.jpg\n|imagesize =\n|smallimage =\n|caption =\n|office1      = [[Permanent Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs|Permanent Under Secretary of State of the Foreign and Commonwealth Office]]\n|term_start1  = 2002\n|term_end1    = 2006\n|predecessor1 = [[Sir John Kerr]]\n|successor1   = [[Sir Peter Ricketts]]\n|office2      = Chairman of the [[House of Lords Appointments Commission]]\n|term_start2  = 23 July 2008\n|term_end2    = 19 July 2013\n|predecessor2 = [[Dennis Stevenson, Baron Stevenson of Coddenham|The Lord Stevenson]]\n|successor2   = [[Ajay Kakkar, Baron Kakkar|The Lord Kakkar]]\n|office3      = [[Members of the House of Lords|Member]] of the [[House of Lords]]<br/><small>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]</small>\n|term_start3  = 18 September 2006<br/><small>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]</small>\n|term_end3    =\n|birthname = Michael Hastings Jay\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1946|06|19}}\n|birth_place = \n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|nationality = British\n|restingplace =\n|restingplacecoordinates =\n|partner =\n|profession =\n}}\n'''Michael Hastings Jay, Baron Jay of Ewelme''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCMG}} (born 19 June 1946) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] politician and former [[HM Diplomatic Service|diplomat]]. He sits as a [[Crossbench]] member of the [[House of Lords]], and previously served as Ambassador to France and [[Permanent Under Secretary]] at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]].\n\n==Education==\nJay was born in [[Hampshire]] and educated at [[Winchester College]], [[Magdalen College, Oxford]] (at which he read [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]]<ref>Transcript of interview with Baron Jay</ref>), of which he is an honorary fellow, and the University of London's [[School of Oriental and African Studies]] (SOAS). He served as a [[Voluntary Service Overseas|VSO]] teacher in [[Zambia]].\n\n==Diplomatic career==\nJay joined the [[Department for International Development|Ministry of Overseas Development]] in 1969, serving in [[London]], [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]] (at the [[World Bank Group|World Bank]]) in 1973 and as [[Diplomatic rank|First Secretary (Development)]] at the [[British High Commission, New Delhi]], in 1978. He transferred to the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] in 1981, serving as [[Private Secretary]] to the [[Permanent Under-Secretary of State]]. As [[Minister-counselor|Counsellor]] he served in the European Secretariat of the [[Cabinet Office]] from 1985 to 1987.<ref>The Diplomatic Service List 1989, p. 219), [[HMSO]], {{ISBN|0-11-591707-1}}</ref> He was posted as Counsellor in the [[Paris]] Embassy from 1987 to 1990, returning to the FCO as Director for European Affairs until 1994. He was appointed Director General for European and Economic Affairs 1994-96, following which he became a Senior Associate Member of [[St Antony's College, Oxford]].\n\nFrom July 1996 to September 2001 he was [[List of ambassadors from the United Kingdom to France|British Ambassador to France]]. During this tenure, he was the first British spokesman to speak publicly on the death of [[Diana, Princess of Wales]]. In July 2001, he was appointed [[Permanent Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs]] and thus Head of the [[Diplomatic Service]], a post he took up on 14 January 2002.\n\nIn 2005 and 2006, Jay served as the Prime Minister's Personal Representative ([[Sherpa (G8)|Sherpa]]) for the G8 summits at Gleneagles and St Petersburg in addition to his PUS duties.\n\nHe was appointed a Companion of the [[Order of St Michael & St George]] in the [[1992 Birthday Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=52952 |date=13 June 1992 |page=3 |supp=y}}</ref> promoted to Knight Commander in the [[1997 New Year Honours]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54625 |date=31 December 1996 |page=3 |supp=y}}</ref> and made a Knight Grand Cross in the [[2006 Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58014 |date=17 June 2006 |page=3 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n==Post retirement==\nUpon his retirement from [[Her Majesty's Diplomatic Service|HM's Diplomatic Service]] on 27 July 2006, he was recommended for a [[Life peer]]age, and this was [[London Gazette|gazetted]] as '''Baron Jay of Ewelme''', of [[Ewelme]] in the [[Oxfordshire|County of Oxfordshire]], on 18 September 2006.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=58105 |date=22 September 2006 |page=12975}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200506/minutes/061012/ldminute.htm |title=Announcement of Michael Jay's introduction at the House of Lords |date=12 October 2006}}</ref>\n\nLord Jay was the Chair of [[Merlin (charity)|Merlin]], the British health and medical aid agency, from 2007 until 2013. He has been a non-executive director of Associated British Foods (2006-),Credit Agricole (2007-2011), EDF (2009-), Candover PLC (2008-)and Valeo SA (2007-). He is a Trustee of the Thomson Reuters Founders share company (2013-), and Chairman of the Advisory Council of the British Library (2011 -). He was Chairman of the House of Lords Appointments Commission from 2008 until 2013). he has served on sub-committees C, E and F of the House of Lords Select Committee on European Union affairs.\n\n==Family==\nJay married Sylvia Mylroie in 1975. In 2005 Lady Jay was appointed Vice-Chairman of [[L'Oreal]] UK & Ireland, then Chairman from 2011-2013. She has been a non-executive director on the board of [[Alcatel-Lucent]], and is non-executive director of St-Gobain, Lazard and Casino Group. She is Chairman of the [[Pilgrim Trust]] and has been a trustee of the [[Prison Reform Trust]] and Entente Cordiale Scholarship Scheme. In 2019 she was appointed as High Sheriff of Oxfordshire.\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = \n|image size = \n|notes = \n|year_adopted = 2007\n|coronet = [[Coronet|Coronet of a Baron]]\n|escutcheon = Per saltire Argent and Sable two Clarions in pale each ensigned with an Ancient Crown Sable and two Clarions in fess Argent each ensigned by an Ancient Crown Or\n|supporters = On either side a Manx Shearwater contourny supporting with the wings addorsed and inverted proper beaked and legged Or in the beak a Trefoil slipped also Or\n|crest = Upon a Helm with a Wreath Argent Or and Sable an Otter sejant erect Sable holding with both forepaws and blowing a Trumpet Or\n|badge = An Otter's Face Sable anciently crowned Or\n|motto = '''IN HOMINES BENEVOLENTIA'''\n|symbolism = The grantee's career in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office is reflected in the pelagic Manx Shearwaters. The latter's short legs prevent them from supporting the shield with a foot in a satisfactory manner. Accordingly, they have been shown contourny, thus enabling them to support with the wings. The natural black and white of the shearwater is reflected in the Arms which are divided to represent North, South, East, and West. Crown service is reflected in the coronets which ensign clarions which, in turn, suggest the initial J. General proclamation and industry is found with the trumpet-blowing otter in the crest. An industrious otter in the Crown Service is an idea repeated in the Badge.\n}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060925230945/http://www.number-10.gov.uk/output/Page9890.asp Announcement of life peerage]\n\n==Offices held==\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{succession box\n  | title = [[List of ambassadors from the United Kingdom to France|British Ambassador to France]]\n  | years = 1996\u20132001\n  | before = [[Christopher Mallaby|Sir Christopher Mallaby]]\n  | after = [[John Holmes (British diplomat)|Sir John Holmes]]\n}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box\n  | title = Director-General, European and Economic Affairs of the <br /> [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]]\n  | years = 1994\u20131996\n  | before = Unknown\n  | after = Unknown\n}}\n{{succession box\n  | title = [[Permanent Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs|Permanent Secretary]] of the <br /> [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]]\n  | years = 2002\u20132006\n  | before = [[John Kerr, Baron Kerr of Kinlochard|Sir John Kerr]]\n  | after = [[Peter Ricketts|Sir Peter Ricketts]]\n}}\n{{s-other}}\n{{s-bef|befo