{"title_page": "Hugh Foot, Baron Caradon", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Caradon\n|honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCMG|KCVO|OBE|PC}}\n|image            = Sir Hugh Foot 1951.jpg\n|caption          = \n|office           = [[Permanent Representative of the United Kingdom to the United Nations|British Permanent Representative to the United Nations]]\n|monarch          = [[Elizabeth II]]\n|term_start       = 16 October 1964\n|term_end         = 19 June 1970\n|predecessor      = [[Patrick Dean|Sir Patrick Dean]]\n|successor        = [[Colin Crowe|Sir Colin Crowe]]\n|office1          = [[Minister of State for Foreign Affairs (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]]<br><small>[[Minister of State for Foreign Affairs (United Kingdom)|Foreign Affairs]] (1964\u20131968)</small>\n|primeminister1   = [[Harold Wilson]]\n|term_start1      = 16 October 1964\n|term_end1        = 19 June 1970\n|predecessor1     = [[Henry Scrymgeour-Wedderburn, 11th Earl of Dundee|The Earl of Dundee]]<br>[[Peter Thomas, Baron Thomas of Gwydir|Peter Thomas]]\n|successor1       = [[Joseph Godber]]<br>[[Richard Wood, Baron Holderness|Richard Wood]]\n| office3 = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start3 = 27 October 1964\n| term_end3 = 5 September 1990<br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n| office4          = [[List of colonial governors and administrators of British Cyprus|Governor of Cyprus]]\n| monarch4         = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister4   = [[Harold Macmillan]]\n| term_start4      = 3 December 1957\n| term_end4        = 16 August 1960\n| predecessor4     = [[John Harding, 1st Baron Harding of Petherton|Sir John Harding]]\n| successor4       = ''Cyprus gained independence''\n| office5          = [[List of governors of Jamaica|Governor of Jamaica]]\n| monarch5         = [[George VI]]<br>[[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister5   = [[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Churchill]]<br>[[Anthony Eden|Sir Anthony Eden]]<br>[[Harold Macmillan]]\n| term_start5      = 7 April 1951\n| term_end5        = 18 November 1957\n| predecessor5     = [[John Huggins (governor)|Sir John Huggins]]\n| successor5       = [[Kenneth Blackburne|Sir Kenneth Blackburne]]\n|birth_date       = {{birth date|1907|10|8|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Southampton]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|1990|9|5|1907|10|8|df=yes}}\n|death_place      = \n|alma_mater       = [[St John's College, Cambridge]]\n}}\n\n'''Hugh Mackintosh Foot, Baron Caradon''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCMG|KCVO|OBE|PC}} (8 October 1907 \u2013 5 September 1990) was a British colonial administrator and diplomat who presided over moves to [[Independence]] in various colonies and was UK representative to the [[United Nations]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nHugh Mackintosh Foot was born in [[Plymouth]] in [[Devon]], England, on 8 October 1907. He was educated at [[Leighton Park School]] in [[Reading, Berkshire]], and went on to study at [[St John's College, Cambridge|St John's College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], where he graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in 1929.<ref name=thepeerage>{{cite web |publisher=The Peerage |title=Hugh Mackintosh Foot, Baron Caradon |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p19110.htm#i191099 |accessdate=7 January 2017}}</ref> He was President of the [[Cambridge Union]] and also of the [[Cambridge University Liberal Club]]. His three politically active brothers, [[Dingle Foot|Dingle]], [[John Foot, Baron Foot|John]] and [[Michael Foot|Michael]], were all educated at [[University of Oxford|Oxford]] and all became Presidents of the [[Oxford Union]].\n\n==Career==\nHugh Foot's career in the diplomatic service was both long and distinguished. In [[Mandatory Palestine]], he served as the assistant district commissioner for the [[Nablus]] region.<ref>{{cite book|title=A Lifetime in Jerusalem: The Memoirs of the Second Viscount Samuel|author=[[Edwin Samuel, 2nd Viscount Samuel|Samuel, E.H.]]|year=1970|page=131|publisher=Transaction Publishers}}</ref> During the [[World War II|Second World War]] he was appointed as British Military Administrator of [[Cyrenaica]], and served as Colonial Secretary of [[British Cyprus|Cyprus]] from 1943 to 1945. After the War, he served as Colonial Secretary of [[Jamaica]], 1945\u201347, Chief Secretary for [[Nigeria]], 1947\u201350 and was appointed to be the Captain-General and Governor-in-Chief of Jamaica in 1951,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=39166 |date=9 March 1951 |page=1226}}</ref> a post he held until 1957.\n\nHe returned to Cyprus as the last colonial Governor and Commander in Chief in 1957<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=41246 |date=6 December 1957 |page=7115}}</ref> until 1960, when Cyprus [[London-Z\u00fcrich Agreements|gained independence]]. In 1961, he became British Ambassador to the United Nations Trusteeship Council. After the Labour Party won the [[1964 United Kingdom general election|1964 general election]], Foot became Minister of State for Foreign Affairs and [[Permanent Representatives from the United Kingdom to the United Nations|British Ambassador to the United Nations]] from 1964 to 1970. During his tenure as Permanent Representative, he was sworn of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] in the [[1968 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=44484 |date=29 December 1967 |page=1 |supp=y}}</ref> After his retirement, he became a Visiting Fellow at [[Harvard University]] and [[Princeton University]].\n\nIn 1964 Foot was granted a [[life peer|life]] [[Peerage of the United Kingdom|peerage]] as '''Baron Caradon''', of [[St Cleer]] in the County of [[Cornwall]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=43475 |date=27 October 1964 |page=9125}}</ref> the title referring to [[Caradon Hill]] on [[Bodmin Moor]], not far from [[Trematon Castle]], which was his country home. He jokingly claimed to be glad to be divested of the surname \"Foot\", which he considered a standing invitation to wags, as he liked to illustrate by recalling a telegram his father received on his election to parliament: \"Foot, congratulations on your feat!\" Foot was an active [[freemason]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=\n|title= Power of the Masons - Myth of Menace?\n|date= 13 July 1986\n|work= Sunday People\n|page=  \n}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and arms==\nFoot was appointed Officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[1939 New Year Honours]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=34585 |date=30 December 1938 |page=18 |supp=y}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=15559 |date=6 January 1939 |page=26 |city=e}}</ref> and elevated Companion of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] (CMG) in the [[1946 Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=37598 |date=4 June 1946 |page=2761 |supp=y}}</ref> He was elevated Knight Commander of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] (KCMG) in the [[1951 New Year Honours]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=39104 |date=29 December 1950 |page=4 |supp=y}}</ref> and was appointed Knight Commander of the [[Royal Victorian Order]] (KCVO) on 27 November 1953.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=40043 |date=15 December 1953 |page=6816}}</ref> In the [[1957 Birthday Honours]], he was elevated a Knight Grand Cross of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] (GCMG).<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=41089 |date=4 June 1957 |page=3370 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Caradon Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|crest = Perching on a Tower Sable supported by two Lions' Gambs erect Gules a Cornish Chough proper\n|escutcheon = Or on a Chevron engrailed Sable between three Lions' Gambs erect and erased Gules three Wheels Or\n|supporters = On either side an African Lion proper charged on the shoulder with the Head of a Trident Or within a Wreath a two Olive Branches leaved and the Stems crossed in saltire Argent, the whole on a Compartment of Rock in the middle thereof a Pit proper\n|motto = Pro lege et libertate (For law and liberty) <ref>http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/lp1958%20c.htm</ref>}}\n\n==Family==\nHe was one of the four sons of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] [[Member of Parliament]] [[Isaac Foot]], his three brothers being the politician Sir [[Dingle Foot]], the life peer [[John Foot, Baron Foot|Lord Foot]], and the journalist and [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] leader [[Michael Foot]]. \"We were proud to be nonconformists and Roundheads\", Caradon once wrote of his family: \"[[Oliver Cromwell]] was our hero and [[John Milton]] our poet.\"\n\nFoot married Florence Sylvia Tod in 1936. She predeceased him in 1985. They had three sons and a daughter together:<ref name=thepeerage/>\n\n* [[The Honourable|Hon.]] [[Paul Foot (journalist)|Paul Mackintosh Foot]] (8 November 1937 \u2013 18 July 2004), a journalist.\n* Hon. [[Sarah Foot (journalist)|Sarah Dingle Foot]] (24 September 1939 \u2013 28 February 2015), also a journalist.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/11454956/Sarah-Foot-writer-obituary.html \"Sarah Foot, writer - obituary\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 6 March 2015.</ref>\n* Hon. [[Oliver Foot|Oliver Isaac Foot]] (19 September 1946 \u2013 6 February 2008), a charity worker who led [[Project Orbis International]].<ref>Geoffrey Holland [https://www.theguardian.com/science/2008/feb/12/medicalresearch.voluntarysector \"Oliver Foot\"] (obituary), ''The Guardian'', 12 February 2008.</ref>\n* Hon. Benjamin Arthur Foot (born 19 August 1949)\n\nFoot died in Plymouth, aged 82, on 5 September 1990. He was survived by his four children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Works==\n* Lord Caradon, [http://dmr.bsu.edu/cdm4/document.php?CISOROOT=/ConspectusH&CISOPTR=1486&REC=1 \"The Obligation of Optimism\"], ''Conspectus of History'' 1.8 (1982): 1\u20139.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n* [http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9000803/Hugh-Foot Entry] in ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box\n| before=Sir [[John Huggins (governor)|John Huggins]]\n| title=[[Governor of Jamaica]] | years=1951\u20131957\n| after=Sir [[Kenneth Blackburne]]\n}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Harding, 1st Baron Harding of Petherton|John Harding]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of Cyprus]] | years=1957\u20131960}}\n{{s-non|reason=Cyprus became independent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caradon, Hugh Foot, Baron}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:Permanent Representatives of the United Kingdom to the United Nations]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Cambridge Union]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic peers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:British Methodists]]\n[[Category:Cornish Methodists]]\n[[Category:Colonial Administrative Service officers]]\n[[Category:Governors of Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Leighton Park School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:Princeton University faculty]]\n[[Category:Governors of British Cyprus]]\n[[Category:20th-century Methodists]]\n[[Category:British people of the Cyprus Emergency]]\n[[Category:Foot family|Hugh]]\n[[Category:Colonial Secretaries of Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Chief Secretaries of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Colonial Secretaries of Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Freemasons of the United Grand Lodge of England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Caradon\n|honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCMG|KCVO|OBE|PC}}\n|image            = Sir Hugh Foot 1951.jpg\n|caption          = \n|office           = [[Permanent Representative of the United Kingdom to the United Nations|British Permanent Representative to the United Nations]]\n|monarch          = [[Elizabeth II]]\n|term_start       = 16 October 1964\n|term_end         = 19 June 1970\n|predecessor      = [[Patrick Dean|Sir Patrick Dean]]\n|successor        = [[Colin Crowe|Sir Colin Crowe]]\n|office1          = [[Minister of State for Foreign Affairs (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]]<br><small>[[Minister of State for Foreign Affairs (United Kingdom)|Foreign Affairs]] (1964\u20131968)</small>\n|primeminister1   = [[Harold Wilson]]\n|term_start1      = 16 October 1964\n|term_end1        = 19 June 1970\n|predecessor1     = [[Henry Scrymgeour-Wedderburn, 11th Earl of Dundee|The Earl of Dundee]]<br>[[Peter Thomas, Baron Thomas of Gwydir|Peter Thomas]]\n|successor1       = [[Joseph Godber]]<br>[[Richard Wood, Baron Holderness|Richard Wood]]\n| office3 = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br>[[Lord Temporal]]\n| term_start3 = 27 October 1964\n| term_end3 = 5 September 1990<br/>[[Life peer|Life Peerage]]\n| office4          = [[List of colonial governors and administrators of British Cyprus|Governor of Cyprus]]\n| monarch4         = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister4   = [[Harold Macmillan]]\n| term_start4      = 3 December 1957\n| term_end4        = 16 August 1960\n| predecessor4     = [[John Harding, 1st Baron Harding of Petherton|Sir John Harding]]\n| successor4       = ''Cyprus gained independence''\n| office5          = [[List of governors of Jamaica|Governor of Jamaica]]\n| monarch5         = [[George VI]]<br>[[Elizabeth II]]\n| primeminister5   = [[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Churchill]]<br>[[Anthony Eden|Sir Anthony Eden]]<br>[[Harold Macmillan]]\n| term_start5      = 7 April 1951\n| term_end5        = 18 November 1957\n| predecessor5     = [[John Huggins (governor)|Sir John Huggins]]\n| successor5       = [[Kenneth Blackburne|Sir Kenneth Blackburne]]\n|birth_date       = {{birth date|1907|10|8|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Southampton]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|1990|9|5|1907|10|8|df=yes}}\n|death_place      = \n|alma_mater       = [[St John's College, Cambridge]]\n}}\n\n'''Hugh Mackintosh Foot, Baron Caradon''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCMG|KCVO|OBE|PC}} (8 October 1907 \u2013 5 September 1990) was a British colonial administrator and diplomat who presided over moves to [[Independence]] in various colonies and was UK representative to the [[United Nations]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nHugh Mackintosh Foot was born in [[Plymouth]] in [[Devon]], England, on 8 October 1907. He was educated at [[Leighton Park School]] in [[Reading, Berkshire]], and went on to study at [[St John's College, Cambridge|St John's College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], where he graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in 1929.<ref name=thepeerage>{{cite web |publisher=The Peerage |title=Hugh Mackintosh Foot, Baron Caradon |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p19110.htm#i191099 |accessdate=7 January 2017}}</ref> He was President of the [[Cambridge Union]] and also of the [[Cambridge University Liberal Club]]. His three politically active brothers, [[Dingle Foot|Dingle]], [[John Foot, Baron Foot|John]] and [[Michael Foot|Michael]], were all educated at [[University of Oxford|Oxford]] and all became Presidents of the [[Oxford Union]].\n\n==Career==\nHugh Foot's career in the diplomatic service was both long and distinguished. In [[Mandatory Palestine]], he served as the assistant district commissioner for the [[Nablus]] region.<ref>{{cite book|title=A Lifetime in Jerusalem: The Memoirs of the Second Viscount Samuel|author=[[Edwin Samuel, 2nd Viscount Samuel|Samuel, E.H.]]|year=1970|page=131|publisher=Transaction Publishers}}</ref> During the [[World War II|Second World War]] he was appointed as British Military Administrator of [[Cyrenaica]], and served as Colonial Secretary of [[British Cyprus|Cyprus]] from 1943 to 1945. After the War, he served as Colonial Secretary of [[Jamaica]], 1945\u201347, Chief Secretary for [[Nigeria]], 1947\u201350 and was appointed to be the Captain-General and Governor-in-Chief of Jamaica in 1951,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=39166 |date=9 March 1951 |page=1226}}</ref> a post he held until 1957.\n\nHe returned to Cyprus as the last colonial Governor and Commander in Chief in 1957<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=41246 |date=6 December 1957 |page=7115}}</ref> until 1960, when Cyprus [[London-Z\u00fcrich Agreements|gained independence]]. In 1961, he became British Ambassador to the United Nations Trusteeship Council. After the Labour Party won the [[1964 United Kingdom general election|1964 general election]], Foot became Minister of State for Foreign Affairs and [[Permanent Representatives from the United Kingdom to the United Nations|British Ambassador to the United Nations]] from 1964 to 1970. During his tenure as Permanent Representative, he was sworn of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] in the [[1968 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=44484 |date=29 December 1967 |page=1 |supp=y}}</ref> After his retirement, he became a Visiting Fellow at [[Harvard University]] and [[Princeton University]].\n\nIn 1964 Foot was granted a [[life peer|life]] [[Peerage of the United Kingdom|peerage]] as '''Baron Caradon''', of [[St Cleer]] in the County of [[Cornwall]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=43475 |date=27 October 1964 |page=9125}}</ref> the title referring to [[Caradon Hill]] on [[Bodmin Moor]], not far from [[Trematon Castle]], which was his country home. He jokingly claimed to be glad to be divested of the surname \"Foot\", which he considered a standing invitation to wags, as he liked to illustrate by recalling a telegram his father received on his election to parliament: \"Foot, congratulations on your feat!\" Foot was an active [[freemason]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=\n|title= Power of the Masons - Myth of Menace?\n|date= 13 July 1986\n|work= Sunday People\n|page=  \n}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and arms==\nFoot was appointed Officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[1939 New Year Honours]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=34585 |date=30 December 1938 |page=18 |supp=y}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=15559 |date=6 January 1939 |page=26 |city=e}}</ref> and elevated Companion of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] (CMG) in the [[1946 Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=37598 |date=4 June 1946 |page=2761 |supp=y}}</ref> He was elevated Knight Commander of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] (KCMG) in the [[1951 New Year Honours]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=39104 |date=29 December 1950 |page=4 |supp=y}}</ref> and was appointed Knight Commander of the [[Royal Victorian Order]] (KCVO) on 27 November 1953.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=40043 |date=15 December 1953 |page=6816}}</ref> In the [[1957 Birthday Honours]], he was elevated a Knight Grand Cross of the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] (GCMG).<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=41089 |date=4 June 1957 |page=3370 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Caradon Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|crest = Perching on a Tower Sable supported by two Lions' Gambs erect Gules a Cornish Chough proper\n|escutcheon = Or on a Chevron engrailed Sable between three Lions' Gambs erect and erased Gules three Wheels Or\n|supporters = On either side an African Lion proper charged on the shoulder with the Head of a Trident Or within a Wreath a two Olive Branches leaved and the Stems crossed in saltire Argent, the whole on a Compartment of Rock in the middle thereof a Pit proper\n|motto = Pro lege et libertate (For law and liberty) <ref>http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/lp1958%20c.htm</ref>}}\n\n==Family==\nHe was one of the four sons of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] [[Member of Parliament]] [[Isaac Foot]], his three brothers being the politician Sir [[Dingle Foot]], the life peer [[John Foot, Baron Foot|Lord Foot]], and the journalist and [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] leader [[Michael Foot]]. \"We were proud to be nonconformists and Roundheads\", Caradon once wrote of his family: \"[[Oliver Cromwell]] was our hero and [[John Milton]] our poet.\"\n\nFoot married Florence Sylvia Tod in 1936. She predeceased him in 1985. They had three sons and a daughter together:<ref name=thepeerage/>\n\n* [[The Honourable|Hon.]] [[Paul Foot (journalist)|Paul Mackintosh Foot]] (8 November 1937 \u2013 18 July 2004), a journalist.\n* Hon. [[Sarah Foot (journalist)|Sarah Dingle Foot]] (24 September 1939 \u2013 28 February 2015), also a journalist.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/11454956/Sarah-Foot-writer-obituary.html \"Sarah Foot, writer - obituary\"], ''The Daily Telegraph'', 6 March 2015.</ref>\n* Hon. [[Oliver Foot|Oliver Isaac Foot]] (19 September 1946 \u2013 6 February 2008), a charity worker who led [[Project Orbis International]].<ref>Geoffrey Holland [https://www.theguardian.com/science/2008/feb/12/medicalresearch.voluntarysector \"Oliver Foot\"] (obituary), ''The Guardian'', 12 February 2008.</ref>\n* Hon. Benjamin Arthur Foot (born 19 August 1949)\n\nFoot died in Plymouth, aged 82, on 5 September 1990. He was survived by his four children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Works==\n* Lord Caradon, [http://dmr.bsu.edu/cdm4/document.php?CISOROOT=/ConspectusH&CISOPTR=1486&REC=1 \"The Obligation of Optimism\"], ''Conspectus of History'' 1.8 (1982): 1-9.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n* [http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9000803/Hugh-Foot Entry] in ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]''\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box\n| before=Sir [[John Huggins (governor)|John Huggins]]\n| title=[[Governor of Jamaica]] | years=1951\u20131957\n| after=Sir [[Kenneth Blackburne]]\n}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Harding, 1st Baron Harding of Petherton|John Harding]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor of Cyprus]] | years=1957\u20131960}}\n{{s-non|reason=Cyprus became independent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caradon, Hugh Foot, Baron}}\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:Permanent Representatives of the United Kingdom to the United Nations]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Cambridge Union]]\n[[Category:Diplomatic peers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:British Methodists]]\n[[Category:Cornish Methodists]]\n[[Category:Colonial Administrative Service officers]]\n[[Category:Governors of Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Leighton Park School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:Princeton University faculty]]\n[[Category:Governors of British Cyprus]]\n[[Category:20th-century Methodists]]\n[[Category:British people of the Cyprus Emergency]]\n[[Category:Foot family|Hugh]]\n[[Category:Colonial Secretaries of Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Chief Secretaries of Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Colonial Secretaries of Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Freemasons of the United Grand Lodge of England]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorks:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1-9 \u2192 1\u20139", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugh_Foot,_Baron_Caradon"}
